[Amit Varma]: ways, maybe, you know, parts of the Indian state are a little bit like that. Let's let's

02:44:35.680 --> 02:44:41.800
[Amit Varma]: sort of talk about federalism. Now, in a sense, the Indian state was designed to be a federal

02:44:41.800 --> 02:44:46.040
[Amit Varma]: state, a union of states, as Rahul Gandhi put it in Parliament recently, and as our

02:44:46.040 --> 02:44:50.520
[Amit Varma]: constitution begins. So we were designed to be federal, yet we were designed to be incredibly

02:44:50.520 --> 02:44:57.400
[Amit Varma]: centralized at the same time. So I'd like you to sort of disentangle this by first speaking

02:44:57.400 --> 02:45:01.880
[Amit Varma]: about the aspect in which we were designed to be federal, like how are we federal? What

02:45:01.880 --> 02:45:06.760
[Amit Varma]: does federalism mean? And how you know, you talk about the five tiers of the Indian state

02:45:06.760 --> 02:45:13.640
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. So again, as you know, you so helpfully defined the term state capacity,

02:45:13.640 --> 02:45:17.520
[Amit Varma]: define federalism, you know, what does it mean? And how does that meaning apply to us

02:45:17.520 --> 02:45:18.520
[Guest]: right now?

02:45:18.520 --> 02:45:23.320
[Guest]: Yes, I think, you know, even before we get into that, you know, consistent with my, you

02:45:23.320 --> 02:45:26.760
[Guest]: know, conceptual, I like to take a step back to see, you know, what is the big picture

02:45:26.760 --> 02:45:31.000
[Guest]: of the concept? So let's start with a very, very basic question. Okay. So imagine a thought

02:45:31.000 --> 02:45:37.080
[Guest]: experiment that you are to be reborn, and you can be a random person born in any country

02:45:37.080 --> 02:45:42.400
[Guest]: in any in any part of the world, you do not get to pick where in the country's income

02:45:42.400 --> 02:45:46.760
[Guest]: distribution you will be. So this is kind of a veil of ignorance exercise. The only

02:45:46.760 --> 02:45:50.920
[Guest]: parameter you're allowed to pick is would you rather be born in a big country defined

02:45:50.920 --> 02:45:56.880
[Guest]: as population, say over 50 million, a medium country, say population, you know, 20 to 50

02:45:56.880 --> 02:46:01.320
[Guest]: million or a small country in a population under 20 million. Okay. So how do you think

02:46:01.320 --> 02:46:05.720
[Guest]: about what would be the optimal size of a country? Okay, where you would like to be

02:46:05.720 --> 02:46:06.720
[Amit Varma]: born?

02:46:06.720 --> 02:46:13.400
[Amit Varma]: Oh, you're asking me? No, I mean, the answer is, it depends. And the reason that is the

02:46:13.400 --> 02:46:18.160
[Amit Varma]: case is like, one, as I have often expressed, I think, you know, population is a great thing.

02:46:18.160 --> 02:46:21.920
[Amit Varma]: People talk about, you know, population as being one reason India is so poor, and blah,

02:46:21.920 --> 02:46:25.400
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah. No, I think that's the reason we are poor is a failure of governance. I

02:46:25.400 --> 02:46:30.360
[Amit Varma]: think more people mean larger economic networks, networks of scale, people are brains, not

02:46:30.360 --> 02:46:31.360
[Amit Varma]: stomachs.

02:46:31.360 --> 02:46:35.440
[Guest]: And by the way, like, in the spirit of our healthy disagreement in the past, like, let

02:46:35.440 --> 02:46:39.880
[Guest]: me push back on that a little bit, right, which is I fundamentally agree with the argument

02:46:39.880 --> 02:46:44.440
[Guest]: that people are brains and not stomachs. But for the brains to develop, the stomachs have

02:46:44.440 --> 02:46:45.440
[Guest]: to be fed. Okay.

02:46:45.440 --> 02:46:52.360
[Amit Varma]: I haven't finished my answer. So just to just to go through, that's why I said it depends.

02:46:52.360 --> 02:46:56.000
[Amit Varma]: So you're the initial answer from the notion that more people are good people are brains

02:46:56.000 --> 02:47:00.800
[Amit Varma]: not stomachs. You know, it's easy to say that India, Bangladesh, so overpopulated, but equally

02:47:00.800 --> 02:47:06.240
[Amit Varma]: you look at Bahrain and Monaco, and you look at just the density of people. I mean, the

02:47:06.240 --> 02:47:11.640
[Amit Varma]: whole movement of human beings through human history is from a place of less population

02:47:11.640 --> 02:47:16.580
[Amit Varma]: density to a place of more population density that is towards cities. That's what urbanization

02:47:16.580 --> 02:47:21.800
[Amit Varma]: is all about. Because, again, economic networks, networks of scale. However, the flip side

02:47:21.800 --> 02:47:30.680
[Amit Varma]: of that is that you also need good governance to actually, you know, sort of enable all

02:47:30.680 --> 02:47:35.080
[Amit Varma]: these forces to express themselves. And if you are stuck in a large company with bad

02:47:35.080 --> 02:47:39.240
[Amit Varma]: governance, then it's a problem. So that's the imponderable. And that is why my answer

02:47:39.240 --> 02:47:44.120
[Amit Varma]: has to be, it depends because of veil of ignorance, there's too much ignorance. If you tell me

02:47:44.120 --> 02:47:45.920
[Guest]: what the state is like, I'll give you my answer.

02:47:45.920 --> 02:47:49.480
[Guest]: Correct. No, see, but in a way, I was even abstracting from the nature of the state.

02:47:49.480 --> 02:47:52.320
[Guest]: And I guess, you know, I shouldn't put you on the spot like that. And, you know, just

02:47:52.320 --> 02:47:55.760
[Guest]: take a step back and just think about, independent of the nature of the state of the government,

02:47:55.760 --> 02:48:01.840
[Guest]: right? Let's just think about the mechanics of size, okay? So the way to conceptually

02:48:01.840 --> 02:48:06.240
[Guest]: think about this question about the optimal size of nations is to say, what are the benefits

02:48:06.240 --> 02:48:11.200
[Guest]: of size? And what are the costs of size? And as with everything, right, there are both

02:48:11.200 --> 02:48:15.200
[Guest]: costs and benefits, right? Now, the thing is, there are actually many, many, many benefits

02:48:15.200 --> 02:48:20.200
[Guest]: of size, okay? So historically, the biggest benefit of size being in a big country is

02:48:20.200 --> 02:48:25.160
[Guest]: economies of scale in defense, okay? Because the most important existential threat was

02:48:25.160 --> 02:48:31.040
[Guest]: just being run over and invaded. And so being large is the geometry of defense is that if

02:48:31.040 --> 02:48:35.120
[Guest]: your population is uniformly distributed, then the number of people increases with the

02:48:35.120 --> 02:48:39.440
[Guest]: square of the radius, but the circumference to be defended is increasing linearly with

02:48:39.440 --> 02:48:44.120
[Guest]: the radius, right? So population per unit of border to be defended is actually higher,

02:48:44.120 --> 02:48:48.280
[Guest]: the bigger you are, okay? So, and that is why historically, like, you know, countries

02:48:48.280 --> 02:48:52.280
[Guest]: try to expand partly to protect the core, right? Because you would have a periphery

02:48:52.280 --> 02:48:55.280
[Guest]: and then there would be the core that would be a productive core. So that was one of the

02:48:55.280 --> 02:49:00.400
[Guest]: biggest historical advantages of size, okay? Now, there is a related advantage of size,

02:49:00.400 --> 02:49:06.200
[Guest]: which is that along with the scale of investing in military comes other spillovers to civilian

02:49:06.200 --> 02:49:11.520
[Guest]: life, okay? So you build roads partly to mobilize troops from one part to the other, and that

02:49:11.520 --> 02:49:15.800
[Guest]: also has economic spillovers, and that logic applies even today, right? So the best kind

02:49:15.800 --> 02:49:22.080
[Guest]: of, you know, so the internet came from DARPA's investments in defense communications, right?

02:49:22.080 --> 02:49:27.680
[Guest]: Boeing came from investments in military aviation, okay? So a lot of the technological advances

02:49:27.680 --> 02:49:33.120
[Guest]: of society have also happened in the context of military innovation. And that is also benefited

02:49:33.120 --> 02:49:38.160
[Guest]: by scale. It's fundamentally a scale game, right? That because the more people you have,

02:49:38.160 --> 02:49:41.520
[Guest]: the more tax revenue you have, and that allows you to cover the fixed costs of these kind

02:49:41.520 --> 02:49:45.560
[Guest]: of big expenses. Now, there's a third advantage of size, right, which is the size of your

02:49:45.560 --> 02:49:50.320
[Guest]: domestic market, okay? So in worlds where you have trade barriers across countries,

02:49:50.320 --> 02:49:56.160
[Guest]: the size of the market also helps in terms of enabling high fixed cost industries, okay?

02:49:56.160 --> 02:50:01.480
[Guest]: So and just the larger markets are good in many ways. There's a fourth advantage, which

02:50:01.480 --> 02:50:05.600
[Guest]: is better spatial insurance, okay? So something goes wrong in one part of the country, you

02:50:05.600 --> 02:50:09.640
[Guest]: have an earthquake, you have a flood, you have something, and now you have two mechanisms

02:50:09.640 --> 02:50:13.840
[Guest]: of kind of providing insurance against these natural disasters, right? The first is you

02:50:13.840 --> 02:50:18.360
[Guest]: have tax revenue from other parts of the country that can be used to kind of compensate and

02:50:18.360 --> 02:50:22.960
[Guest]: rebuild the places that are hurt. And the even more important channel is migration,

02:50:22.960 --> 02:50:26.720
[Guest]: okay? That people can just move out of the afflicted area and kind of make their lives

02:50:26.720 --> 02:50:30.120
[Guest]: in other parts of the country, right? So and then there's a fifth point, which is fifth

02:50:30.120 --> 02:50:36.000
[Guest]: advantage of size, which is it becomes easier to kind of manage spillovers across jurisdictions,

02:50:36.000 --> 02:50:40.520
[Guest]: okay? So I think, say, rivers are a great example, that if rivers flow through multiple

02:50:40.520 --> 02:50:44.360
[Guest]: countries, then figuring out the public goods aspects of that is harder. Now, it's not easy

02:50:44.360 --> 02:50:48.560
[Guest]: even within a country as we see in the interstate river disputes, but in principle, you kind

02:50:48.560 --> 02:50:53.440
[Guest]: of have structures that allow you to negotiate these areas of policy where there are spillovers,

02:50:53.440 --> 02:50:57.120
[Guest]: okay? So there's many, many, many advantages of being big, okay? So but then the question

02:50:57.120 --> 02:51:01.320
[Guest]: is why are we not like infinitely sized? And that's because there are also enormous costs

02:51:01.320 --> 02:51:06.640
[Guest]: of being big, okay? So the two big costs of being big, see, the biggest cost of size is

02:51:06.640 --> 02:51:12.960
[Guest]: that you have to accommodate greater diversity in people's preferences, right? And as you

02:51:12.960 --> 02:51:17.560
[Guest]: get bigger and bigger and bigger, if you have, again, on a scale of zero to 100, right? If

02:51:17.560 --> 02:51:21.720
[Guest]: you increase your people, then your policy has to be somewhere in the middle, right?

02:51:21.720 --> 02:51:27.080
[Guest]: So the bigger you are, the more you have people whose policy preferences are really far away

02:51:27.080 --> 02:51:30.960
[Guest]: away, right? I mean, from the policies that are being chosen. And at some point, like,

02:51:30.960 --> 02:51:35.240
[Guest]: you know, people want to secede, because they would rather have kind of the autonomy to

02:51:35.240 --> 02:51:39.520
[Guest]: craft their own policies as they see make sense for them, as opposed to being tied to

02:51:39.520 --> 02:51:45.200
[Guest]: this big core, okay? So the first big problem is how do you accommodate diversity in policy

02:51:45.200 --> 02:51:50.120
[Guest]: preferences with like a single set of policies? And the second challenge of size is just how

02:51:50.120 --> 02:51:55.400
[Guest]: much more unwieldy governance becomes because of the layers between the people and the rulers,

02:51:55.400 --> 02:51:59.240
[Guest]: right? And so if, if you have to go through six levels versus two levels, the government

02:51:59.240 --> 02:52:03.120
[Guest]: is just much less responsive, right? I mean, when you become too big, okay, so, so those

02:52:03.120 --> 02:52:07.760
[Guest]: are the two fundamental costs of size, right? And so the over time in history, the optimal

02:52:07.760 --> 02:52:12.400
[Guest]: size of nations, so, you know, countries have expanded, right? I mean, at times a strong

02:52:12.400 --> 02:52:16.600
[Guest]: emperor strong thing, and then they've receded as you overextend and as kind of typically

02:52:16.600 --> 02:52:20.780
[Guest]: populations in the fringe of the country, like, I mean, would rather be on their own,

02:52:20.780 --> 02:52:23.960
[Guest]: because you've typically had a core. And if you see, say, Russia, Ukraine, today, it's

02:52:23.960 --> 02:52:28.360
[Guest]: exactly like, I mean, a manifestation of that, right? I mean, so, you know, historically,

02:52:28.360 --> 02:52:32.480
[Guest]: Tsarist Russia would expand, like, I mean, and kind of bring more areas under kind of

02:52:32.480 --> 02:52:37.120
[Guest]: core Russian control, there was a certain element of coercion, a certain element of,

02:52:37.120 --> 02:52:42.040
[Guest]: you know, migration. But, you know, there is also costs, which the peripheral republics

02:52:42.040 --> 02:52:46.400
[Guest]: were bearing by kind of, you know, having to put up with Russian policies. And when

02:52:46.400 --> 02:52:50.680
[Guest]: 91 happens, people, you know, prefer to break up. Okay, so then that's kind of this basic

02:52:50.680 --> 02:52:55.840
[Guest]: tension that's playing out. So the question then is that, so the beauty of federalism,

02:52:55.840 --> 02:53:00.880
[Guest]: right, I mean, is that the, when you want to then think about what is the optimal size

02:53:00.880 --> 02:53:07.000
[Guest]: of a country, right, federalism, when done well, is a very, very powerful kind of solution,

02:53:07.000 --> 02:53:12.000
[Guest]: because what it does is, if you abstract from the politics, and just focus on the efficiency

02:53:12.000 --> 02:53:17.240
[Guest]: aspects of government for a moment, right, that federalism done right, is basically saying,

02:53:17.240 --> 02:53:22.360
[Guest]: let's put the functions of government that benefit from economies of scale at the level

02:53:22.360 --> 02:53:28.120
[Guest]: of a national government that has a much larger scale. And let's put the functions that need

02:53:28.120 --> 02:53:34.560
[Guest]: to better accommodate diversity of preferences at, say, a state level. And let's put functions

02:53:34.560 --> 02:53:40.200
[Guest]: that require responsiveness, right, I mean, an immediate acting on information at the

02:53:40.200 --> 02:53:45.800
[Guest]: local level, right? I mean, and so, so the core idea of federalism is that let's get

02:53:45.800 --> 02:53:51.080
[Guest]: the benefit of, best of both worlds, right, get the benefit of size by kind of having

02:53:51.080 --> 02:53:55.320
[Guest]: size where it really matters, right? So size matters for defence, size matters for international

02:53:55.320 --> 02:54:00.160
[Guest]: relations, size matters, you know, for all kinds of actions that require economies of

02:54:00.160 --> 02:54:06.280
[Guest]: scale, but let's kind of move the governance much lower in areas where size is a disadvantage,

02:54:06.280 --> 02:54:12.680
[Guest]: okay? So that is kind of the conceptual core of federalism, right? Now, I think, so in

02:54:12.680 --> 02:54:17.320
[Guest]: the Indian case, the federalism, I mean, so, you know, and the Indian case is a particularly

02:54:17.320 --> 02:54:21.520
[Guest]: good example, right, of how these federal principles have, I think, in my view, and

02:54:21.520 --> 02:54:26.920
[Guest]: other experts really contributed to the preservation of the Union, right? Because, you know, one

02:54:26.920 --> 02:54:31.320
[Guest]: of the big concerns at the time of independence was, you know, whether it was the British

02:54:31.320 --> 02:54:35.920
[Guest]: or the Americans, everybody was like, listen, you know, the Punjabi in East Punjab has more

02:54:35.920 --> 02:54:39.040
[Guest]: in common with the Punjabi in West Punjab than with the Tamilian, and they couldn't

02:54:39.040 --> 02:54:43.480
[Guest]: stay together, right? Like, having seen partition, you know, the sense was that this is not a

02:54:43.480 --> 02:54:47.760
[Guest]: country that is going to be together, it's just too unwieldy and too diverse, okay? Like,

02:54:47.760 --> 02:54:53.040
[Guest]: you know, so, but I think, and again, there was an old debate at the time where, you know,

02:54:53.040 --> 02:54:56.960
[Guest]: Gandhi was always in favour of more linguistic states, but Nehru and Ambedkar were concerned

02:54:56.960 --> 02:55:02.960
[Guest]: about the Balkanisation and the risk of further linguistic regional Balkanisation. But I think

02:55:02.960 --> 02:55:08.520
[Guest]: the 56th reorganisation of states by language was a really important decision that has helped

02:55:08.520 --> 02:55:13.920
[Guest]: preserve the Indian Union, and it's because it has kind of allowed the area where people

02:55:13.920 --> 02:55:19.240
[Guest]: have kind of diversity and preferences, particularly culture, language, right? I mean, that it's

02:55:19.240 --> 02:55:23.000
[Guest]: allowed that to be preserved at the state level, right? Like, I mean, while delegating

02:55:23.000 --> 02:55:26.520
[Guest]: to the Union government, right, the functions where there are true economies of scale, okay?

02:55:26.520 --> 02:55:32.400
[Guest]: So, I think, so, federalism, when done well, can really help by getting you the best of

02:55:32.400 --> 02:55:36.480
[Guest]: all of these worlds, right? Now, the problem, of course, is it also comes with a whole bunch

02:55:36.480 --> 02:55:41.640
[Guest]: of additional challenges, right? So, it comes with basic challenges of who's in charge,

02:55:41.640 --> 02:55:46.800
[Guest]: okay? Like, you know, who has the final say on a particular set of decisions, okay? It

02:55:46.800 --> 02:55:51.680
[Guest]: has additional complications in terms of coordination and kind of passing the buck and getting credit.

02:55:51.680 --> 02:55:54.840
[Guest]: So, everybody at different levels wants credit when things go right, they want to pass the

02:55:54.840 --> 02:55:59.440
[Guest]: buck when things go wrong. And there is also this generic kind of push towards over-centralisation,

02:55:59.440 --> 02:56:04.320
[Guest]: right? I mean, which is a constant risk in federal systems. But I think, you know, just

02:56:04.320 --> 02:56:09.120
[Guest]: taking a step back about how to think about federalism, I think the key insight in what

02:56:09.120 --> 02:56:14.360
[Guest]: I'm telling you is that we often think about kind of governments as hierarchies, right?

02:56:14.360 --> 02:56:18.040
[Guest]: I mean, we say, oh, there's a, the central government is the highest, and then there's

02:56:18.040 --> 02:56:21.800
[Guest]: the state government, and then there's the local government. But thinking about governments

02:56:21.800 --> 02:56:26.260
[Guest]: as hierarchies is fundamentally, I think, incorrect, right? Rather, you should be thinking

02:56:26.260 --> 02:56:30.760
[Guest]: about these governments in terms of functions and not hierarchies. There are some functions

02:56:30.760 --> 02:56:35.520
[Guest]: that naturally are best done at the central government level, some best done at the state,

02:56:35.520 --> 02:56:40.400
[Guest]: and some best done at the local. And frankly, from the perspective of the citizen, you know,

02:56:40.400 --> 02:56:44.040
[Guest]: the decisions and effectiveness of the local government matter much, much more, right?

02:56:44.040 --> 02:56:47.560
[Guest]: I mean, are my lights, are my streets, is the drains, are the drains being cleaned,

02:56:47.560 --> 02:56:50.840
[Guest]: is the garbage being collected, are the streetlights working, are the teachers showing up? And

02:56:50.840 --> 02:56:57.360
[Guest]: these are all kind of local government functions, because they depend on acting on local information,

02:56:57.360 --> 02:57:02.080
[Guest]: and kind of reducing the time lag between kind of an issue being identified and it being

02:57:02.080 --> 02:57:05.680
[Guest]: solved, right? So, and, you know, and we can talk a little bit more about this about now,

02:57:05.680 --> 02:57:10.440
[Guest]: see, the Constitution tries to kind of provide some clarity on what function should sit at

02:57:10.440 --> 02:57:15.080
[Guest]: what level by segregating things at the sectoral level, okay, saying that some sectors are

02:57:15.080 --> 02:57:19.560
[Guest]: in the state list, some are in the central list, or some are in the concurrent list.

02:57:19.560 --> 02:57:23.040
[Guest]: But I think, and we can talk more about, you know, the COVID example and other things that

02:57:23.040 --> 02:57:27.800
[Guest]: in some ways we are better off by thinking in terms of function as opposed to sector,

02:57:27.800 --> 02:57:32.520
[Guest]: right? So, functions that require economies of scale are best done at the national level.

02:57:32.520 --> 02:57:36.880
[Guest]: Functions that require coordination and that need to kind of accommodate migration and

02:57:36.880 --> 02:57:40.880
[Guest]: people moving across are better done at the national level. Functions that need to respond

02:57:40.880 --> 02:57:44.360
[Guest]: to local variation are better done, like, you know, at a lower level. So anyway, so

02:57:44.360 --> 02:57:48.840
[Guest]: that's, I think, like, you know, a high-level conceptual, you know, taxonomy of federalism,

02:57:48.840 --> 02:57:52.480
[Guest]: so to speak. And then, you know, we can talk more about, you know, tensions as well as

02:57:52.480 --> 02:57:53.480
[Guest]: the Indian experience.

02:57:53.480 --> 02:57:58.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, that's fascinating. And what I also sort of liked about your chapter was a historical

02:57:58.520 --> 02:58:02.800
[Amit Varma]: perspective you bring to this, like when you talk about Europe and China in the 15th century,

02:58:02.800 --> 02:58:07.360
[Amit Varma]: and you know, looking at the start of the 15th century, you would imagine, imagine that

02:58:07.360 --> 02:58:11.600
[Amit Varma]: China will do much better. And, you know, they will, all the technological progress

02:58:11.600 --> 02:58:15.240
[Amit Varma]: will happen there, and the innovation will happen there, and so on and so on, so forth.

02:58:15.240 --> 02:58:19.400
[Amit Varma]: But it's actually Europe, because China is too centralized, information takes too long

02:58:19.400 --> 02:58:23.640
[Amit Varma]: to kind of pass, like those giant dinosaurs, which became extinct, I don't know why I thought

02:58:23.640 --> 02:58:29.680
[Amit Varma]: of that. And by the way, a Velociraptor, I think it's called, you know, Spielberg created

02:58:29.680 --> 02:58:36.320
[Amit Varma]: a WhatsApp narrative about it, actually, it's the size of a turkey. So just a small aside,

02:58:36.320 --> 02:58:41.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, you could have a pet Velociraptor, if you lived in those days, if it allowed

02:58:41.440 --> 02:58:45.680
[Amit Varma]: you, I think in that particular case, consent would be important. But again, the example

02:58:45.680 --> 02:58:49.680
[Amit Varma]: of Europe and China in the 15th century, and why Europe did so well, because it's basically

02:58:49.680 --> 02:58:54.720
[Amit Varma]: is perforce decentralized, it's different states, but people are moving back and forth,

02:58:54.720 --> 02:58:57.960
[Amit Varma]: innovation is moving back and forth, ideas are moving back and forth, they're competing

02:58:57.960 --> 02:59:01.720
[Amit Varma]: for labor, they're competing for capital, all of that is happening, it's almost like

02:59:01.720 --> 02:59:07.920
[Amit Varma]: a perfect environment. Now, you know, when you think of both the benefits of many, many

02:59:07.920 --> 02:59:14.960
[Amit Varma]: people, the economies of scale, and also the importance of local governance, so you know,

02:59:14.960 --> 02:59:20.840
[Amit Varma]: you don't have sort of sclerosis setting in, it makes complete sense that, you know, national

02:59:20.840 --> 02:59:26.160
[Amit Varma]: defense, you know, foreign affairs, that's best left to the center, and who's going to

02:59:26.160 --> 02:59:32.880
[Amit Varma]: clean my Nalla outside, that's best, you know, left at a local level. And indeed, India was,

02:59:32.880 --> 02:59:37.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, designed, as you point out, at a federal structure across five tiers, you know,

02:59:37.240 --> 02:59:42.920
[Amit Varma]: you had national government, state governments, district, block, and local body levels, right.

02:59:42.920 --> 02:59:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And this is in conception, this sounds absolutely brilliant. But the way our state was really

02:59:48.120 --> 02:59:53.200
[Amit Varma]: designed by our founders had a bias towards centralization, and not enough power, not

02:59:53.200 --> 02:59:58.520
[Amit Varma]: enough money went all the way down the line. And we, you know, suffer with that today.

02:59:58.520 --> 03:00:04.520
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about the reasons for this bias of centralization, because, you know, in hindsight,

03:00:04.520 --> 03:00:10.280
[Amit Varma]: it's, of course, easy to pass judgment. But, you know, sitting there, in Delhi, as a country

03:00:10.280 --> 03:00:14.400
[Amit Varma]: is collapsing around you, I can totally understand that thing that let's keep it together, you

03:00:14.400 --> 03:00:18.760
[Amit Varma]: know, the center must hold, as it were, you know, so you centralize power and all of that.

03:00:18.760 --> 03:00:24.560
[Amit Varma]: But the consequences of that, you know, you have 50, 70, 100 years down the line for all,

03:00:24.560 --> 03:00:29.720
[Amit Varma]: you know. So tell me a bit about how the state actually evolved. These are the good intentions,

03:00:29.720 --> 03:00:34.080
[Amit Varma]: federal karenge, state, you know, and again, states organized by language is also great.

03:00:34.080 --> 03:00:35.320
[Amit Varma]: Where did it go wrong?

03:00:35.320 --> 03:00:40.400
[Guest]: Yes, I think, so let's first kind of get some facts, right, to understand just how overcentralized

03:00:40.400 --> 03:00:46.560
[Guest]: India is, right? I mean, so, see, one measure of just how overcentralized India is, is,

03:00:46.560 --> 03:00:51.720
[Guest]: if you look at the number of times a state government has been dismissed, okay, a democratically

03:00:51.720 --> 03:00:56.680
[Guest]: elected state government, right, I mean, has just been summarily dismissed by the central

03:00:56.680 --> 03:01:01.920
[Guest]: government, or a weaker variant of that, which is the chief minister is just replaced, okay,

03:01:01.920 --> 03:01:06.760
[Guest]: by campaign, because, and that happens even today, though, 356 has gone down. Okay, so

03:01:06.760 --> 03:01:12.760
[Guest]: I think I have a stat in the book that says that I think between 1960 and 2000, there's

03:01:12.760 --> 03:01:17.680
[Guest]: a there's a window there, that, you know, there's, we document over 80 cases of either

03:01:17.680 --> 03:01:21.600
[Guest]: Article 356, or chief ministers being replaced. And so this was really

03:01:21.600 --> 03:01:22.600
[Guest]: 83 times.

03:01:22.600 --> 03:01:29.920
[Guest]: 83 times, right? Like, you know, I can't remember the exact dates. I think it was 1960 to 2010.

03:01:29.920 --> 03:01:30.920
[Guest]: 50 to 90.

03:01:30.920 --> 03:01:35.400
[Guest]: 50 to 90. Oh, just 90. Okay, not even, I thought it went to 2010. But anyway, like, you know,

03:01:35.400 --> 03:01:41.720
[Guest]: I think, regardless, there's a very, very, very large number of cases where local democratic

03:01:41.720 --> 03:01:46.400
[Guest]: kind of decision making as represented in the elected government has completely been

03:01:46.400 --> 03:01:51.280
[Guest]: countermanded by the centre. Okay, now, Article 356 was meant to be used in the most egregious

03:01:51.280 --> 03:01:56.480
[Guest]: cases of complete breakdown of law and order, like, you know, and, and a lot of those powers.

03:01:56.480 --> 03:02:01.720
[Guest]: In fact, I can't remember which one of you guys said this, right? But a lot of because

03:02:01.720 --> 03:02:05.640
[Guest]: the initial constitution, the laws in many ways reflected that of a colonial state, not

03:02:05.640 --> 03:02:10.240
[Guest]: just a colonial state, but also a state designed for wartime. Okay, because a lot of these

03:02:10.240 --> 03:02:13.800
[Guest]: discussions happening around the preparation for World War Two, that those things stayed

03:02:13.800 --> 03:02:19.960
[Guest]: on to kind of give the government of India, kind of extreme powers to be used in emergencies.

03:02:19.960 --> 03:02:24.360
[Guest]: But it got routinized, right? It got routinized to the point where states almost become became

03:02:24.360 --> 03:02:29.040
[Guest]: subservient. So that was one part of overcentralization, at the political level, right? Then at the

03:02:29.040 --> 03:02:33.560
[Guest]: financial level, at the policy level, one way to then think about how much control the

03:02:33.560 --> 03:02:38.120
[Guest]: centre keeps is that, you know, it's both at the level of say, centrally sponsored schemes,

03:02:38.120 --> 03:02:42.040
[Guest]: okay, so even though issues like health and education are supposed to be in the state

03:02:42.040 --> 03:02:47.680
[Guest]: list, right, by kind of having a lot of financial power with the central government that gets

03:02:47.680 --> 03:02:53.240
[Guest]: done through schemes, you're also effectively forcing states to kind of toe the line with

03:02:53.240 --> 03:02:57.240
[Guest]: regard to these central guidelines, right? So we can talk a lot more about that as well

03:02:57.240 --> 03:03:01.120
[Guest]: and get into details of how over-centralized things are and what the costs of those things

03:03:01.120 --> 03:03:06.120
[Guest]: are. See, but I think it's important not just to blame the centre, right? The bigger culprit

03:03:06.120 --> 03:03:09.960
[Guest]: in some ways are the state governments, right? Because they have not actually decentralised

03:03:09.960 --> 03:03:14.200
[Guest]: any authority to local governments, okay? So, and Raja Chalaiya had this kind of wonderful

03:03:14.200 --> 03:03:18.800
[Guest]: quote, he says, everybody wants decentralization up to their level, okay? Like, you know, so

03:03:18.800 --> 03:03:23.240
[Guest]: nobody wants to give up power and this is true both politically and bureaucratically,

03:03:23.240 --> 03:03:27.840
[Guest]: right? You know, nobody wants to spend the long climbing the greasy pole of power to

03:03:27.840 --> 03:03:31.440
[Guest]: get to the top and then give it away, right? Like, you know, so there's all these tendencies

03:03:31.440 --> 03:03:35.520
[Guest]: towards over-centralization. But I think if you take a step back into why we are the way

03:03:35.520 --> 03:03:38.800
[Guest]: we are at the time of the Constitution, how we've evolved, there's really three reasons,

03:03:38.800 --> 03:03:42.880
[Guest]: right? There are political reasons, there's economic reasons and frankly, the most important

03:03:42.880 --> 03:03:46.520
[Guest]: may well be social reasons, which I think Madhav Khosla talks about in his book, right?

03:03:46.520 --> 03:03:51.400
[Guest]: And the political reason was obvious, which is the single biggest concern of the framers

03:03:51.400 --> 03:03:56.040
[Guest]: was that the country would fall apart, okay? So, you needed this idea of a strong centre

03:03:56.040 --> 03:03:59.520
[Guest]: and you know, it was a union of states partly reflecting how British India was organized,

03:03:59.520 --> 03:04:04.520
[Guest]: but partly reflecting the princely states and the fact that these were reasonably distinct

03:04:04.520 --> 03:04:09.680
[Guest]: kind of entities. But the political unity of India was paramount in the minds of the

03:04:09.680 --> 03:04:13.560
[Guest]: founders and so that's partly why you give the union government so much power. There's

03:04:13.560 --> 03:04:20.600
[Guest]: also the economic aspect of the thinking that most of the development had to be state-led

03:04:20.600 --> 03:04:25.160
[Guest]: and the resources that were needed for these investments were so large that it was felt

03:04:25.160 --> 03:04:29.400
[Guest]: that only the government of India could actually mobilize those resources. So, there's an economic

03:04:29.400 --> 03:04:33.320
[Guest]: reason and I think the most important one was actually the social reason, right? Which

03:04:33.320 --> 03:04:39.440
[Guest]: is that the Indian state was not just trying to create a functioning order of, you know,

03:04:39.440 --> 03:04:44.080
[Guest]: just law and order in a functioning state, but it was also trying to do social reform

03:04:44.080 --> 03:04:49.600
[Guest]: in a big way, okay? And I think the biggest concern of decentralization of power was the

03:04:49.600 --> 03:04:55.640
[Guest]: concern of local elite capture, right? And this was not just a theoretical concern. We'll

03:04:55.640 --> 03:04:59.600
[Guest]: see this even now, right? I mean, in empirical work and social welfare programs and other

03:04:59.600 --> 03:05:04.800
[Guest]: areas is that, you know, given just the deeply ingrained inequalities in Indian society,

03:05:04.800 --> 03:05:09.960
[Guest]: the reformers who kind of, you know, were architects of the constitution just did not trust, right?

03:05:09.960 --> 03:05:13.520
[Guest]: So, Ambedkar's famous quote about the village kind of being a den of prejudice, etc. So,

03:05:13.520 --> 03:05:17.080
[Guest]: very practically, what does this mean? Practically, it means that, think about something like

03:05:17.080 --> 03:05:22.080
[Guest]: education, okay? Now, in, say, the US or in most other high-income countries, education

03:05:22.080 --> 03:05:26.320
[Guest]: is purely a local government function, okay? It's done at the local level and the logic

03:05:26.320 --> 03:05:30.240
[Guest]: is that you accommodate preferences, there are certain standard curriculum, but local

03:05:30.240 --> 03:05:35.200
[Guest]: bodies have a lot of power, okay? But in an Indian case, where the history of caste in

03:05:35.200 --> 03:05:39.520
[Guest]: many ways was about denying education, right? I mean, to the underprivileged or denying

03:05:39.520 --> 03:05:43.520
[Guest]: education to women, right? There was just this very real concern that local control

03:05:43.520 --> 03:05:47.760
[Guest]: would mean that you would simply not educate the underprivileged folks. Now, it's a different

03:05:47.760 --> 03:05:52.920
[Guest]: story that it didn't happen for other reasons, but the concern was that you cannot trust

03:05:52.920 --> 03:05:58.920
[Guest]: local elites to kind of do the investments that will disturb the social order, but that

03:05:58.920 --> 03:06:02.960
[Guest]: which are really important for social progress, okay? So, I think that was probably the biggest

03:06:02.960 --> 03:06:07.040
[Guest]: reason for the over-centralisation. I mean, think about this, right? So, if you're a government

03:06:07.040 --> 03:06:11.600
[Guest]: teacher who is recruited by the government and sent there to do a job, and again, panchayat

03:06:11.600 --> 03:06:15.000
[Guest]: is this wonderful example, right, where you see these tensions playing out even today.

03:06:15.000 --> 03:06:19.280
[Guest]: So, you see that episode of kind of, you know, so throughout the thing, you see that this

03:06:19.280 --> 03:06:24.840
[Guest]: is reserved for women, but it's the Sarpanchpati who's doing the job, but you see that the

03:06:24.840 --> 03:06:29.880
[Guest]: agent of the state is kind of meant to make sure that the laws of the state are being

03:06:29.880 --> 03:06:35.960
[Guest]: followed against kind of the local pressures, and as usual, the end result will be somewhere

03:06:35.960 --> 03:06:40.880
[Guest]: in the middle, right? So, you don't fully, the modernising state is meeting the traditional

03:06:40.880 --> 03:06:46.240
[Guest]: society. Tradition doesn't give up immediately, and modernity also loses, but they meet somewhere

03:06:46.240 --> 03:06:50.200
[Guest]: in the middle, right? So, you do get progress, and so I think these are the historical reasons

03:06:50.200 --> 03:06:55.680
[Guest]: for why we are so over-centralised, and so again, it made sense at that time, but I think

03:06:55.680 --> 03:07:01.000
[Guest]: part of the reason we need to re-imagine our possibilities today is that those kind of

03:07:01.000 --> 03:07:06.440
[Guest]: founding moments were times of literacy rates of 120% at a time when you had, you know,

03:07:06.440 --> 03:07:10.320
[Guest]: no cell phones, no way of getting information, no way of monitoring, no way of really knowing

03:07:10.320 --> 03:07:14.480
[Guest]: what's going on, and so you over-centralised partly because you didn't trust, but, you

03:07:14.480 --> 03:07:18.680
[Guest]: know, we are at a place where the optimal amount of decentralisation is almost certainly

03:07:18.680 --> 03:07:21.720
[Guest]: much higher than, you know, what we've had so far.

03:07:21.720 --> 03:07:26.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I'll read out that Ambedkar quote because I love it so much, where he said,

03:07:26.840 --> 03:07:31.280
[Amit Varma]: quote, what is a village but a sink of localism, a den of ignorance, narrow-mindedness and

03:07:31.280 --> 03:07:35.960
[Amit Varma]: communalism. Just a beautiful sentence, flows so well, and, you know, and that kind of gets

03:07:35.960 --> 03:07:42.960
[Amit Varma]: me to thinking, and of course, you know, what Ambedkar is implicitly also nodding to is

03:07:42.960 --> 03:07:46.800
[Amit Varma]: that notion of people as a good thing, of, you know, no such thing as overpopulation

03:07:46.800 --> 03:07:51.560
[Amit Varma]: that I pointed out, that cities change incentives, that you enter those larger economic networks,

03:07:51.560 --> 03:07:56.560
[Amit Varma]: your incentives change, and you can no longer afford to be ignorant, you can no longer afford

03:07:56.560 --> 03:08:01.840
[Amit Varma]: to be so narrow-minded or prejudiced or whatever, and they're not magic bullets, but it changes

03:08:01.840 --> 03:08:06.000
[Amit Varma]: a little bit for the better. Now, you know, it's easy to look back in hindsight and say

03:08:06.000 --> 03:08:10.480
[Amit Varma]: that, oh, that was wrong, but at that moment, sitting in his position, it just seemed a

03:08:10.480 --> 03:08:15.160
[Amit Varma]: completely plausible thing to do. The country is falling apart, you got to do something,

03:08:15.160 --> 03:08:19.000
[Amit Varma]: social imperative, centralised power, you know, there is so much to be done in terms

03:08:19.000 --> 03:08:24.240
[Amit Varma]: of building new industries, building infrastructure, centralised power, that's economic reason.

03:08:24.240 --> 03:08:30.240
[Amit Varma]: And the social reason is that, look, the country is a den of such, you know, casteism, bigotry,

03:08:30.240 --> 03:08:34.280
[Amit Varma]: all of this shit happening all over the place, and we elites in Delhi are not like that,

03:08:34.280 --> 03:08:39.120
[Amit Varma]: we'll figure it out, we'll change it from the top down, centralised power, right? And

03:08:39.120 --> 03:08:43.960
[Amit Varma]: the thing is, and I know it's possible to be too harsh and be judgmental about this

03:08:43.960 --> 03:08:48.520
[Amit Varma]: third instinct, the way it worked out, because, you know, you couldn't change society from

03:08:48.520 --> 03:08:52.720
[Amit Varma]: the top down. This was, of course, a classic, you know, Gandhi versus the other guy's argument

03:08:52.720 --> 03:08:55.640
[Amit Varma]: where Gandhi Singh was, we got to change it from the bottom up, though Gandhi, of course,

03:08:55.640 --> 03:09:00.200
[Amit Varma]: also romanticised villages, partly because he didn't spend too much time in them. But

03:09:00.200 --> 03:09:04.200
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi Singh was, we'll change it from the bottom up, otherwise it won't happen. And

03:09:04.200 --> 03:09:09.300
[Amit Varma]: these guys were like, no, no, top down. And top down has failed in every sense. All these

03:09:09.300 --> 03:09:14.080
[Amit Varma]: problems are still with us, caste is still with us, we are still a misogynist society,

03:09:14.080 --> 03:09:16.080
[Guest]: and so on and so forth. And of course, we don't know the counterfactual.

03:09:16.080 --> 03:09:19.160
[Guest]: Exactly, right? So that's what I was going to say yes and no, right? I think because

03:09:19.160 --> 03:09:24.720
[Guest]: see, the careful research that looks at, say, the impact of women's reservation in panchayat

03:09:24.720 --> 03:09:29.280
[Guest]: elections, right, like, you know, actually shows that despite all of these limitations,

03:09:29.280 --> 03:09:34.160
[Guest]: right, I mean, it has had not, again, worked is too strong a word, right? It has moved

03:09:34.160 --> 03:09:38.160
[Guest]: things in the right direction, right? See, in the end, progress is only directional,

03:09:38.160 --> 03:09:41.440
[Guest]: right? I mean, so you can always look at this glass half empty and say, kuch nahi hua, it

03:09:41.440 --> 03:09:45.520
[Guest]: has failed. So I think, again, with all of these things, the binary of worked or not

03:09:45.520 --> 03:09:49.720
[Guest]: worked, I don't think is that useful, right? I think it's useful to kind of then just break

03:09:49.720 --> 03:09:53.740
[Guest]: apart the different components and go to first principles and say, so, what were we trying

03:09:53.740 --> 03:09:57.600
[Guest]: to achieve here? Okay, and then to what extent has that succeeded or failed? And then look

03:09:57.600 --> 03:10:01.760
[Guest]: at the empirical evidence where possible. And this is why, you know, I think as we get

03:10:01.760 --> 03:10:06.320
[Guest]: into the, and I'll spend a little bit more time talking about the research, right, and

03:10:06.320 --> 03:10:10.760
[Guest]: the evidence, which is again, you know, hopefully, the comparative advantage I bring to the show,

03:10:10.760 --> 03:10:14.280
[Guest]: right, the things I say are actually based on or bringing together a bunch of academic

03:10:14.280 --> 03:10:18.080
[Guest]: papers, you know, but this is a huge area of research, right, of looking at the impact

03:10:18.080 --> 03:10:22.600
[Guest]: of decentralization, at the impact of different kinds of reforms, you know, whether it's legislative

03:10:22.600 --> 03:10:27.320
[Guest]: reforms and representation, where you do find positive effects, right? So that is the modernizing

03:10:27.320 --> 03:10:31.120
[Guest]: state that is top down, like, you know, left to themselves, villages are not going to elect

03:10:31.120 --> 03:10:37.040
[Guest]: women as pradhans, right? So that is a top down imposition. But, you know, I think it

03:10:37.040 --> 03:10:41.360
[Guest]: was Urvashi, I think, in the most recent episode, like, you know, I mean, who was saying that

03:10:41.360 --> 03:10:45.960
[Guest]: these things are moving, okay, like, I mean, that these reservations or others have moved

03:10:45.960 --> 03:10:51.680
[Guest]: things in the right direction. So, you know, I think that's one thing. But another case

03:10:51.680 --> 03:10:56.920
[Guest]: for top down, frankly, and this is where the NREGA paper comes in, is that there is now

03:10:56.920 --> 03:11:01.800
[Guest]: actually pretty strong evidence that, let's think about the design and delivery of welfare

03:11:01.800 --> 03:11:05.560
[Guest]: programs, okay? So there's an element of this that's about targeting, about identifying

03:11:05.560 --> 03:11:09.960
[Guest]: who is the poor, and there's an element about this that is delivery, okay? And is maybe

03:11:09.960 --> 03:11:15.840
[Guest]: you can argue both ways, you can argue that local communities have more information as

03:11:15.840 --> 03:11:20.800
[Guest]: to who is in fact, the most deprived, and therefore needs the support, right? So one

03:11:20.800 --> 03:11:25.000
[Guest]: logic would be to say, you should give the local communities more control over a welfare

03:11:25.000 --> 03:11:29.920
[Guest]: budget that they can allocate to who actually is the most needy. But the flip side is to

03:11:29.920 --> 03:11:34.440
[Guest]: say that welfare for the poor usually affects the power structures like, you know, of the

03:11:34.440 --> 03:11:39.960
[Guest]: current rich, and NREGA is a perfect example that was massively resisted by landlords,

03:11:39.960 --> 03:11:44.300
[Guest]: okay? And so there is both the risk of elite capture, that these resources will be captured

03:11:44.300 --> 03:11:48.640
[Guest]: by them, and the risk that, you know, they will simply not implement the program. And

03:11:48.640 --> 03:11:53.200
[Guest]: so here the evidence now from multiple studies does suggest, right, that the top down approach

03:11:53.200 --> 03:11:59.160
[Guest]: has worked better, okay, in terms of, so this is a very nice paper in Indonesia, that Ben

03:11:59.160 --> 03:12:02.680
[Guest]: Olkin, Abhijit Banerjee and others have done, and I think that will soon be out in the American

03:12:02.680 --> 03:12:07.120
[Guest]: Economic Review. But, you know, they basically look at a reform that went from distributing

03:12:07.120 --> 03:12:10.600
[Guest]: rice by taking whole bags of rice to the local communities and saying you distribute it to

03:12:10.600 --> 03:12:15.440
[Guest]: one that kind of identifies the poor and sends the money directly to them. And they basically

03:12:15.440 --> 03:12:20.860
[Guest]: estimate that this reform dramatically improved the progressivity of the welfare by actually

03:12:20.860 --> 03:12:25.120
[Guest]: finding more of the needy, right? So that's again a case where in the delivery of welfare

03:12:25.120 --> 03:12:31.960
[Guest]: programs actually top down, technology enabled interventions may in fact work better than

03:12:31.960 --> 03:12:36.480
[Guest]: the decentralized version. But there are other areas, like say school governance and service

03:12:36.480 --> 03:12:41.080
[Guest]: delivery, where I think a decentralized model, particularly with regard to accountability

03:12:41.080 --> 03:12:44.280
[Guest]: and things like attendance, right, I mean, may work better. But again, you can see the

03:12:44.280 --> 03:12:49.400
[Guest]: tension, right? The tension, there are political tensions in federalism, but there's also administrative

03:12:49.400 --> 03:12:54.120
[Guest]: tensions in federalism, right? Because the view towards a more centralized state for

03:12:54.120 --> 03:12:58.480
[Guest]: say teachers and doctors is to say that a local village will never be able to attract

03:12:58.480 --> 03:13:02.320
[Guest]: a highly qualified teacher or doctor. The only way they will ever get a qualified staff

03:13:02.320 --> 03:13:06.680
[Guest]: member is if they are recruited through a civil service exam, and then you are posted

03:13:06.680 --> 03:13:10.480
[Guest]: to that village, because otherwise the village is never going to get a qualified staff member.

03:13:10.480 --> 03:13:16.440
[Guest]: But that comes at the cost of the fact that two problems. One is that this highly qualified

03:13:16.440 --> 03:13:20.600
[Guest]: and highly paid person feels no social connection to the village, and therefore lives far away.

03:13:20.600 --> 03:13:24.240
[Guest]: So a big part of the absence problem is that people are just not living in the communities,

03:13:24.240 --> 03:13:27.280
[Guest]: right? Like I mean, they're traveling from in and out. And second is that they're not

03:13:27.280 --> 03:13:31.040
[Guest]: embedded in the community. And so therefore, there's very little kind of accountability.

03:13:31.040 --> 03:13:35.320
[Guest]: So again, you see the tension, right? I mean, do you want a more qualified person, but who's

03:13:35.320 --> 03:13:40.260
[Guest]: not accountable and embedded? Or are you better off with a slightly less qualified person,

03:13:40.260 --> 03:13:44.200
[Guest]: but who's from the community and held accountable there, right? So I think, so in all of these

03:13:44.200 --> 03:13:48.880
[Guest]: cases, theoretically, you can argue it both ways, which is kind of why you then need the

03:13:48.880 --> 03:13:52.840
[Guest]: empirical evidence to say what is happening. And this is, again, a very interesting case

03:13:52.840 --> 03:13:57.280
[Guest]: in education, where, see, for example, there's this nice RCT that Abhijit and Esther and

03:13:57.280 --> 03:14:01.680
[Guest]: others did in UP, and that paper is called Pitfalls of Participatory Development, where

03:14:01.680 --> 03:14:06.440
[Guest]: they tried to activate village education committees, okay, which are supposed to do this oversight

03:14:06.440 --> 03:14:10.320
[Guest]: of the teachers and local, and you know, they have some local control. And what they found

03:14:10.320 --> 03:14:14.200
[Guest]: was most people who were on VCs didn't even know they were on the VCs. And, you know,

03:14:14.200 --> 03:14:17.800
[Guest]: and even those who knew they were on basically were completely ineffective, because they

03:14:17.800 --> 03:14:23.680
[Guest]: had very little authority, okay, on the teachers. Conversely, there was a study on school management

03:14:23.680 --> 03:14:27.760
[Guest]: in Kenya that was also randomized. And what they find is a bit more nuanced, which is

03:14:27.760 --> 03:14:32.040
[Guest]: that strengthening the school management committee has no effect on the performance of the regular

03:14:32.040 --> 03:14:35.400
[Guest]: civil service teacher, but it does have a significant effect on the performance of the

03:14:35.400 --> 03:14:39.480
[Guest]: locally hired contract teacher. And that's because the community controls the renewal

03:14:39.480 --> 03:14:43.560
[Guest]: of the contract, but the community has no say over the regular teacher. So I think the

03:14:43.560 --> 03:14:48.960
[Guest]: point again, is just to highlight that conceptually, you can argue these both ways. But you know,

03:14:48.960 --> 03:14:51.080
[Guest]: evidence matters and details really, really matter.

03:14:51.080 --> 03:14:55.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and you've got plenty of nuance in your chapter. And you know, when you write about

03:14:55.800 --> 03:14:59.200
[Amit Varma]: the key tensions, you've already mentioned a few of them, like there is a tension about

03:14:59.200 --> 03:15:03.680
[Amit Varma]: who has a final say, then there are conflicts over fundamental values, where at the local

03:15:03.680 --> 03:15:08.000
[Amit Varma]: level, you may have a different set of values. And at a central level, you could have a different

03:15:08.000 --> 03:15:12.240
[Amit Varma]: set of values, a classic example being the US Civil War, which you give, or Ambedkar

03:15:12.240 --> 03:15:17.320
[Amit Varma]: himself, when he's talking about the village correctly, as a, you know, a den of ignorance,

03:15:17.320 --> 03:15:22.200
[Amit Varma]: is sort of talking about a similar conflict, which is there, you speak about the administrative

03:15:22.200 --> 03:15:26.740
[Amit Varma]: and political tensions, risk of elite capture at the local level, you've spoken about that,

03:15:26.740 --> 03:15:31.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, the trade off between education and the local embeddedness, as you point out,

03:15:31.720 --> 03:15:35.480
[Amit Varma]: that you know, locally, there may not be enough trained teachers. So if at a central level,

03:15:35.480 --> 03:15:39.560
[Amit Varma]: you're sending your teachers to government schools, even if they don't show up there,

03:15:39.560 --> 03:15:44.800
[Amit Varma]: but we discussed that in another episode. And another tension that you point out is

03:15:44.800 --> 03:15:48.480
[Amit Varma]: a political tensions when different parties are in power at different levels and all of

03:15:48.480 --> 03:15:54.320
[Amit Varma]: that. Now, I get all of this. And I also like as an approach, especially when we are getting

03:15:54.320 --> 03:15:59.040
[Amit Varma]: inquiry done into this, we are getting empirical evidence, RCTs are being done, all these insights

03:15:59.040 --> 03:16:03.880
[Amit Varma]: are coming up. I understand that in theory, we can just really modify it and figure out

03:16:03.880 --> 03:16:08.760
[Amit Varma]: where you need a top down intervention and where it is best left locally. But here's

03:16:08.760 --> 03:16:14.480
[Amit Varma]: the thing, in theory, we both agree that we need to be federal, federalism is good, you

03:16:14.480 --> 03:16:19.680
[Amit Varma]: need local governance, you need to design the areas and say, okay, the centre does this,

03:16:19.680 --> 03:16:24.880
[Amit Varma]: local governments do this. But at the same time, as you say, the three concerns that

03:16:24.880 --> 03:16:30.360
[Amit Varma]: our founders had when they were effectively designing the state, you know, 75 years ago,

03:16:30.360 --> 03:16:36.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, are completely valid that the centre may not have held, what the hell do you do,

03:16:36.440 --> 03:16:41.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, and economically, at that time, the thinking would just have been, you know,

03:16:41.560 --> 03:16:46.520
[Amit Varma]: top down and all of that. And, and Ambedkar's tensions were, of course, valid that listen,

03:16:46.520 --> 03:16:50.840
[Amit Varma]: this whole country will descend into, you know, its worst values, if we if we just,

03:16:50.840 --> 03:16:56.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, leave it to local forces. So here's my thought experiment for you, that let's

03:16:56.160 --> 03:17:01.040
[Amit Varma]: say that with the knowledge that you have now, if you are sitting in Ambedkar's place,

03:17:01.040 --> 03:17:07.160
[Amit Varma]: with context as it was then, how would you design it differently? Because it is not enough

03:17:07.160 --> 03:17:12.320
[Amit Varma]: to say that let's design it in at x equilibrium, and then gradually we will tinker, tinker,

03:17:12.320 --> 03:17:16.520
[Amit Varma]: tinker as we get data. It's not enough to say that because once you've set the equilibrium

03:17:16.520 --> 03:17:21.120
[Amit Varma]: at x, you've set the incentives kind of in stone because nobody who has power is going

03:17:21.120 --> 03:17:25.160
[Amit Varma]: to give it up to speak to your you know, the earlier quote of yours about how everybody

03:17:25.160 --> 03:17:30.680
[Amit Varma]: wants to devolve power, but only up to them, they don't want to, you know, so a state,

03:17:30.680 --> 03:17:33.800
[Amit Varma]: so a state government will say no, no, we need more power, local governance, but they

03:17:33.800 --> 03:17:37.080
[Amit Varma]: won't give it to the districts and the districts won't give it to the blocks and so on and

03:17:37.080 --> 03:17:41.560
[Amit Varma]: so forth. And therefore it just in terms of the political economy, nobody's going to give

03:17:41.560 --> 03:17:46.660
[Amit Varma]: the power away. So it is easier said than done, that we will tinker things and we will

03:17:46.660 --> 03:17:51.120
[Amit Varma]: smoothen the system as we go along. No, once you've set it, you've kind of set it in stone.

03:17:51.120 --> 03:17:56.080
[Amit Varma]: So what are you sort of going for in this horrible thought experiment I've inflicted

03:17:56.080 --> 03:17:57.080
[Amit Varma]: upon you?

03:17:57.080 --> 03:18:01.520
[Guest]: Yeah, it's too much pressure, right? Like, you know, I think, so let me just say a couple

03:18:01.520 --> 03:18:05.120
[Guest]: of other things, right? I mean, since you're talking about the founding moments, and I

03:18:05.120 --> 03:18:08.680
[Guest]: want to connect back to this episode you did with Madhavan, like, you know, and I think

03:18:08.680 --> 03:18:12.000
[Guest]: the other nice thing I've seen in the arc of your own episodes over the years is, you

03:18:12.000 --> 03:18:17.440
[Guest]: know, how some of your, if I may say so, more black and white characterizations, right?

03:18:17.440 --> 03:18:21.680
[Guest]: I mean, have become more nuanced, right? So your early version would just be, like, you

03:18:21.680 --> 03:18:25.400
[Guest]: know, the US Constitution was so small, why do we have this huge thing? And it's a periodical

03:18:25.400 --> 03:18:26.400
[Guest]: that gets in so much.

03:18:26.400 --> 03:18:28.080
[Amit Varma]: I still feel that.

03:18:28.080 --> 03:18:33.320
[Guest]: But, but I think what Madhavan rightly pointed out was that the US Constitution is an incredibly

03:18:33.320 --> 03:18:38.120
[Guest]: conservative constitution that is written in many ways, codifying the power of a very

03:18:38.120 --> 03:18:43.320
[Guest]: narrow landed educated elite, right? I mean, that wrote that constitution. So, and there

03:18:43.320 --> 03:18:48.200
[Guest]: was no concept, really, of social justice, or any of issues of slavery or any of these

03:18:48.200 --> 03:18:52.200
[Guest]: things, right? And so, and so there are two things, one, that constitution is small. So

03:18:52.200 --> 03:18:57.200
[Guest]: for two reasons, really, see, one is going back to first principles of federalism, right?

03:18:57.200 --> 03:19:02.440
[Guest]: I mean, that the US is what we call in political science, coming together federalism, right?

03:19:02.440 --> 03:19:07.960
[Guest]: I mean, where the states were distinct units, and any power that is not given explicitly

03:19:07.960 --> 03:19:12.560
[Guest]: to the central government sits with the states, okay? So, which is why that is what is called

03:19:12.560 --> 03:19:16.520
[Guest]: coming together, you come together and give up a few powers. And the modern European Union

03:19:16.520 --> 03:19:19.920
[Guest]: is a bit like that, right? I mean, that you're coming together and saying, I'm giving you

03:19:19.920 --> 03:19:23.280
[Guest]: powers and currency, I'm giving you powers and defense, because there is economies of

03:19:23.280 --> 03:19:27.600
[Guest]: scale, but anything I'm not giving you sits with me. Okay, so there is one part of that,

03:19:27.600 --> 03:19:31.640
[Guest]: which reflects the fact that the US Constitution is short, simply because of that. But the

03:19:31.640 --> 03:19:36.480
[Guest]: much bigger issue is that it is not trying to do any social reform. And you see the tension

03:19:36.480 --> 03:19:41.200
[Guest]: then 100 years later, or 80 years later, when they're dealing with slavery, right? I mean,

03:19:41.200 --> 03:19:46.280
[Guest]: is that it does take a federal government to come in with military force to actually

03:19:46.280 --> 03:19:50.360
[Guest]: kind of abolish slavery. And that is still not enough, right? It takes, you know, many,

03:19:50.360 --> 03:19:54.960
[Guest]: many years after that, you know, you need the Voting Rights Act in the 1960s to even

03:19:54.960 --> 03:19:59.200
[Guest]: make sure that voting rights of minorities were respected, right? So, and that gives

03:19:59.200 --> 03:20:04.040
[Guest]: you a sense of just how deeply entrenched these local power structures are, and how

03:20:04.040 --> 03:20:10.320
[Guest]: it takes kind of, you know, not just ideational change at the level of constitutions and laws,

03:20:10.320 --> 03:20:14.920
[Guest]: but the actual physical backing of force of that state, right? I mean, that comes and

03:20:14.920 --> 03:20:19.440
[Guest]: enforces the rights of the most marginalized. Okay, so I think this challenge that we're

03:20:19.440 --> 03:20:25.240
[Guest]: trying to both kind of govern with stability, because think about it, right? Any attempt

03:20:25.240 --> 03:20:30.000
[Guest]: at social justice is fundamentally disruptive to a status quo. Okay, like, you know, so

03:20:30.000 --> 03:20:33.880
[Guest]: you're trying to, and that is, I think, the magic of India, right? The magic of India

03:20:33.880 --> 03:20:37.360
[Guest]: is that, and I think this was also in your episode with Urvashi, right? I mean, which

03:20:37.360 --> 03:20:42.880
[Guest]: is how, despite all of the conflicts and fault lines we have, the society is still actually

03:20:42.880 --> 03:20:48.120
[Guest]: remarkably stable, okay, in terms of not kind of, you know, exploding in conflagrations,

03:20:48.120 --> 03:20:53.320
[Guest]: and it's a miracle, right? And so, the challenge of kind of the Indian state is that governance

03:20:53.320 --> 03:20:57.960
[Guest]: and constitutions are fundamentally conservative, right? Because you want to preserve law and

03:20:57.960 --> 03:21:02.280
[Guest]: order, you want to preserve certain things, but social reform is fundamentally disruptive,

03:21:02.280 --> 03:21:07.680
[Guest]: right? And so, historically, social reform has happened with revolutions, right? Whether

03:21:07.680 --> 03:21:12.840
[Guest]: it's the Russian revolution, the peasant revolutions in China. So, what is, again, magical about

03:21:12.840 --> 03:21:18.160
[Guest]: the Indian experience is, like, how we have managed to kind of push the arc of the state

03:21:18.160 --> 03:21:23.680
[Guest]: in progressive ways, right? I mean, that improves social justice, but within an arc of kind

03:21:23.680 --> 03:21:28.600
[Guest]: of overall democratic constitutional systems and stability, right? So, you get, you know,

03:21:28.600 --> 03:21:33.920
[Guest]: so anyway, so I think the, so therefore, coming back to how you would re-architect or re-write

03:21:33.920 --> 03:21:38.160
[Guest]: certain aspects of the constitution today, based on what we know from the last 70 years.

03:21:38.160 --> 03:21:42.880
[Guest]: See, it's not just what we know, right? It is the fact that today, education rates, literacy

03:21:42.880 --> 03:21:47.400
[Guest]: rates are 75% compared to 15%, right? You know, smartphones and cell phones. So, why

03:21:47.400 --> 03:21:51.480
[Guest]: do you not trust the local areas? So, the two reasons you don't decentralize is, one,

03:21:51.480 --> 03:21:54.920
[Guest]: you think people are not capable, and second, like, you know, you don't have visibility,

03:21:54.920 --> 03:22:00.320
[Guest]: okay? Now you have both, right? So, essentially, what I argue, in terms of the kind of reform

03:22:00.320 --> 03:22:05.400
[Guest]: agenda that I think states should be doing, that deepen federalism, while at the same,

03:22:05.400 --> 03:22:10.160
[Guest]: deepen federalism and local control, while at the same time, recognizing the importance

03:22:10.160 --> 03:22:15.120
[Guest]: of checks and balances, right? Because the local communities left to themselves may very

03:22:15.120 --> 03:22:19.680
[Guest]: often kind of undo some of these goals of justice and progressive kind of, you know,

03:22:19.680 --> 03:22:24.480
[Guest]: both programs and policies. So, let's take a very concrete example of teachers, okay?

03:22:24.480 --> 03:22:30.920
[Guest]: So, the logic of federalism would suggest that education should be locally managed.

03:22:30.920 --> 03:22:35.760
[Guest]: The problem is that will the village guy appoint his crony as the teacher, like, you know,

03:22:35.760 --> 03:22:39.120
[Guest]: and therefore, you get a poor teacher and who's not accountable, whatever, right? So,

03:22:39.120 --> 03:22:43.640
[Guest]: how do you therefore build a modified architecture that builds both the strength of your current

03:22:43.640 --> 03:22:48.520
[Guest]: systems of quality control, with the additional accountability, okay, that comes from local

03:22:48.520 --> 03:22:52.320
[Guest]: control, okay? So, one of the things I talk about, so I have this whole section of nuanced

03:22:52.320 --> 03:22:57.160
[Guest]: decentralization, right? So, it can't just be, I'm blindly going to send off everything,

03:22:57.160 --> 03:23:04.960
[Guest]: but the flip side, the argument of the centralizer, who says, local level, local level, also needs

03:23:04.960 --> 03:23:09.480
[Guest]: to be treated with a grain of salt, because there is a self-serving power preserving element

03:23:09.480 --> 03:23:14.240
[Guest]: of that argument, okay? So, what a framework that I broadly talk about in the chapter,

03:23:14.240 --> 03:23:17.760
[Guest]: when I talk about nuanced decentralization, is to imagine just in the case of teachers

03:23:17.760 --> 03:23:22.920
[Guest]: the following, okay? That you can only be appointed as a teacher, if you have been empanelled

03:23:22.920 --> 03:23:26.400
[Guest]: through a selection process, whereby you have to pass certain exams and show that you have

03:23:26.400 --> 03:23:31.720
[Guest]: certain qualifications, okay? But being empanelled doesn't guarantee you a job, okay? So, today,

03:23:31.720 --> 03:23:35.200
[Guest]: you get into the government system, you're basically guaranteed a job, okay? So, the

03:23:35.200 --> 03:23:39.440
[Guest]: job is still held at the pleasure of the local community. And so, you know, if you don't

03:23:39.440 --> 03:23:43.200
[Guest]: show up, if you're not effectively catering to the local community, they can say, nahi,

03:23:43.200 --> 03:23:46.720
[Guest]: like, we don't want you, okay? So, they can just say, I don't want you, I want somebody

03:23:46.720 --> 03:23:51.080
[Guest]: else, but they are constrained in finding people who are also empanelled, okay? So,

03:23:51.080 --> 03:23:55.840
[Guest]: in a world where you have empanelled, say, more teachers than there are jobs, okay, you

03:23:55.840 --> 03:24:00.120
[Guest]: have got both the quality control aspect of it and the local control aspect of it, right?

03:24:00.120 --> 03:24:04.520
[Guest]: So, that's kind of an example of how you might want to architect certain things that has

03:24:04.520 --> 03:24:09.560
[Guest]: both the benefits of a slightly higher level of kind of administration and oversight, but

03:24:09.560 --> 03:24:13.800
[Guest]: also the strengths of local accountability and local control. And then there are more

03:24:13.800 --> 03:24:17.480
[Guest]: radical versions of this, you know, which I talk about, which is a slightly more radical

03:24:17.480 --> 03:24:22.400
[Guest]: version is you could take the entire budget for schools and say, because see, right now,

03:24:22.400 --> 03:24:26.960
[Guest]: the government school salaries are so much higher, okay, than the private schools, right?

03:24:26.960 --> 03:24:31.400
[Guest]: So, and part of the problem in the, why does the private school kind of do well? It's because

03:24:31.400 --> 03:24:34.800
[Guest]: they're paying one-fourth the salaries and hiring two times or three times as many teachers.

03:24:34.800 --> 03:24:37.800
[Guest]: And so, you have lesser multi-grade teaching, you have smaller groups, you have all of that,

03:24:37.800 --> 03:24:43.280
[Guest]: right? So, there is nothing that prevents a public school from having those same efficiencies

03:24:43.280 --> 03:24:47.280
[Guest]: if you were to say that I'm going to give the local body the entire budget of the school,

03:24:47.280 --> 03:24:50.920
[Guest]: right? And the local body can choose to spend that money how they see fit. Now, of course,

03:24:50.920 --> 03:24:53.720
[Guest]: you still have to worry about corruption, you still have to worry about a bunch of things.

03:24:53.720 --> 03:24:58.120
[Guest]: And so, you will need certain things that says you can still only hire an empanel teacher,

03:24:58.120 --> 03:25:02.240
[Guest]: but you have some flexibility in the wage setting. So, here is the budget for the salary.

03:25:02.240 --> 03:25:06.960
[Guest]: Maybe the salary is made to 50% and the remaining 50% is allocated on a performance-based basis

03:25:06.960 --> 03:25:10.760
[Guest]: or allocated to say, I want to attract a more qualified teacher. So, there are ways of kind

03:25:10.760 --> 03:25:15.440
[Guest]: of taking the current budget and dramatically improving the efficiency and accountability

03:25:15.440 --> 03:25:19.640
[Guest]: by increasing the stake of local communities, but at the same time, building some checks

03:25:19.640 --> 03:25:24.600
[Guest]: and balances, right? I mean, to make sure that there is a trust but verify approach

03:25:24.600 --> 03:25:30.440
[Guest]: to how we do this. And that's not an answer to how I would read out the constitution,

03:25:30.440 --> 03:25:33.720
[Guest]: but that's kind of a very specific example, right? I mean, of saying how these principles

03:25:33.720 --> 03:25:34.720
[Guest]: can be tweaked.

03:25:34.720 --> 03:25:39.360
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. No, you know, I have changed my mind a lot over the course of all the great

03:25:39.360 --> 03:25:44.040
[Amit Varma]: conversations I've had with people who've given me so much insight, but this particular

03:25:44.040 --> 03:25:47.880
[Amit Varma]: issue about the US Constitution is not one of them. I maintain that we would have been

03:25:47.880 --> 03:25:52.600
[Amit Varma]: incredibly fortunate to have the US Constitution because it enshrined and protected individual

03:25:52.600 --> 03:25:57.720
[Amit Varma]: rights, you know, and that's important. It protected free speech, you know, Umar Khalid

03:25:57.720 --> 03:26:01.720
[Amit Varma]: and Siddique Kapun would not be in prison today if we had that constitution. Mohammad

03:26:01.720 --> 03:26:05.400
[Amit Varma]: Zubair would not have been arrested if we had that constitution. So, it is something

03:26:05.400 --> 03:26:09.840
[Amit Varma]: I feel strongly about protecting individual rights. As far as slavery is concerned, that's

03:26:09.840 --> 03:26:14.360
[Amit Varma]: a social evil. If the elites of that time were to enshrine their values into the constitution,

03:26:14.360 --> 03:26:19.320
[Amit Varma]: abolishing slavery wouldn't have been there anyway. And over time, as society changed,

03:26:19.320 --> 03:26:23.640
[Amit Varma]: thankfully it went away. I would argue that our efforts at social justice didn't really

03:26:23.640 --> 03:26:28.440
[Amit Varma]: work in the top down way. You know, we still have many of those problems that we had then.

03:26:28.440 --> 03:26:34.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the whole quest for social justice in some ways became a bit of a political farce.

03:26:34.080 --> 03:26:38.320
[Amit Varma]: And I don't necessarily mean that you leave it to the villages to reform themselves as

03:26:38.320 --> 03:26:41.360
[Amit Varma]: Gandhiji might have hoped. I don't think that would have worked either. So, I don't have

03:26:41.360 --> 03:26:47.440
[Amit Varma]: an answer for this. But I do see where sort of the limitations are. So, on this particular

03:26:47.440 --> 03:26:51.880
[Amit Varma]: issue, I won't take a stand because I don't have any answers. But I see the problems of,

03:26:51.880 --> 03:26:54.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, where the elites failed, I do see that.

03:26:54.680 --> 03:26:57.880
[Guest]: No, but I think this connects us back all the way to state capacity, right? See, because

03:26:57.880 --> 03:27:04.760
[Guest]: in a way, the story of India, right, is that because we are crafting our ideals of what

03:27:04.760 --> 03:27:09.800
[Guest]: we want to do, right, at a time when, because, see, and this is, I think, partly in Alex

03:27:09.800 --> 03:27:15.240
[Guest]: and Shruti's episode on, you know, on kind of the imitation, right, premature imitation,

03:27:15.240 --> 03:27:20.600
[Guest]: right? See, the ideas of what kind of a modern democratic society should stand for, even

03:27:20.600 --> 03:27:25.560
[Guest]: in 1947 and 50, are informed by what people are seeing in the West, right? So, the story

03:27:25.560 --> 03:27:30.840
[Guest]: of India is always one of aspirations ahead of our capacity, right? I mean, so the problem

03:27:30.840 --> 03:27:35.000
[Guest]: is not, again, what's in the aspirations, right? It is that we haven't had the capacity

03:27:35.000 --> 03:27:39.440
[Guest]: to then actually follow up against that. So, one view is to say that, listen, you need

03:27:39.440 --> 03:27:43.640
[Guest]: to put the aspirations there, even if you're not able to deliver, because that is a bit

03:27:43.640 --> 03:27:48.360
[Guest]: of a North Pole and a guide star, not star, to where do we want to go? Okay, like, okay,

03:27:48.360 --> 03:27:52.600
[Guest]: at least the laws aspire to this so that we can get inspired to get there. Okay, so that

03:27:52.600 --> 03:27:58.560
[Guest]: is one framing. The converse framing of that is that when your aspirations are so far ahead

03:27:58.560 --> 03:28:03.160
[Guest]: of your capacity to deliver, it actually breeds cynicism, like, you know, that we just say

03:28:03.160 --> 03:28:06.760
[Guest]: all of these things and never do it, and then that creates kind of the trust deficits and

03:28:06.760 --> 03:28:10.560
[Guest]: everything that we talk about. And so, I think that is, it is the core challenge, and why,

03:28:10.560 --> 03:28:14.760
[Guest]: you know, when I talk about state capacity, I see these investments in state capacity

03:28:14.760 --> 03:28:19.680
[Guest]: as the central, the core. When I think about India at 75, right, I think about, you know,

03:28:19.680 --> 03:28:23.280
[Guest]: we are a miracle in many, many ways, right? There are just so many things to be proud

03:28:23.280 --> 03:28:27.880
[Guest]: of, right? But if we want to focus our mind on what is it that we really need to get our

03:28:27.880 --> 03:28:33.400
[Guest]: act together in the next 25 years, it is essentially building a state that is capable of meeting

03:28:33.400 --> 03:28:38.400
[Guest]: the aspirations, right? I mean, in the Constitution, the law, and coming back to Fukuyama's scope

03:28:38.400 --> 03:28:43.320
[Guest]: and strength, I agree. Some of this will also require reducing the scope of the state, right?

03:28:43.320 --> 03:28:47.500
[Guest]: I mean, there's a basic mathematical truism that if I'm, you know, and in fact, I find

03:28:47.500 --> 03:28:51.880
[Guest]: a very useful analogy to be with my own time management, right? I mean, so in a way, I'm

03:28:51.880 --> 03:28:55.600
[Guest]: like the overcommitted state in terms of my time commitment, right? I mean, because I

03:28:55.600 --> 03:29:00.400
[Guest]: have committed to more things than I have time for. So I am always kind of juggling,

03:29:00.400 --> 03:29:04.400
[Guest]: I'm always kind of responding to what is most urgent, who's putting the most pressure on

03:29:04.400 --> 03:29:08.920
[Guest]: me, and things that are important, but not urgent are getting neglected. So to bring

03:29:08.920 --> 03:29:13.720
[Guest]: my life into kind of balance, it requires a combination of two things. One is becoming

03:29:13.720 --> 03:29:17.800
[Guest]: more efficient and investing in capacity. But the other is also cutting down the things

03:29:17.800 --> 03:29:23.160
[Guest]: I say yes to. Okay, so mechanically, you need both, right? I mean, and so that applies even

03:29:23.160 --> 03:29:27.000
[Guest]: to the state. I mean, we are definitely overextended doing a bunch of things that we have no business

03:29:27.000 --> 03:29:30.640
[Guest]: doing. So some of that has to come down. But I think where I want to push back not to you,

03:29:30.640 --> 03:29:34.280
[Guest]: but some kind of some of the naive kind of discussions that happen out there to say,

03:29:34.280 --> 03:29:37.620
[Guest]: look, that where the markets have taken over, the markets have done well. So let's kind

03:29:37.620 --> 03:29:41.080
[Guest]: of unleash the markets in these areas. And that will also do well. And I think there

03:29:41.080 --> 03:29:44.640
[Guest]: in the core functions of the state, right, I mean, that that is not going to work. So

03:29:44.640 --> 03:29:49.280
[Guest]: you are going to have to kind of invest in core state capacity and apply that in these

03:29:49.280 --> 03:29:53.120
[Guest]: six areas that I've talked about, right? I mean, so and the reason the federalism chapter

03:29:53.120 --> 03:29:57.640
[Guest]: is kind of a theme rather than a sector is that the ideas in the federalism chapter then

03:29:57.640 --> 03:30:03.560
[Guest]: apply across the sectors, correct? Which is how do you then kind of optimally re-architect

03:30:03.560 --> 03:30:09.600
[Guest]: our governance across multiple layers, so that you really kind of give local communities

03:30:09.600 --> 03:30:13.840
[Guest]: more of a stake and more of a control. So and maybe there's a chicken and egg problem,

03:30:13.840 --> 03:30:19.160
[Guest]: right? The chicken and egg problem of decentralization is that people say we will not decentralize

03:30:19.160 --> 03:30:23.640
[Guest]: because there is no capacity to actually do the work locally. Conversely, the capacity

03:30:23.640 --> 03:30:27.240
[Guest]: is not built because you've never given them the money and the authority to kind of make

03:30:27.240 --> 03:30:31.600
[Guest]: it worth developing the capacity, okay? So and in a way, if you look at even the arc

03:30:31.600 --> 03:30:34.880
[Guest]: of Indian independence, the British in the early 20th century were like they can't govern

03:30:34.880 --> 03:30:39.080
[Guest]: themselves, right? So which is why 1935 Government of India Act kind of having the provincial

03:30:39.080 --> 03:30:43.880
[Guest]: governments showing that you can do some stuff then kind of builds your muscles along the

03:30:43.880 --> 03:30:48.600
[Guest]: way to being able to govern yourself. So similarly, at the local government level, we're in this

03:30:48.600 --> 03:30:52.520
[Guest]: chicken and egg today, where we say we won't decentralize because there's no capacity.

03:30:52.520 --> 03:30:56.000
[Guest]: And conversely, people say, why bother when there's no capacity? And that's where I think,

03:30:56.000 --> 03:30:59.560
[Guest]: you know, particularly in urban governance, right? I mean, where I agree with Ashwin and

03:30:59.560 --> 03:31:04.640
[Guest]: others is that because you now have enough educated, highly competent people, in many

03:31:04.640 --> 03:31:09.520
[Guest]: cases, more competent who are in the government, right? If you can find ways for greater civic

03:31:09.520 --> 03:31:13.680
[Guest]: engagement in urban governance, right? I mean, then you're kind of both proving that the

03:31:13.680 --> 03:31:18.040
[Guest]: community can handle its problems. And by doing that, you're also building a little

03:31:18.040 --> 03:31:22.160
[Guest]: bit more of a political force, right? I mean, to actually ask for more devolution mean at

03:31:22.160 --> 03:31:26.560
[Guest]: the local level, right? So and, and I think it's not an accident, of course, you know,

03:31:26.560 --> 03:31:31.720
[Guest]: the jury's out on what Aam Aadmi Party will do in Punjab, right? But it's not an accident

03:31:31.720 --> 03:31:36.480
[Guest]: that the chief minister who focuses the most in service delivery issues is the most empowered

03:31:36.480 --> 03:31:41.680
[Guest]: mayor of India, right? Like Kirneen is, because he is basically governing Delhi. And therefore,

03:31:41.680 --> 03:31:45.520
[Guest]: like Kirneen talks about service delivery issues. And you know, the more the more you

03:31:45.520 --> 03:31:52.000
[Guest]: start kind of seeing organic political formations that focus exclusively on local service delivery

03:31:52.000 --> 03:31:55.240
[Guest]: and governance, right? I mean, then you will kind of build a little bit of a bottom up

03:31:55.240 --> 03:32:00.080
[Guest]: aspect to that. And, you know, power is never taken, right? Power is all power is never

03:32:00.080 --> 03:32:04.440
[Guest]: given away, right? Power is taken, okay. And so it's just like, so there are people in

03:32:04.440 --> 03:32:09.520
[Guest]: for decentralization advocates who think as who feel as strongly about this as democratization

03:32:09.520 --> 03:32:14.000
[Guest]: itself, let's say, like, you know, democracy itself, elites never give up power, it happens

03:32:14.000 --> 03:32:19.680
[Guest]: when people kind of demand the power that, you know, you you give away the vote. And

03:32:19.680 --> 03:32:23.360
[Guest]: there are people who argue the same thing for decentralization. And going back to question,

03:32:23.360 --> 03:32:27.280
[Guest]: nobody will willingly give up power, but it has to come up bottom up and saying, you know,

03:32:27.280 --> 03:32:30.920
[Guest]: we will step up and do what it takes to govern ourselves, right? I mean, and having done

03:32:30.920 --> 03:32:35.720
[Guest]: that, that creates the space over time for more and more decentralization. And, you know,

03:32:35.720 --> 03:32:39.880
[Guest]: and sometimes the institutions will also help. I think this time, the Finance Commission

03:32:39.880 --> 03:32:44.520
[Guest]: has explicitly kind of linked certain transfers to kind of the next level. Now, again, you

03:32:44.520 --> 03:32:48.480
[Guest]: could argue that that's not democratic. But you know, it's it's one of the ways in which

03:32:48.480 --> 03:32:52.960
[Guest]: things that we know are good, but that are politically not incentive compatible get done

03:32:52.960 --> 03:32:57.680
[Guest]: is through these nonpartisan commissions that make recommendations that then get adopted.

03:32:57.680 --> 03:33:03.720
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful. I'll push back a little bit at your pushing back of allegedly non-me. You

03:33:03.720 --> 03:33:09.000
[Amit Varma]: know, in your book, you have this little bit about how, you know, some market proponents

03:33:09.000 --> 03:33:12.920
[Amit Varma]: say that, you know, look at what markets have done in telecom and airlines.

03:33:12.920 --> 03:33:16.520
[Amit Varma]: That is not you, by the way. I'm not pushing back on you. That's not you.

03:33:16.520 --> 03:33:20.240
[Amit Varma]: No, because you know, that that is actually the classic example I use whenever I talk

03:33:20.240 --> 03:33:24.080
[Amit Varma]: about the power of the market that, you know, I remember what phones were, you know, you

03:33:24.080 --> 03:33:28.920
[Amit Varma]: had a 10 year waiting period for phones in the 1980s. Airlines were so expensive. I remember

03:33:28.920 --> 03:33:33.440
[Amit Varma]: when you opened it up, how things changed because of market incentives. And so I use

03:33:33.440 --> 03:33:37.880
[Amit Varma]: exactly those two sectors. And you kind of mentioned exactly those two sectors. But even

03:33:37.880 --> 03:33:42.720
[Amit Varma]: if you're pushing back against someone who is allegedly non-me, it is still to be noted

03:33:42.720 --> 03:33:46.200
[Amit Varma]: that you're pushing back against the straw man because I don't think anyone argues that

03:33:46.200 --> 03:33:51.000
[Amit Varma]: the basic roles of the government should be supplanted by the market. Instead, the argument

03:33:51.000 --> 03:33:56.560
[Amit Varma]: is and the kind of argument I would make in essential services like education, for example,

03:33:56.560 --> 03:34:00.560
[Amit Varma]: is that I am not saying that you abolish government schools and only have private schools, right?

03:34:00.560 --> 03:34:04.800
[Amit Varma]: Not at all. All I'm saying is that you and we've discussed this at length in our episode

03:34:04.800 --> 03:34:10.480
[Amit Varma]: is that while you do what you do, allow private schools the chance to exist instead of putting

03:34:10.480 --> 03:34:15.200
[Amit Varma]: so many impediments in their way, such as you can't have a for profit school. So you

03:34:15.200 --> 03:34:19.880
[Amit Varma]: know, a lot of the budget private schools today to which, you know, slum dwellers send

03:34:19.880 --> 03:34:23.560
[Amit Varma]: their children instead of to a free government school, thereby voting with their feet. A

03:34:23.560 --> 03:34:28.640
[Amit Varma]: lot of those schools are illegal outside the law, outside the law can shut down any moment,

03:34:28.640 --> 03:34:34.160
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. So all I'm saying is that allow society to solve its own problems. And

03:34:34.160 --> 03:34:37.560
[Amit Varma]: the few things that a state should do well, again, going back to Fokuyama Singh about

03:34:37.560 --> 03:34:41.240
[Amit Varma]: scope and strength, we need a strong state that does a few things well, not a weak state

03:34:41.240 --> 03:34:45.040
[Amit Varma]: that does many things badly. What I would say is that in the things that a strong state

03:34:45.040 --> 03:34:50.320
[Amit Varma]: should do, well, you know, by all means, a state should do that no one is making the,

03:34:50.320 --> 03:34:54.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, argument that the market should do everything, but at least allow people to

03:34:54.920 --> 03:34:59.000
[Guest]: solve their own problems. That's and I agree completely. And you know, that's why I have

03:34:59.000 --> 03:35:03.120
[Guest]: this whole chapter in state and market, right? In fact, so, you know, this is the temptation

03:35:03.120 --> 03:35:06.800
[Guest]: of going into other chapters, but I am going to, you know, read out one paragraph from

03:35:06.800 --> 03:35:14.080
[Guest]: chapter 10, right? On kind of, you know, on basically this, you know, so I say this, right?

03:35:14.080 --> 03:35:17.560
[Guest]: In ideological terms, my approach in the coming chapters is best characterized as being to

03:35:17.560 --> 03:35:22.040
[Guest]: the center left in terms of goals and center right in terms of means, right? So my choice

03:35:22.040 --> 03:35:26.160
[Guest]: of sectors is clearly influenced by the development and capabilities framework associated with

03:35:26.160 --> 03:35:29.400
[Guest]: those who prioritize equity and justice, right? So whether it's education, health, all of

03:35:29.400 --> 03:35:33.440
[Guest]: these things. Further, my focus on improving the capacity of public systems to deliver

03:35:33.440 --> 03:35:37.720
[Guest]: better will also resonate with the center left. Yet, the ideas and themes I focus on

03:35:37.720 --> 03:35:42.200
[Guest]: also reflect my views based on years of research and practice that delivering these goals at

03:35:42.200 --> 03:35:46.860
[Guest]: scale, especially with our limited resource base, will require us to sharply improve accountability

03:35:46.860 --> 03:35:50.800
[Guest]: efficiency and cost effectiveness within the government, pay careful attention to incentives

03:35:50.800 --> 03:35:55.800
[Guest]: and design systems that better align the incentives of all stakeholders to deliver improved outcomes,

03:35:55.800 --> 03:35:59.400
[Guest]: not simply assume that well-intentioned laws and higher budgets will translate into better

03:35:59.400 --> 03:36:04.160
[Guest]: outcomes, and treat markets in the private sector as an ally in achieving social and

03:36:04.160 --> 03:36:08.120
[Guest]: development goals. And these are views that are more commonly associated with the economic

03:36:08.120 --> 03:36:12.480
[Guest]: right. Okay, so that's kind of, you know, where I come in on this. And so hopefully

03:36:12.480 --> 03:36:14.480
[Guest]: there, I think we would agree very, very broadly.

03:36:14.480 --> 03:36:18.960
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I, you know, you don't have to agree to agree with me to be brilliant, you're brilliant

03:36:18.960 --> 03:36:22.920
[Amit Varma]: anyway, and I learned so much from you. But I would again push back at a little characterization

03:36:22.920 --> 03:36:27.440
[Amit Varma]: here when you talk about these goals as center left goals, I think you should in good faith

03:36:27.440 --> 03:36:31.640
[Amit Varma]: accept that they're everybody's goals. And the only argument is about means, right? That

03:36:31.640 --> 03:36:36.440
[Amit Varma]: we want everyone to be educated, we want everyone to be healthy, how do we get there? And what

03:36:36.440 --> 03:36:40.640
[Amit Varma]: the economic right would argue is that, you know, good intentions and the coercive power

03:36:40.640 --> 03:36:45.120
[Amit Varma]: of the state won't get you there. We have all of history as testimony to that. And we

03:36:45.120 --> 03:36:49.960
[Amit Varma]: have to unleash the power of markets and society to help itself. And at the same time, if you

03:36:49.960 --> 03:36:54.680
[Amit Varma]: believe that, you know, good intentions alone, and you know, the power of the state will

03:36:54.680 --> 03:36:58.640
[Amit Varma]: help solve it, go ahead, good luck, but don't stop us from solving our own problems. That's

03:36:58.640 --> 03:37:02.720
[Guest]: kind of what I would say, you know, why I am in the constitution so much now.

03:37:02.720 --> 03:37:06.040
[Guest]: And we agree. And we fully, fully agree.

03:37:06.040 --> 03:37:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. No, let's, let's, let's get on to sort of, let's continue talking about federalism.

03:37:12.160 --> 03:37:15.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, some of the stats that blew my mind, and this is something I should have known,

03:37:15.240 --> 03:37:18.160
[Amit Varma]: this is something in a sense I knew, because I think when Iceland was doing well, in the

03:37:18.160 --> 03:37:23.040
[Amit Varma]: last football World Cup, I said, Varsova has more people than them, you know, so this is

03:37:23.040 --> 03:37:26.680
[Amit Varma]: something I should have known. But I just want to read these statistics out because

03:37:26.680 --> 03:37:31.880
[Amit Varma]: it you realize the scale of the problem and how stupid this kind of our kind of centralization

03:37:31.880 --> 03:37:38.120
[Amit Varma]: is, where at one point, you write, the 15 largest Indian states by population would

03:37:38.120 --> 03:37:43.120
[Amit Varma]: all rank in the top 42 countries in the world by population or 20% of the most populous

03:37:43.120 --> 03:37:47.720
[Amit Varma]: countries in the world, and you've got a chart also, right. So it's not just UP, the 15 largest

03:37:47.720 --> 03:37:52.160
[Amit Varma]: Indian states would be among the top 40 countries in the world. Simply put governing an Indian

03:37:52.160 --> 03:37:56.720
[Amit Varma]: state is best sort of as the equivalent of running a medium to large country, stop quote,

03:37:56.720 --> 03:38:01.140
[Amit Varma]: and then you go on to say, quote, Indian districts and sub districts are also large India has

03:38:01.140 --> 03:38:07.240
[Amit Varma]: over 700 districts, average population under 2 million per district, around 7000 sub districts

03:38:07.240 --> 03:38:13.000
[Amit Varma]: slash blocks, with an average population of 200,000 each, and so on and so forth. And

03:38:13.000 --> 03:38:18.600
[Amit Varma]: then at the end by saying, for perspective, the average district in India has more people

03:38:18.600 --> 03:38:24.760
[Amit Varma]: than 85 countries, or 36% of the countries in the world. So the average district in India

03:38:24.760 --> 03:38:31.120
[Amit Varma]: is bigger than 85 countries in the world, like my god, that's, that's sort of mind blowing.

03:38:31.120 --> 03:38:38.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, if one can't quantify this, but what has been sort of like, first before before

03:38:38.040 --> 03:38:42.240
[Amit Varma]: I ask you questions about what has been the sort of the cost of being centralized all

03:38:42.240 --> 03:38:48.040
[Amit Varma]: this time, if I am to ask you to sort of lay out how deep is the dysfunction between power

03:38:48.040 --> 03:38:51.960
[Amit Varma]: and accountability in this kind of a system, like I had an episode with Shruti Rajagopalan

03:38:51.960 --> 03:38:56.200
[Amit Varma]: on urban governance, and she pointed out that, listen, the guy you're voting for has no power

03:38:56.200 --> 03:38:59.600
[Amit Varma]: to change your life. And the guy who has power to change your life, your votes don't matter

03:38:59.600 --> 03:39:04.520
[Amit Varma]: to him, in a context of Maharashtra, as it were, but I think it would be kind of true

03:39:04.520 --> 03:39:11.760
[Amit Varma]: a lot. So give me a better sense of this structure overall, how powerful is a centre, how powerful

03:39:11.760 --> 03:39:16.400
[Amit Varma]: are the states, how powerful are districts, and so on and so forth. Like both of us agree

03:39:16.400 --> 03:39:20.960
[Amit Varma]: that, for example, you know, reserving those panchayat head seats for women did have an

03:39:20.960 --> 03:39:26.080
[Amit Varma]: impact over a period of time, right? Even if people can argue net positive, net negative,

03:39:26.080 --> 03:39:31.400
[Amit Varma]: I tend to think net positive, but they did have an impact, right, at the very local level.

03:39:31.400 --> 03:39:35.600
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it's true that there's almost no power at the very local level, that

03:39:35.600 --> 03:39:38.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, the centre will stop anything going to the state, the state will stop anything

03:39:38.920 --> 03:39:44.160
[Amit Varma]: going further down. You point out that, you know, the percentage of money, for example,

03:39:44.160 --> 03:39:48.080
[Amit Varma]: that the states get is, I think, two thirds of all revenues are spent by the, all money

03:39:48.080 --> 03:39:49.640
[Guest]: is spent by the centre, right?

03:39:49.640 --> 03:39:55.280
[Guest]: So, sorry, expenditure is more in the states than the centre. But see, essentially, first

03:39:55.280 --> 03:39:58.160
[Guest]: principle, that's why, you know, some of this is overlaps with chapter seven on revenue

03:39:58.160 --> 03:40:02.480
[Guest]: as well, right? So first principles of public finance say that a lot, it makes sense to

03:40:02.480 --> 03:40:07.320
[Guest]: collect revenue at a higher level, okay, because particularly, because there's economies of

03:40:07.320 --> 03:40:10.520
[Guest]: scale and tax administration, you don't want to raise to the bottom in certain aspects

03:40:10.520 --> 03:40:16.040
[Guest]: like corporate taxes, customs and stuff are obviously kind of done. So, and in a way,

03:40:16.040 --> 03:40:20.400
[Guest]: so essentially, revenue, by first principles, it does make more sense that the Government

03:40:20.400 --> 03:40:24.620
[Guest]: of India collects more. But expenditure, by first principles, it makes more sense that

03:40:24.620 --> 03:40:28.600
[Guest]: more of it happens at the state level, because that's, they are closer to the delivery. And

03:40:28.600 --> 03:40:32.120
[Guest]: the gap between that is usually that's what is fulfilled by the Finance Commission, right?

03:40:32.120 --> 03:40:35.840
[Guest]: Because the Finance Commission takes kind of the divisible pool of revenues, and then

03:40:35.840 --> 03:40:42.440
[Guest]: through a formula that has components of horizontal and vertical kind of, you know, the delegation,

03:40:42.440 --> 03:40:47.280
[Guest]: basically allocates money to states. And so the gap comes is fulfilled in two ways. One

03:40:47.280 --> 03:40:51.200
[Guest]: is money that comes to the Finance Commission that is broadly untied. And second is money

03:40:51.200 --> 03:40:54.600
[Guest]: that comes through the centrally sponsored schemes, which is also money coming from the

03:40:54.600 --> 03:40:59.360
[Guest]: centre, but that is more tied, right, into specific things. So anyway, so overall, most

03:40:59.360 --> 03:41:04.040
[Guest]: of the expenditure close to 60% of spending happens at the state level, but about 60%

03:41:04.040 --> 03:41:07.120
[Guest]: of the revenue is collected at the national level.

03:41:07.120 --> 03:41:14.160
[Amit Varma]: Right. And give me a give me sort of a breakdown of the system in terms of what is a power

03:41:14.160 --> 03:41:20.560
[Amit Varma]: breakdown and what should it be? And also, what have sort of been some of the consequences

03:41:20.560 --> 03:41:24.320
[Amit Varma]: of this? And obviously, those will be broader brush, because you can't really quantify anything.

03:41:24.320 --> 03:41:28.760
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, to be honest, the biggest source of discrepancy, frankly, see, if you look

03:41:28.760 --> 03:41:33.080
[Guest]: at the design, by first principles, the centre and the state are the levels where you're

03:41:33.080 --> 03:41:37.440
[Guest]: supposed to design policies and programs and the district and lower level are where you're

03:41:37.440 --> 03:41:42.440
[Guest]: supposed to implement them. Okay, so, and that's broadly how powers are allocated. Okay,

03:41:42.440 --> 03:41:47.120
[Guest]: so when we say that there isn't much power at the local level, I think in practice, it

03:41:47.120 --> 03:41:52.400
[Guest]: really translates into two things. Okay, one is that there is very, very little or frankly

03:41:52.400 --> 03:41:58.360
[Guest]: zero discretionary budget, okay, that is there at the local level. So if you're a local principal

03:41:58.360 --> 03:42:03.920
[Guest]: or even a district education officer, okay, your discretionary budget, in terms of funding

03:42:03.920 --> 03:42:09.440
[Guest]: programs or interventions that may make sense are basically zero. Okay, so that is one margin

03:42:09.440 --> 03:42:15.360
[Guest]: where local levels have very little power. The second margin in and this is more true

03:42:15.360 --> 03:42:20.680
[Guest]: kind of, you know, at the village and at the facility level, is you have basically no power

03:42:20.680 --> 03:42:24.840
[Guest]: over the government employees, right? I mean, so because when we say that the bulk of the

03:42:24.840 --> 03:42:30.160
[Guest]: budget, so when I talk about the decentralization in China, that why does China have so China

03:42:30.160 --> 03:42:34.280
[Guest]: has about 50% of total public expenditure happens at the local government level. In

03:42:34.280 --> 03:42:39.640
[Guest]: India, that's only 3%. Okay, so that gives you a sense of how big this queue is. Okay,

03:42:39.640 --> 03:42:45.640
[Guest]: but the biggest driver of that is that almost all service delivery employees, okay, whether

03:42:45.640 --> 03:42:51.000
[Guest]: it's teachers or doctors, or, you know, street cleaners or anybody is employed at the local

03:42:51.000 --> 03:42:55.520
[Guest]: government. Okay, and so that's where that delta comes in. So when we say, so it is not

03:42:55.520 --> 03:43:01.200
[Guest]: that the Indian villages do not get the resources, but because the bulk of the resources is tied

03:43:01.200 --> 03:43:06.880
[Guest]: to the salary cost of the employee, right, I mean, on whom you have zero kind of accountability,

03:43:06.880 --> 03:43:10.760
[Guest]: that's where the fundamental mismatch happens. Correct. So I think the tweaks we would want

03:43:10.760 --> 03:43:15.000
[Guest]: to make are relatively simple, okay, which is to say, if local governments have a lot

03:43:15.000 --> 03:43:20.000
[Guest]: more authority on kind of the staffing, okay, and, and that's where that nuanced decentralization

03:43:20.000 --> 03:43:24.080
[Guest]: I talked about, right, mean matters, which is saying, you have an empanelled list of

03:43:24.080 --> 03:43:29.760
[Guest]: people who kind of satisfy a certain set of technical criteria for having this government

03:43:29.760 --> 03:43:33.920
[Guest]: job, but that doesn't guarantee you the actual employment that is still done at the local

03:43:33.920 --> 03:43:38.480
[Guest]: government level. So that would be one meaningful way of empowering them. Now, a more radical

03:43:38.480 --> 03:43:43.400
[Guest]: way of empowering them would be to transfer the entire budget, okay, to the local government

03:43:43.400 --> 03:43:47.360
[Guest]: and saying, this is the budget per child, and you know, you have the freedom to spend.

03:43:47.360 --> 03:43:52.320
[Guest]: And then you still want accountability in terms of, you know, so what you want, and

03:43:52.320 --> 03:43:56.040
[Guest]: this goes back to a principle I talk about a lot throughout the book, right, of autonomy

03:43:56.040 --> 03:44:00.200
[Guest]: and process and accountability for outcomes, okay, which is to say that you have the budget,

03:44:00.200 --> 03:44:04.320
[Guest]: but we will kind of have independent measurement of certain outcomes. And then, you know, you

03:44:04.320 --> 03:44:09.120
[Guest]: can think about fiscal rules that say, here is a certain amount that's equal for every

03:44:09.120 --> 03:44:14.120
[Guest]: child. So I talk about this in the expenditure chapter, right, where I talk about a 70-20-10

03:44:14.120 --> 03:44:19.080
[Guest]: principle of allocation of public funds, which is 70% based on an equality principle, where

03:44:19.080 --> 03:44:23.040
[Guest]: every child or every citizen gets the same amount, about 20% based on an equity principle,

03:44:23.040 --> 03:44:26.920
[Guest]: where you say, here are the places that are the kind of most underprivileged and need

03:44:26.920 --> 03:44:31.320
[Guest]: gap kind of financing, and the 10% based on an effectiveness principle that, you know,

03:44:31.320 --> 03:44:34.880
[Guest]: the places that are actually delivering outcomes, so you put a little bit of skin in the game,

03:44:34.880 --> 03:44:39.080
[Guest]: like, you know, for people to be oriented towards outcomes. So I think these would be,

03:44:39.080 --> 03:44:42.520
[Guest]: and this is why, again, the foundation of so many of the reform ideas I have is better

03:44:42.520 --> 03:44:46.400
[Guest]: data, right? And that's why that chapter four, see, these are ideas about performance-based

03:44:46.400 --> 03:44:49.760
[Guest]: funding, which I have shared in the past, even with the Finance Commission, right? And

03:44:49.760 --> 03:44:52.680
[Guest]: in fact, Dr. Y. V. Reddy, I remember talking to him about this back in the day, he said,

03:44:52.680 --> 03:44:55.440
[Guest]: you know, Karthik, all these ideas make a lot of sense, but I don't have the data to

03:44:55.440 --> 03:44:59.400
[Guest]: implement them. Okay, so you need the data, which is again, why that's a foundational

03:44:59.400 --> 03:45:03.760
[Guest]: investment in being able to do reforms along a whole bunch of these lines. But yes, so

03:45:03.760 --> 03:45:10.720
[Guest]: I think, when we say that the state has most of the power, it reflects the fact that the

03:45:10.720 --> 03:45:14.680
[Guest]: employees are state government employees, okay, and it reflects the fact that that's

03:45:14.680 --> 03:45:19.200
[Guest]: where the bulk of the cost is going. And because the local communities have very little oversight

03:45:19.200 --> 03:45:23.760
[Guest]: and accountability on the employees, that's kind of where the core lack of decentralization

03:45:23.760 --> 03:45:28.520
[Guest]: hits you. And the second place where it hits you is the complete lack of discretionary

03:45:28.520 --> 03:45:32.360
[Guest]: budgets. Okay, so if you have some ideas and want to do something, you just don't have

03:45:32.360 --> 03:45:33.360
[Guest]: the resources to do it.

03:45:33.360 --> 03:45:39.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I like the 70-20-10 formulation. And just in terms of local knowledge and local

03:45:39.760 --> 03:45:42.960
[Amit Varma]: priorities, I don't know if you seem to have heard every episode of mine. Did you hear

03:45:42.960 --> 03:45:43.960
[Amit Varma]: the one with Abhinandan Sekhi?

03:45:43.960 --> 03:45:49.880
[Amit Varma]: Yes, the one about the movie theater. They wanted the movie theater. I passed your pop

03:45:49.880 --> 03:45:50.880
[Amit Varma]: quiz.

03:45:50.880 --> 03:45:54.520
[Amit Varma]: You passed my test. You passed. Yeah, I will not remember as many things from my episodes

03:45:54.520 --> 03:45:59.400
[Amit Varma]: as you do. But just for the benefit of listeners who haven't heard that great episode, the

03:45:59.400 --> 03:46:03.560
[Amit Varma]: funda is that, you know, Abhinandan and his team were at this northeast village and they

03:46:03.560 --> 03:46:07.880
[Amit Varma]: asked the villagers, you know, where would you like to kind of your money spend the most?

03:46:07.880 --> 03:46:11.320
[Amit Varma]: And they said, we want a movie theater. Now, this is completely counterintuitive. There

03:46:11.320 --> 03:46:15.200
[Amit Varma]: are people in a village, they could ask for a dispensary, they could ask for a road, they

03:46:15.200 --> 03:46:19.040
[Amit Varma]: could ask for whatever, why do they want a movie theater? And the answer was that because

03:46:19.040 --> 03:46:24.640
[Amit Varma]: there was no entertainment in the village, all the kids would go to, you know, near whatever

03:46:24.640 --> 03:46:28.920
[Amit Varma]: the nearby town was to watch movies. And the roads were bad and unsafe and all of that

03:46:28.920 --> 03:46:32.160
[Amit Varma]: and they would have accidents and the death rate was high. So it was, you had to risk

03:46:32.160 --> 03:46:37.080
[Amit Varma]: your life to watch a film. And if it was a Bollywood film, you probably deserve to risk

03:46:37.080 --> 03:46:42.480
[Amit Varma]: your life for it. But, and that was the thing. And this is local knowledge. This is not something

03:46:42.480 --> 03:46:48.460
[Amit Varma]: a central planner could ever have worked out. And similarly, in every sort of local area,

03:46:48.460 --> 03:46:54.720
[Amit Varma]: you might have different priorities, which only local people would know. And, you know,

03:46:54.720 --> 03:47:00.840
[Amit Varma]: my instinct here would be to figure out what is the most local base of unit you can get

03:47:00.840 --> 03:47:04.600
[Amit Varma]: to and give them as much money as possible and let them make the decisions and then let

03:47:04.600 --> 03:47:08.040
[Amit Varma]: these units, whether they are blocks or districts or whatever, compete with each other, much

03:47:08.040 --> 03:47:12.520
[Amit Varma]: as we would say, states should compete with each other, like in the US to a certain extent

03:47:12.520 --> 03:47:17.200
[Amit Varma]: they do in terms of these are the taxation laws. And, you know, these are all the different

03:47:17.200 --> 03:47:21.320
[Amit Varma]: kind of laws that we have available. This is the ecosystem we are building. You compete

03:47:21.320 --> 03:47:24.880
[Amit Varma]: with each other and then people vote with their feet, which they can because, you know,

03:47:24.880 --> 03:47:29.200
[Amit Varma]: they're moving across states, not across countries. And I think that's a great way, that's a healthy

03:47:29.200 --> 03:47:33.280
[Amit Varma]: competition. And I would have thought that that's one of the fundamental principles of

03:47:33.280 --> 03:47:37.960
[Amit Varma]: federalism, that you allow people to compete at that kind of policy level.

03:47:37.960 --> 03:47:44.480
[Guest]: So, sorry, I think, you know, so you're absolutely right. There's a slight additional nuance

03:47:44.480 --> 03:47:48.480
[Guest]: to that, right? I mean, so what you're kind of, so there is an element of competition,

03:47:48.480 --> 03:47:52.680
[Guest]: right? I mean, which happens, say, at the state level and kind of attracting people,

03:47:52.680 --> 03:47:58.800
[Guest]: investments and all of that stuff. But there is also a very powerful element here of accommodating

03:47:58.800 --> 03:48:05.320
[Guest]: divergence in people's preferences. OK, so the original idea of what's called tibu sorting,

03:48:05.320 --> 03:48:11.560
[Guest]: so Charles, t-i-e-b-o-u-t. So some people actually pronounce it to tibout, but my first

03:48:11.560 --> 03:48:17.080
[Guest]: teacher pronounced him, so Caroline Huxby calls him tibu. But the core idea of tibu

03:48:17.080 --> 03:48:22.560
[Guest]: sorting is that, that what is government? OK, if you take a step back, what is government

03:48:22.560 --> 03:48:29.400
[Guest]: is, government is meant to be a vehicle for expressing our collective desires on kind

03:48:29.400 --> 03:48:34.600
[Guest]: of taxation and a bundle of public goods, correct? So, and different people will have

03:48:34.600 --> 03:48:39.800
[Guest]: different preferences, right? Some would say, OK, I'm happy to pay a 40% tax if the government

03:48:39.800 --> 03:48:42.680
[Guest]: is going to give me a whole bunch of these things. Others might say, no, I only want

03:48:42.680 --> 03:48:47.360
[Guest]: 10% tax. You just provide law and order and the rest will take care of. OK, now, the logic

03:48:47.360 --> 03:48:53.520
[Guest]: of the tibu sorting is that by allowing local jurisdictions to set their own bundles of

03:48:53.520 --> 03:49:00.480
[Guest]: taxation and public goods, you are also, it's not just competition, but you're accommodating

03:49:00.480 --> 03:49:04.760
[Guest]: diversity and preferences, right? Like, you know, by giving people a chance to not saying

03:49:04.760 --> 03:49:09.560
[Guest]: this is better than that on average, this is better for me. I want this and I want that.

03:49:09.560 --> 03:49:13.880
[Guest]: But I think, frankly, in India, we're very, very, very far from that. And see, the problem

03:49:13.880 --> 03:49:19.440
[Guest]: is to make that model work, you need a model of revenue collection that is differentiated

03:49:19.440 --> 03:49:24.840
[Guest]: by space, OK? And because most of our revenue collection is not differentiated by space,

03:49:24.840 --> 03:49:29.160
[Guest]: right? Because whether it's income tax or whether it's GST, these are all kind of doesn't

03:49:29.160 --> 03:49:33.840
[Guest]: matter where you are right now. But that kind of gets me to one, I think, very, very important

03:49:33.840 --> 03:49:38.960
[Guest]: area of reform, which I think is key to strengthen local governments, and that is strengthening

03:49:38.960 --> 03:49:43.520
[Guest]: property taxes. OK, so this will show up again in Chapter 7, right, when I talk about revenue.

03:49:43.520 --> 03:49:49.040
[Guest]: Because the reason property taxes are so important is it's important for multiple reasons, right?

03:49:49.040 --> 03:49:56.000
[Guest]: See, I think one of the key problems in taxation in India is that the fiscal compact between

03:49:56.000 --> 03:50:00.820
[Guest]: the taxpayer and the government is broken, OK, which is the fiscal compact is I pay taxes

03:50:00.820 --> 03:50:05.200
[Guest]: and expect services in return. But where we are today is I pay taxes, the services are

03:50:05.200 --> 03:50:09.760
[Guest]: so bad, I go to the private sector. So therefore, I'm double paying both the taxes and paying

03:50:09.760 --> 03:50:14.400
[Guest]: out of my pocket. And therefore, tax evasion is almost kind of morally justified, right?

03:50:14.400 --> 03:50:18.800
[Guest]: I mean, that people kind of justify their mind, OK, why am I paying taxes? OK, so there

03:50:18.800 --> 03:50:24.080
[Guest]: is a lot of evidence on what's called tax morale, OK, which is what kind of increases

03:50:24.080 --> 03:50:29.880
[Guest]: voluntary tax compliance. And a big part of tax morale is people kind of two things. One

03:50:29.880 --> 03:50:35.240
[Guest]: is seeing a visible link between your taxation and the services you're receiving. And second

03:50:35.240 --> 03:50:40.800
[Guest]: is having a say in how those taxes are spent. OK, and so therefore, if you want to raise

03:50:40.800 --> 03:50:45.680
[Guest]: taxes in India, like I get very nervous. In fact, I say this very clearly, there's a reason

03:50:45.680 --> 03:50:50.320
[Guest]: my revenue chapter comes after expenditure, because, you know, a government that spends

03:50:50.320 --> 03:50:54.720
[Guest]: money badly loses moral authority to collect taxes. OK, so that's why I first want to improve

03:50:54.720 --> 03:50:58.600
[Guest]: efficiency of expenditure before you raise more taxes. But that being said, you know,

03:50:58.600 --> 03:51:02.280
[Guest]: there is no question we need better urban public infrastructure, we need a whole bunch,

03:51:02.280 --> 03:51:06.800
[Guest]: we need the revenue for these things. OK, but the value of more property taxes, it has

03:51:06.800 --> 03:51:13.360
[Guest]: many, many benefits, right? So the first is that actually, if done well, you can create

03:51:13.360 --> 03:51:19.960
[Guest]: a self-sustaining virtuous cycle, right, whereby if the tax revenue is providing local public

03:51:19.960 --> 03:51:25.800
[Guest]: goods, right, of a certain quality, then that can actually improve the local housing prices

03:51:25.800 --> 03:51:31.040
[Guest]: to capitalise the quality of the public goods, which then increases that and increases the

03:51:31.040 --> 03:51:34.840
[Guest]: tax revenue, right? So you get into a virtuous cycle of public good provision, because again,

03:51:34.840 --> 03:51:39.800
[Guest]: what is the core economics of public finance? The core economics is that if I take taxpayer

03:51:39.800 --> 03:51:44.160
[Guest]: money, I should spend it on things that have a higher ROI, right, I mean, than the money

03:51:44.160 --> 03:51:49.360
[Guest]: I'm spending. And if it has a higher ROI, say, in the case of public goods, that higher

03:51:49.360 --> 03:51:52.800
[Guest]: return on investment is capitalised in the property prices. So there's a lot of research

03:51:52.800 --> 03:51:57.440
[Guest]: in the US, for example, showing how if you invest in better schools, right, I mean, through

03:51:57.440 --> 03:52:01.920
[Guest]: issuing school bonds, then that kind of is reflected in the property prices that then

03:52:01.920 --> 03:52:06.040
[Guest]: kind of more than pays for the bond. Okay, so that's why it's a positive ROI investment.

03:52:06.040 --> 03:52:09.560
[Guest]: Now coming therefore, to how do you, so that's one reason for why I think property taxes

03:52:09.560 --> 03:52:13.680
[Guest]: make more sense, because you create a bit of a virtuous cycle between kind of local

03:52:13.680 --> 03:52:19.360
[Guest]: service delivery and kind of the underlying value of the asset. The second reason is politically,

03:52:19.360 --> 03:52:23.600
[Guest]: it is kind of, there's a tighter link between the tax and the services, because it's not

03:52:23.600 --> 03:52:26.800
[Guest]: going into very, very far away government of India, or even the state government, it's

03:52:26.800 --> 03:52:30.600
[Guest]: going to your local government. And therefore, you see how it comes back to you in terms

03:52:30.600 --> 03:52:36.560
[Guest]: of services. And the third is that it also kind of helps with the federalism point, which

03:52:36.560 --> 03:52:41.400
[Guest]: is that the key challenge today for local government is local government has zero or

03:52:41.400 --> 03:52:45.320
[Guest]: very little revenue raising capacity, right. So they're dependent on the goodwill and the

03:52:45.320 --> 03:52:49.480
[Guest]: transfers that come from higher levels of government. But the, and that's why at least

03:52:49.480 --> 03:52:53.320
[Guest]: in urban areas, right, I mean, if you're able to strengthen kind of property taxation, that

03:52:53.320 --> 03:52:57.600
[Guest]: gives you a virtuous cycle of also strengthening federalism. Because, see, one of the reasons

03:52:57.600 --> 03:53:01.440
[Guest]: state governments are not bothered so much about property taxes is they see this as humko

03:53:01.440 --> 03:53:05.160
[Guest]: kya fayada, right? I actually talked to an advisor to chief minister said, ha ha, this

03:53:05.160 --> 03:53:08.320
[Guest]: is good, but it doesn't help the state government finances. I'm like, boss, you know, that's

03:53:08.320 --> 03:53:12.280
[Guest]: very, very short sighted, because A, you are responsible for welfare of your people. And

03:53:12.280 --> 03:53:16.540
[Guest]: if there are investments the state government can make that increase the capacity of local

03:53:16.540 --> 03:53:20.920
[Guest]: governments to raise property taxes efficiently, that's good for welfare. But it's also good

03:53:20.920 --> 03:53:25.520
[Guest]: for the state, because you create this positive cycle of increased economic activity that

03:53:25.520 --> 03:53:29.480
[Guest]: translates into higher GST and other revenue for the state. So you know, overall, it makes

03:53:29.480 --> 03:53:34.520
[Guest]: sense for states to invest purely from a fiscal perspective in the revenue raising capacity

03:53:34.520 --> 03:53:38.320
[Guest]: of local government. So just to give you a sense of perspective, India's total property

03:53:38.320 --> 03:53:43.360
[Guest]: tax to GDP is under point is around point 1%, okay, point 1 to point 1.5. I think in

03:53:43.360 --> 03:53:48.600
[Guest]: France, it's about 3%. Okay, so it's about 25x or 30x. So that gives you a sense of how

03:53:48.600 --> 03:53:53.480
[Guest]: far behind we are, where the feasible frontier is. And that's the kind of investment, again,

03:53:53.480 --> 03:53:57.160
[Guest]: these are very concrete, implementable reforms, okay. And these are some of the things we're

03:53:57.160 --> 03:54:02.040
[Guest]: working on. And see, just is that these are immediate things that will both increase fiscal

03:54:02.040 --> 03:54:07.560
[Guest]: capacity and increase kind of effective federalism, because the local government now has the revenue

03:54:07.560 --> 03:54:12.080
[Guest]: on which to act. So as an aside, it's a very nice research paper again. So I keep getting

03:54:12.080 --> 03:54:15.480
[Guest]: excited about, I see I make connections, both to papers and podcasts, right. So there's

03:54:15.480 --> 03:54:20.000
[Guest]: a very nice study in China, okay, that even though China is kind of centralized party

03:54:20.000 --> 03:54:24.120
[Guest]: rule and stuff like that, China did have a period of experimenting with village level

03:54:24.120 --> 03:54:29.780
[Guest]: elections, okay. And the logic was that to have at least local representatives, along

03:54:29.780 --> 03:54:34.480
[Guest]: with the party secretary having a say in kind of what local projects were done. And one

03:54:34.480 --> 03:54:39.120
[Guest]: of the most interesting results in the paper was that the local elections led to an increase

03:54:39.120 --> 03:54:43.800
[Guest]: in people's willingness to pay taxes, okay. And that's because you're more willing to

03:54:43.800 --> 03:54:48.840
[Guest]: pay tax if you have a say in how that tax is spent, okay. So anyway, so all I'm saying

03:54:48.840 --> 03:54:54.680
[Guest]: is that part of the chicken and egg of our decentralization discourse in India, is because

03:54:54.680 --> 03:54:58.760
[Guest]: of this chicken and egg of how do I decentralize when there's no capacity, and it all depends

03:54:58.760 --> 03:55:03.720
[Guest]: on kind of the higher level largesse, okay, as opposed to building systems that make it

03:55:03.720 --> 03:55:07.960
[Guest]: sustainable for there to be more effective local governance, the property tax agenda

03:55:07.960 --> 03:55:11.840
[Guest]: becomes I think, a very, very important part of that state capacity that also strengthens

03:55:11.840 --> 03:55:16.880
[Amit Varma]: federalism. Yeah, the China experiment is fascinating. I'm going to go on a mini tax

03:55:16.880 --> 03:55:21.600
[Amit Varma]: rant here, because I think taxes are one of the things that we have normalized. Look,

03:55:21.600 --> 03:55:26.740
[Amit Varma]: here's the thing. The thing is that let's say that I pay 30% of my income every year

03:55:26.740 --> 03:55:31.720
[Amit Varma]: through taxes. So actually, I happen to pay more because 18% GST plus, which I can't offset

03:55:31.720 --> 03:55:36.160
[Amit Varma]: against anything plus more than 30% income tax, almost half my income goes in taxes,

03:55:36.160 --> 03:55:41.680
[Amit Varma]: a common rent. But just take a common citizen. And let's say a common citizen is paying 30%,

03:55:41.680 --> 03:55:45.600
[Amit Varma]: one third of their income in taxes every year, direct plus indirect, because after all, everybody

03:55:45.600 --> 03:55:49.520
[Amit Varma]: pays taxes, not just income taxpayers. Let's say your total is 33%.

03:55:49.520 --> 03:55:56.680
[Guest]: Very quickly, India's overall tax to GDP ratio is only 18%. And that's because only 5% pay

03:55:56.680 --> 03:56:02.080
[Guest]: income tax, right? So the bulk of people are paying the indirect taxes. And so GST will

03:56:02.080 --> 03:56:04.680
[Guest]: end up being about 12. Yeah, anyway, so yeah.

03:56:04.680 --> 03:56:08.480
[Amit Varma]: See you're spoiling the rhythm of my rant. If you were singing Antakshari, I would not

03:56:08.480 --> 03:56:13.480
[Amit Varma]: cut in the middle of a song and let me tell you where this mukhra came from.

03:56:13.480 --> 03:56:19.440
[Amit Varma]: Okay, yeah. So here's the deal. If you're paying 33% of your income as tax, that basically

03:56:19.440 --> 03:56:24.240
[Amit Varma]: means that for four months of the year, let's say January to April, you are a slave of the

03:56:24.240 --> 03:56:27.880
[Amit Varma]: government, you're working for the government without actually wanting to. So taxation is

03:56:27.880 --> 03:56:32.200
[Amit Varma]: effectively part time slavery, which is a correct characterization. That is what it

03:56:32.200 --> 03:56:35.680
[Amit Varma]: is without wanting to you're working for the government, all your income goes there for

03:56:35.680 --> 03:56:40.400
[Amit Varma]: those four months. Now, this is fine, right? This is fine, because we need a state to survive,

03:56:40.400 --> 03:56:45.000
[Amit Varma]: we need a state to protect our rights, etc, etc. We all agree upon this, I think ideologies

03:56:45.000 --> 03:56:48.720
[Amit Varma]: really differ only on how much of this is justified, but we all agree that a state is

03:56:48.720 --> 03:56:54.080
[Amit Varma]: justified. Now, what happens in India often is that most people they look around and they

03:56:54.080 --> 03:56:57.960
[Amit Varma]: don't see bang for the buck, like you pointed out. And this is not by the way, an excuse

03:56:57.960 --> 03:57:03.960
[Amit Varma]: for evading taxes, I pay my taxes scrupulously. You know, and in fact, it's a matter of principle

03:57:03.960 --> 03:57:08.960
[Amit Varma]: for me to do so because as long as I'm a citizen here, I want to, you know, I otherwise I can't

03:57:08.960 --> 03:57:13.440
[Amit Varma]: raise my voice if I don't also pay the taxes that gives me the right to do so. However,

03:57:13.440 --> 03:57:18.480
[Amit Varma]: the point is that it has reached a stage in the modern time where you earlier one would

03:57:18.480 --> 03:57:22.720
[Amit Varma]: look around and see all this money being basically wasted. Today, one looks around and see that

03:57:22.720 --> 03:57:27.280
[Amit Varma]: this money is being used for bulldozers, and giant statues, and all of these things which

03:57:27.280 --> 03:57:32.000
[Amit Varma]: I think are very toxic. So it is actually, you know, a question I'll throw to my listeners,

03:57:32.000 --> 03:57:35.920
[Amit Varma]: that in this day and age, when you see what the state is doing with your money, is it

03:57:35.920 --> 03:57:40.880
[Amit Varma]: moral to even pay taxes? And to this, my answer would not be to evade my taxes, evade your

03:57:40.880 --> 03:57:46.040
[Amit Varma]: taxes rather, why would you evade my taxes unless you're me. But I think those who have

03:57:46.040 --> 03:57:50.800
[Amit Varma]: the means would probably then leave, it would be logical, you know, you don't want to fund

03:57:50.800 --> 03:57:55.560
[Amit Varma]: so many things that you actively disapprove of, because some of it is not incompetence,

03:57:55.560 --> 03:58:01.000
[Amit Varma]: some of it is just malice directed towards your fellow citizens. So that's just one random

03:58:01.000 --> 03:58:05.600
[Amit Varma]: rant I'll throw out. But I would say that, you know, like those people in China, I would

03:58:05.600 --> 03:58:12.520
[Amit Varma]: be far happier to pay my taxes, if I could actually see that they were being used properly,

03:58:12.520 --> 03:58:19.080
[Amit Varma]: if they were more local, if I could see that the police is actually active, it is safe

03:58:19.080 --> 03:58:24.040
[Amit Varma]: to walk around at night, that women are not getting EVE teased, and so on and so forth.

03:58:24.040 --> 03:58:28.820
[Amit Varma]: I would feel much more for it, except that part of the reason of the apathy of the Indian

03:58:28.820 --> 03:58:33.280
[Amit Varma]: citizen is that they don't see this connection at all. And luckily, for the state, we've

03:58:33.280 --> 03:58:37.600
[Amit Varma]: normalized taxes. Otherwise, if people realize they are part time slaves, I think there would

03:58:37.600 --> 03:58:44.000
[Amit Varma]: be mass rebellion, but we've normalized this shit. But that is my little rant. That aside,

03:58:44.000 --> 03:58:48.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, everything you said is illuminating. I almost feel like I've read chapter seven

03:58:48.400 --> 03:58:52.240
[Amit Varma]: on revenue, even though you haven't sent it to me yet.

03:58:52.240 --> 03:58:59.960
[Guest]: I'm just scratching the surface of ideas in each of these chapters. Yeah, anyway, so I'm

03:58:59.960 --> 03:59:04.560
[Guest]: hopefully providing some alibi for why this book is taking time. But, you know, thank

03:59:04.560 --> 03:59:08.160
[Guest]: you so much for having me on the show once a year, because it's also kind of, I think

03:59:08.160 --> 03:59:13.160
[Guest]: it's a sneaky artist, right, who said, Nishant, see, I remember people now by their hand handles.

03:59:13.160 --> 03:59:20.400
[Guest]: But I did the same with Bhagavan and Anirban last time, you know, but I think he said,

03:59:20.400 --> 03:59:23.520
[Guest]: right, I mean, that as a writer, the hardest thing is like, you know, how long it takes

03:59:23.520 --> 03:59:26.760
[Guest]: you to get feedback, and therefore the value of serializing things and stuff like that.

03:59:26.760 --> 03:59:31.800
[Guest]: So you know, these episodes and stuff are very, very useful for me as a source of intermediate

03:59:31.800 --> 03:59:36.400
[Guest]: validation that chalo, there's something sensible going on here. But you know, hopefully, we're

03:59:36.400 --> 03:59:39.640
[Guest]: close to the finish line. And this guy should be out soon.

03:59:39.640 --> 03:59:45.200
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I would be happy for you to stay forever. But maybe you're thinking like that. But yeah,

03:59:45.200 --> 03:59:50.520
[Amit Varma]: so after sort of, you know, having given me all these insights on federalism, we've spoken

03:59:50.520 --> 03:59:55.680
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, why it is desirable, we've spoken about what are the tensions that come

03:59:55.680 --> 04:00:00.400
[Amit Varma]: in the way we've spoken about the Indian context, how that affected the design, the structure

04:00:00.400 --> 04:00:05.160
[Amit Varma]: of our state in the sense that we are so centralized, what we need to do to change. Now, let's sort

04:00:05.160 --> 04:00:09.960
[Amit Varma]: of get to the brass tacks of it. You have a section where you talk about implementable

04:00:09.960 --> 04:00:15.880
[Amit Varma]: reform ideas. And I find that title itself extremely interesting, because it's not reform

04:00:15.880 --> 04:00:23.040
[Amit Varma]: ideas, it's implementable reform ideas. So tell me a bit about these ideas, firstly,

04:00:23.040 --> 04:00:29.080
[Amit Varma]: but also perhaps before that, how optimistic are you about them being implementable? Because,

04:00:29.080 --> 04:00:32.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, before this conversation, I would have been fairly pessimistic. And I would

04:00:32.440 --> 04:00:36.280
[Amit Varma]: have said, look at the incentives, why would those in power give up power, so on and so

04:00:36.280 --> 04:00:40.320
[Amit Varma]: forth. But at the same time, what you've pointed out is that a lot of people within the system

04:00:40.320 --> 04:00:44.760
[Amit Varma]: want the system to change, not because of their own individual considerations, but because

04:00:44.760 --> 04:00:50.080
[Amit Varma]: they just want to, you know, they see the benefit that there would be for the people

04:00:50.080 --> 04:00:53.800
[Amit Varma]: at large in the country at large from it changing. And I totally buy that, because I know so

04:00:53.800 --> 04:00:58.360
[Amit Varma]: many such people who are within the government who understand that things need to change,

04:00:58.360 --> 04:01:03.440
[Amit Varma]: who would be grateful for a blueprint and therefore will be grateful to read your book,

04:01:03.440 --> 04:01:07.680
[Amit Varma]: it will now, you know, circulate in brown paper packets in government departments. I

04:01:07.680 --> 04:01:15.360
[Amit Varma]: sincerely hope so, because who will be caught reading it openly? So tell me about why you're

04:01:15.360 --> 04:01:21.120
[Amit Varma]: confident of, how confident are you of these changes actually being implemented? And also

04:01:21.120 --> 04:01:25.120
[Amit Varma]: tell me more about each of these changes, because there's so much to dive into over

04:01:25.120 --> 04:01:26.120
[Guest]: there.

04:01:26.120 --> 04:01:29.160
[Guest]: Yeah. And again, you know, I think that there's a very, very broad list here. But you know,

04:01:29.160 --> 04:01:35.040
[Guest]: so one thing I talk about is just, so I break this into things that can happen at the government

04:01:35.040 --> 04:01:38.600
[Guest]: of India level, like, you know, and things that can happen at the state level, right.

04:01:38.600 --> 04:01:42.320
[Guest]: So at the all India level, I would say, you know, there are two or three things. One is

04:01:42.320 --> 04:01:47.720
[Guest]: I think there is a case potentially over time, without being very specific of considering

04:01:47.720 --> 04:01:53.600
[Guest]: the case for smaller states, okay. And I think the data suggests that the MP Chhattisgarh,

04:01:53.600 --> 04:01:58.640
[Guest]: the Bihar Jharkhand, the UP Uttarakhand, and recently even AP Telangana have all kind of,

04:01:58.640 --> 04:02:02.760
[Guest]: you know, benefited just by kind of making the benefited governance and development outcomes

04:02:02.760 --> 04:02:07.440
[Guest]: by and this is not unambiguous, like Jharkhand, I think regressed a little bit because it

04:02:07.440 --> 04:02:13.400
[Guest]: had your classic resource curse kind of problem. Okay. But over time, I think the data suggests

04:02:13.400 --> 04:02:17.280
[Guest]: that that's been positive, I think an even stronger piece of research and evidence comes

04:02:17.280 --> 04:02:22.680
[Guest]: from. So there's this ongoing study we have where, you know, we're looking at this very

04:02:22.680 --> 04:02:26.840
[Guest]: important governance reform that happened in under N. T. Ramarao in Andhra Pradesh in

04:02:26.840 --> 04:02:32.640
[Guest]: the mid 80s, where one of his big governance reforms was kind of, and AP and Telangana

04:02:32.640 --> 04:02:37.560
[Guest]: are still very, very unique on this, was kind of going from blocks to mandals. Okay, so

04:02:37.560 --> 04:02:41.760
[Guest]: effectively, a block in India today, the average district is about 2 million people, and then

04:02:41.760 --> 04:02:46.640
[Guest]: you have blocks of about 200 to 250,000. Right. But what they did was they went down to mandals

04:02:46.640 --> 04:02:51.900
[Guest]: and thereby quadrupled the number of sub districts. Okay, so that went down to the average population

04:02:51.900 --> 04:02:57.760
[Guest]: in a mandal is about 60 to 75,000, as opposed to 200 to 250,000. And so what that does,

04:02:57.760 --> 04:03:01.600
[Guest]: is it basically brings government closer to the people. Okay, so there's an element both

04:03:01.600 --> 04:03:06.200
[Guest]: of administrative decentralization and an element of political decentralization, because

04:03:06.200 --> 04:03:12.400
[Guest]: your block parishad now becomes a mandal parishad, which is therefore closer to the people, right.

04:03:12.400 --> 04:03:16.080
[Guest]: So, and there we've got kind of, we've been working on this for some time, put together

04:03:16.080 --> 04:03:19.640
[Guest]: a whole bunch of data and development indicators. And you can look at kind of the distance to

04:03:19.640 --> 04:03:23.280
[Guest]: the border and distance to capital. So you can have two places that are otherwise identical,

04:03:23.280 --> 04:03:28.280
[Guest]: where the distance to the block capital has now changed. And what we're able to document

04:03:28.280 --> 04:03:34.320
[Guest]: over time is that there is a significant acceleration in the development indicators in places that

04:03:34.320 --> 04:03:39.240
[Guest]: became closer. And therefore, it kind of there is empirical evidence now broadly pointing

04:03:39.240 --> 04:03:43.320
[Guest]: towards the value of bringing government closer to the people. Okay, so and you can do that

04:03:43.320 --> 04:03:49.080
[Guest]: two ways. One is you can take the powers of an existing level of government and bring

04:03:49.080 --> 04:03:54.720
[Guest]: that level itself closer, which is what happened in blocks to mandals. Or you can say, let's

04:03:54.720 --> 04:03:59.480
[Guest]: take an existing disempowered level of local government and give it more power. Okay, so

04:03:59.480 --> 04:04:04.080
[Guest]: I think in both of these cases, whether it's kind of smaller states or smaller districts,

04:04:04.080 --> 04:04:07.520
[Guest]: right, I mean, there is a case for thinking about it seriously, because the population

04:04:07.520 --> 04:04:11.160
[Guest]: has been growing, and the capacity is not kept up. Okay, so that's one simple thing.

04:04:11.160 --> 04:04:16.520
[Guest]: I think the second thing is in terms of again, the government of India level is kind of really,

04:04:16.520 --> 04:04:20.720
[Guest]: you know, modifying and rethinking centrally sponsored schemes, right? I mean, and it's

04:04:20.720 --> 04:04:24.720
[Guest]: not just a question. It's not just a question of getting rid of them and spending the budgets.

04:04:24.720 --> 04:04:28.560
[Guest]: There are very good reasons for centrally sponsored schemes, right, including kind of

04:04:28.560 --> 04:04:32.280
[Guest]: sometimes from an equity perspective, the money that comes from the centrally sponsored

04:04:32.280 --> 04:04:36.600
[Guest]: scheme becomes the most important way for a state to finance even its basic kind of

04:04:36.600 --> 04:04:40.800
[Guest]: operations. Okay, so, like Maharashtra GDP per capita is five times higher than Bihar.

04:04:40.800 --> 04:04:44.200
[Guest]: Okay, so left to its own resources, Bihar simply wouldn't be able to fund an education

04:04:44.200 --> 04:04:48.840
[Guest]: system. Okay, so that way, the centrally sponsored scheme plays a very important role. The problem

04:04:48.840 --> 04:04:53.680
[Guest]: is not in terms of the resource allocation. The problem is how rigid the guidelines are,

04:04:53.680 --> 04:04:57.840
[Guest]: okay, with regard to how the money has to be spent. And so that has again, like three

04:04:57.840 --> 04:05:02.680
[Guest]: or four problems, right? So one is the one size fit all nature of it, right? So Kerala

04:05:02.680 --> 04:05:06.520
[Guest]: might need high schools and colleges, Bihar might still need some elementary schools,

04:05:06.520 --> 04:05:11.080
[Guest]: but your national program kind of now over time as SSA became Samagrashiksha Abhiyan,

04:05:11.080 --> 04:05:15.120
[Guest]: there is a bit more flexibility, but still, like, you know, mota moti, like, I mean, there

04:05:15.120 --> 04:05:20.120
[Guest]: are tight kind of guidelines which restrict the flexibility across states. The second

04:05:20.120 --> 04:05:25.720
[Guest]: problem is that because the centrally sponsored schemes have a co-financing model, where the

04:05:25.720 --> 04:05:31.720
[Guest]: states have to put in, say, 50%, in some cases, it's 50-50, is not only are you constraining

04:05:31.720 --> 04:05:36.240
[Guest]: the use of Government of India money, you're also constraining the state's own budget by

04:05:36.240 --> 04:05:41.800
[Guest]: saying that the matching funds have to be sent along these lines. Okay, so that's another

04:05:41.800 --> 04:05:46.560
[Guest]: source of kind of infringing on state level autonomy. I think there is a third dimension

04:05:46.560 --> 04:05:51.120
[Guest]: of this, which is just an incredible amount of micromanaging, going back to process level

04:05:51.120 --> 04:05:55.440
[Guest]: kind of, you know, micromanaging. And a senior advisor, Nitya Yog once told me that, you

04:05:55.440 --> 04:05:58.840
[Guest]: know, in the health department under National Health Mission, that every year, there's what

04:05:58.840 --> 04:06:02.880
[Guest]: is called a PIP, I think, Project Implementation Plan or something, under which there are 1500

04:06:02.880 --> 04:06:07.920
[Guest]: permitted line items. So every year, every state has to submit this PIP that has to be

04:06:07.920 --> 04:06:12.440
[Guest]: reviewed and approved. So if you just think about the paperwork of 1500 line items times

04:06:12.440 --> 04:06:18.000
[Guest]: 28 states, so in the end, it just employs an army of consultants on one side to make

04:06:18.000 --> 04:06:21.640
[Guest]: the reports, an army of consultants on the other side to read them, but nothing substantively

04:06:21.640 --> 04:06:26.440
[Guest]: actually happens as a result of that, right? So it's just incredibly inefficient, because

04:06:26.440 --> 04:06:29.600
[Guest]: you don't trust them, because you micromanage and saying, yeh karna, yeh karna, yeh karna,

04:06:29.600 --> 04:06:33.360
[Guest]: yeh aapko report karna hai, right? So that's a third cost. And a fourth cost is, frankly,

04:06:33.360 --> 04:06:37.920
[Guest]: over time, and I mentioned this, I think, in the education episode, it has led to a

04:06:37.920 --> 04:06:44.720
[Guest]: substantial weakening of policymaking muscles and capacity at the state level, okay, which

04:06:44.720 --> 04:06:49.600
[Guest]: is essentially if, if, because and remember what I said, I said, states are bigger than

04:06:49.600 --> 04:06:54.600
[Guest]: most countries, right? So you really should have the policymaking capacity to think about

04:06:54.600 --> 04:06:58.680
[Guest]: your local problems and craft your local solutions. The problem today is if you're a principal

04:06:58.680 --> 04:07:02.720
[Guest]: secretary or commissioner who wants to do something innovative in the state, you are

04:07:02.720 --> 04:07:08.040
[Guest]: much more likely to do it if it is consistent with central government guidelines, because

04:07:08.040 --> 04:07:12.400
[Guest]: then you can use that money. Whereas if you have to do something outside the guidelines,

04:07:12.400 --> 04:07:16.680
[Guest]: then you have to argue with your finance department, right? You need to get the money and that

04:07:16.680 --> 04:07:21.760
[Guest]: is a much more complex process. Okay, so what has happened, therefore, is that while the

04:07:21.760 --> 04:07:25.120
[Guest]: centrally sponsored schemes have created the budgetary space for the social sector, they

04:07:25.120 --> 04:07:29.920
[Guest]: have also had come at severe cost. So, so one of the very, very concrete reform ideas

04:07:29.920 --> 04:07:35.240
[Guest]: which I have is again going back to this idea of, you know, autonomy and process and accountability

04:07:35.240 --> 04:07:40.480
[Guest]: for outcomes, okay, so whereby it's not just, in a way, the government of India faces exactly

04:07:40.480 --> 04:07:44.600
[Guest]: the same problem, say, that a World Bank faces when it's doing development aid, okay, which

04:07:44.600 --> 04:07:49.840
[Guest]: is you want to give money to the places that need it, okay, but the places that need it

04:07:49.840 --> 04:07:55.720
[Guest]: are also the poorest, most poorly governed, okay. And so, in a way, you put in all of

04:07:55.720 --> 04:08:00.800
[Guest]: these conditions, because of the poor governance in the places that need it the most, but that

04:08:00.800 --> 04:08:05.040
[Guest]: also ends up biting the better off states that are well governed, and frankly, don't

04:08:05.040 --> 04:08:10.040
[Guest]: need your interventions, okay. So, you know, one intermediate level might just be performance

04:08:10.040 --> 04:08:15.760
[Guest]: based autonomy, okay, forget performance based financing, but just performance based autonomy

04:08:15.760 --> 04:08:19.040
[Guest]: that says, I mean, frankly, today, a government of Tamil Nadu or Kerala will say, what do

04:08:19.040 --> 04:08:21.920
[Guest]: we have to learn from government of India on education, we're doing better on all of

04:08:21.920 --> 04:08:25.760
[Guest]: these indicators, right, like, I mean, so, for the states that are doing better, at least,

04:08:25.760 --> 04:08:29.360
[Guest]: right, I mean, you might say, here is money with fewer conditions and just report, right,

04:08:29.360 --> 04:08:34.120
[Guest]: you still have to report, but there is a lot that can be done. Now, of course, eventually,

04:08:34.120 --> 04:08:38.400
[Guest]: I think having an element of performance based funding, again, going back to 172010, right,

04:08:38.400 --> 04:08:42.160
[Guest]: that says, you know, here's government money, we're going to allocate this certain amount

04:08:42.160 --> 04:08:47.120
[Guest]: equally by child, a certain amount, an additional amount for underperforming or backward states

04:08:47.120 --> 04:08:51.360
[Guest]: that just allows them to build those gaps, and 10% on performance, right, so that there

04:08:51.360 --> 04:08:54.480
[Guest]: is skin in the game for everybody to kind of innovate on delivering, right. So, those

04:08:54.480 --> 04:08:58.600
[Guest]: would be kind of some of the reform ideas at the central level. So, you know, things

04:08:58.600 --> 04:09:02.520
[Guest]: and then there is a third core reform idea at the central level, which draws on this

04:09:02.520 --> 04:09:07.200
[Guest]: business standard article I wrote in 2011, which really is and the good news is more

04:09:07.200 --> 04:09:11.360
[Guest]: of this is happening, okay, more of this is happening, but it's to really unleash the

04:09:11.360 --> 04:09:17.160
[Guest]: states in terms of policy experimentation, okay. So, when we think about, you know, very

04:09:17.160 --> 04:09:21.720
[Guest]: contentious issues like land reform or labour reform, things like that, you know, trying

04:09:21.720 --> 04:09:24.600
[Guest]: to do this at the Government of India level is just too difficult, right, because there

04:09:24.600 --> 04:09:29.280
[Guest]: are multiple veto players, it's too risky, but you just say, listen, let states innovate

04:09:29.280 --> 04:09:33.920
[Guest]: and experiment. But remember, many of these issues are in the concurrent list, okay. So,

04:09:33.920 --> 04:09:38.080
[Guest]: the Government of India rules will still override the state government rules. So, for the state

04:09:38.080 --> 04:09:42.520
[Guest]: government rules to take primacy within the state still requires presidential assent.

04:09:42.520 --> 04:09:47.400
[Guest]: So, there is a provision for that, but Government of India can encourage a lot more state level

04:09:47.400 --> 04:09:52.320
[Guest]: policy innovation in the concurrent list by kind of indicating that if you kind of provide

04:09:52.320 --> 04:09:56.640
[Guest]: a very clear rationale for this, right, then we will be more willing to kind of support

04:09:56.640 --> 04:10:00.840
[Guest]: this for presidential assent, okay. So, those would be kind of concrete things that can

04:10:00.840 --> 04:10:04.720
[Guest]: happen at the Government of India level. Then there's a lot more things that need to happen

04:10:04.720 --> 04:10:08.920
[Guest]: at the state level, right. And so, one of the things there is this business, the nuanced

04:10:08.920 --> 04:10:12.600
[Guest]: decentralisation I talked about, because that's completely within the limit of a state government,

04:10:12.600 --> 04:10:15.440
[Guest]: right, because you control the people, you control the budgets, and so it's about how

04:10:15.440 --> 04:10:20.080
[Guest]: much am I empowering local governments. Similarly, investing in property tax capacity is something

04:10:20.080 --> 04:10:24.600
[Guest]: that a state government can do, right, I mean, that strengthens local government. And then,

04:10:24.600 --> 04:10:30.520
[Guest]: in some ways, the most radical reform would be kind of more empowered mayors, you know,

04:10:30.520 --> 04:10:36.000
[Guest]: which many people have talked about. Now, the interesting thing here is, one view, okay,

04:10:36.000 --> 04:10:41.200
[Guest]: is that chief ministers don't want to do this because it creates alternate power centres,

04:10:41.200 --> 04:10:46.360
[Guest]: right, which is a threat to them. So, just like in New York, in the state of New York,

04:10:46.360 --> 04:10:49.520
[Guest]: the mayor of New York is often more powerful than the governor of New York State who's

04:10:49.520 --> 04:10:53.680
[Guest]: sitting in Albany, but New York City is the cash cow, and that's where all the action

04:10:53.680 --> 04:10:58.320
[Guest]: is, right. Similarly, an empowered mayor of Mumbai would become a real threat to the chief

04:10:58.320 --> 04:11:02.760
[Guest]: minister of Maharashtra, in like Indonesia, you know, Jokowi became president of the country

04:11:02.760 --> 04:11:05.720
[Guest]: from mayor of Jakarta, right, like, you know, so that was kind of like a really important

04:11:05.720 --> 04:11:10.800
[Guest]: post and position. But here is a way why I think empowered mayors can be politically

04:11:10.800 --> 04:11:16.440
[Guest]: incentive compatible, right, which is one of the kind of design dysfunctions of our

04:11:16.440 --> 04:11:23.120
[Guest]: democracy right now is that we elect MLAs and MPs to be legislators, but their voters

04:11:23.120 --> 04:11:29.200
[Guest]: fundamentally see them as providing constituency services, okay. So, the voters are not evaluating

04:11:29.200 --> 04:11:34.360
[Guest]: them on did you pass good laws, the voters are evaluating them on did you make my life

04:11:34.360 --> 04:11:39.480
[Guest]: better, okay. So, part of the dysfunction of the system, why does an MLA or MP want

04:11:39.480 --> 04:11:44.400
[Guest]: the power to transfer people, because even though we call that political interference,

04:11:44.400 --> 04:11:48.480
[Guest]: the flip side of that is, it is the power to transfer that gives this guy any authority

04:11:48.480 --> 04:11:53.360
[Guest]: on the otherwise kind of, you know, indifferent official who may not listen, okay. So, in

04:11:53.360 --> 04:11:59.000
[Guest]: many ways, like, I mean, the MLA or MPs are kind of dealt a very, very difficult hand

04:11:59.000 --> 04:12:04.160
[Guest]: where they are expected to deliver constituency services without being given the means to

04:12:04.160 --> 04:12:08.240
[Guest]: do that, because all they have is this MP LAD, which is a minuscule amount of money

04:12:08.240 --> 04:12:13.880
[Guest]: compared to the actual budgets of the departments, right. So, what an empowered mayor does and

04:12:13.880 --> 04:12:18.560
[Guest]: why I hope there will be political demand for this, right, I mean, is that even if a

04:12:18.560 --> 04:12:23.000
[Guest]: chief minister is hesitant, like a bunch of MLAs themselves would prefer to be empowered

04:12:23.000 --> 04:12:28.480
[Guest]: mayors like, I mean, of their areas, where there is kind of alignment of accountability

04:12:28.480 --> 04:12:32.680
[Guest]: and what the voters are holding, you know. So, in a way, voters are holding them accountable

04:12:32.680 --> 04:12:36.360
[Guest]: for constituency services, but they don't have the means to deliver that. So, if you

04:12:36.360 --> 04:12:40.680
[Guest]: harmonize those things, it would also kind of, you know, strengthen our democracy by

04:12:40.680 --> 04:12:44.200
[Guest]: better aligning accountability with authority to deliver on that. So, again, this is the

04:12:44.200 --> 04:12:48.320
[Guest]: kind of thing, the good news is that there is nothing that prevents a chief minister

04:12:48.320 --> 04:12:52.720
[Guest]: from undertaking these reforms within their state, okay. So, and why I think the level

04:12:52.720 --> 04:12:56.720
[Guest]: at which we need to have these reform conversations is now, Government of India can kind of, you

04:12:56.720 --> 04:13:00.600
[Guest]: know, they can do a few things, like Finance Commission has put some incentives for states

04:13:00.600 --> 04:13:04.280
[Guest]: that increase their property taxes and stuff like that. And I think Finance Ministry has

04:13:04.280 --> 04:13:08.560
[Guest]: also done some of that, right. But fundamentally, this is a state level political action, okay.

04:13:08.560 --> 04:13:13.040
[Guest]: So, you know, all it takes is one chief minister. And it's actually quite interesting in my

04:13:13.040 --> 04:13:17.520
[Guest]: conversations on Tamil Nadu, right, for example, informally, they will say that Kerala has

04:13:17.520 --> 04:13:21.600
[Guest]: done much better than us in decentralization. And this is something that we should consider.

04:13:21.600 --> 04:13:26.640
[Guest]: So, I think, again, the desire and willingness to take up new ideas is there. I think the

04:13:26.640 --> 04:13:31.480
[Guest]: challenge is, how do you de-risk this? Okay, how do you de-risk this? Because nobody, even

04:13:31.480 --> 04:13:36.400
[Guest]: at a state level, tomorrow, see NTR, like going from districts to blocks to mandals

04:13:36.400 --> 04:13:40.840
[Guest]: is a big change, right, that happens across the state. So, even politicians who are well-meaning

04:13:40.840 --> 04:13:45.680
[Guest]: are often just risk-averse of trying to do something massive that is irreversible. So,

04:13:45.680 --> 04:13:49.640
[Guest]: one of the things which, you know, I briefly discussed, I mean, again, that's why each

04:13:49.640 --> 04:13:54.040
[Guest]: of these chapters can become an entire book, right, I mean, is to then see, are there kind

04:13:54.040 --> 04:13:59.680
[Guest]: of constitutional and legal mechanisms that allow some experiments to be done in a sub-region

04:13:59.680 --> 04:14:03.360
[Guest]: of the state, as opposed to kind of doing it for the whole state. So, then you might

04:14:03.360 --> 04:14:07.360
[Guest]: feel, okay, here's a couple of districts where I'm going to, or a couple of cities, or tier

04:14:07.360 --> 04:14:11.640
[Guest]: two cities, where we're going to experiment, you know, with more empowered mayors. So,

04:14:11.640 --> 04:14:17.640
[Guest]: I think, in each of these things, the question, and I'll come back to CJ's at the end, is

04:14:17.640 --> 04:14:23.840
[Guest]: that I, this is a broader meta-point I want to make, right, I mean, which is that part

04:14:23.840 --> 04:14:29.160
[Guest]: of the reason a lot of these changes don't happen is we're just not having the conversations

04:14:29.160 --> 04:14:34.100
[Guest]: across the different stakeholders in the system, okay. So, you know, and leave the politicians

04:14:34.100 --> 04:14:38.440
[Guest]: out for a moment, right, even just academia, industry, and bureaucracy, okay. So, when

04:14:38.440 --> 04:14:43.760
[Guest]: I look at, go to these policy conferences, there are so many low-hanging fruit of policy

04:14:43.760 --> 04:14:48.520
[Guest]: area, where better academic research and analysis can immediately improve outcomes, okay. The

04:14:48.520 --> 04:14:53.080
[Guest]: problem is that the academics have no patience for the bureaucrats, and the bureaucrats have

04:14:53.080 --> 04:14:56.680
[Guest]: no respect, saying the academics are sitting in the theoretical world, like, I mean, they

04:14:56.680 --> 04:15:01.080
[Guest]: are not working on problems we care about. And then industry thinks academics are too

04:15:01.080 --> 04:15:06.000
[Guest]: esoteric, and bureaucrats are too slow. So, but again, everybody has a stake, right, in

04:15:06.000 --> 04:15:10.920
[Guest]: moving this stuff together. Now, we do have certain fora of these conversations, you know,

04:15:10.920 --> 04:15:14.680
[Guest]: CII will, you know, get together, industry, government, whatever. But I think part of

04:15:14.680 --> 04:15:21.120
[Guest]: how we move forward is by marrying kind of a certain amount of conceptual clarity with

04:15:21.120 --> 04:15:25.520
[Guest]: a very real understanding of what are the risks of the reform, and thinking about ways

04:15:25.520 --> 04:15:31.040
[Guest]: of de-risking the reforms, okay, and accompany that with a certain amount of implementation

04:15:31.040 --> 04:15:36.840
[Guest]: support, which is partly why we're building CJIS, and then also accompany that with evaluation

04:15:36.840 --> 04:15:41.400
[Guest]: and research to say, like, you know, are the reforms working? So, in a way, like, if you

04:15:41.400 --> 04:15:46.560
[Guest]: look at the different parts of the production function of knowledge to action, right, there

04:15:46.560 --> 04:15:50.720
[Guest]: is kind of, there is deep research that says, okay, what is the impact of a specific policy?

04:15:50.720 --> 04:15:54.000
[Guest]: Then there's policy recommendations that say, based on all of this research, here are reforms

04:15:54.000 --> 04:15:59.720
[Guest]: we should do. Then there is kind of, you know, implementation support that says, if you want

04:15:59.720 --> 04:16:04.000
[Guest]: to do this, how do you actually make it happen? And then you need to close the loop back with

04:16:04.000 --> 04:16:07.800
[Guest]: research and evaluation to saying, ye hamne kiya hai, did this actually move us in the

04:16:07.800 --> 04:16:13.040
[Guest]: right direction? And if not, how do we course-correct quickly, right? So, yeah, so that's my long-winded

04:16:13.040 --> 04:16:17.720
[Guest]: way of kind of saying how I see us making progress on these things. And the good news,

04:16:17.720 --> 04:16:21.520
[Guest]: again, is that bilaterally, right, at the political level, at the bureaucratic level,

04:16:21.520 --> 04:16:25.680
[Guest]: the amount of support I see, I mean, there's property taxes, right? You say, oh, yes, ye

04:16:25.680 --> 04:16:30.400
[Guest]: karna hai humko. But the problem for your typical bureaucrat is they are just firefighting.

04:16:30.400 --> 04:16:34.800
[Guest]: I don't think any of us understands how much pressure, right, like, you know, say a principal

04:16:34.800 --> 04:16:38.160
[Guest]: secretary of finance is under, right? I mean, these are people controlling budgets of about

04:16:38.160 --> 04:16:43.080
[Guest]: 200,000 crores, and the sheer amount of pressure they are under, right, is just, you know,

04:16:43.080 --> 04:16:47.720
[Guest]: you're just constantly firefighting, right? Constantly firefighting. So, when you go in

04:16:47.720 --> 04:16:52.840
[Guest]: with kind of both a conceptual clarity and an implementation roadmap and some support,

04:16:52.840 --> 04:16:56.760
[Guest]: I'm seeing that people are actually very, very, very willing to listen. So, yeah, so

04:16:56.760 --> 04:16:58.680
[Guest]: we have to be optimistic and keep trying.

04:16:58.680 --> 04:17:04.000
[Amit Varma]: You've made me incredibly sympathetic towards a principal secretary of finance who's constantly

04:17:04.000 --> 04:17:07.200
[Amit Varma]: firefighting about what to do with 2000 crores. Man, what a problem.

04:17:07.200 --> 04:17:12.040
[Amit Varma]: It's a huge problem. It's a huge problem.

04:17:12.040 --> 04:17:16.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and, you know, I'm very excited with these ideas. As you can see, I'm swaying back

04:17:16.880 --> 04:17:21.200
[Amit Varma]: and forth in my chair, that could also be because the moment you said, everybody has

04:17:21.200 --> 04:17:26.280
[Amit Varma]: a stake, I felt hungry. So, you know, and just thinking aloud, you know, one way of

04:17:26.280 --> 04:17:30.840
[Amit Varma]: politicians becoming risk averse about politicians feeling that we can move ahead with this,

04:17:30.840 --> 04:17:34.320
[Amit Varma]: we know it's the right thing to do. But now we can actually do it is if there is a public

04:17:34.320 --> 04:17:40.120
[Amit Varma]: constituency for these ideas, like in a sense, we need public intellectuals like yourself

04:17:40.120 --> 04:17:44.360
[Amit Varma]: to be the Gandhi's of good ideas, right? And which is why I hope your book does really

04:17:44.360 --> 04:17:49.960
[Amit Varma]: well. And at some point, you know, maybe YouTube, we should brainstorm sometime because, you

04:17:49.960 --> 04:17:54.240
[Amit Varma]: know, I think, for real change to happen, you need to hit the demand end of the political

04:17:54.240 --> 04:18:00.720
[Amit Varma]: marketplace, the supply and can sometimes be a bit shaky. So, sort of last question

04:18:00.720 --> 04:18:06.360
[Amit Varma]: on federalism and these reforms until our next episode. The last question in this episode

04:18:06.360 --> 04:18:13.640
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, how you know, in percentage terms, because I think rather than say how

04:18:13.640 --> 04:18:17.840
[Amit Varma]: optimistic are you, you'll say, ha, I'm optimistic, so many people are good people, they won't

04:18:17.840 --> 04:18:24.000
[Amit Varma]: change. But if I ask you to put a number on it and say that, what is in percentages, what

04:18:24.000 --> 04:18:30.600
[Amit Varma]: is the chance that by 2030, you know, enough of these changes would have been implemented

04:18:30.600 --> 04:18:34.800
[Amit Varma]: for you to feel that there has been, you know, a meaningful progress, you know, what would

04:18:34.800 --> 04:18:39.280
[Amit Varma]: be that percentage chance? And frankly, honestly, even if it's 1%, I would still say it is worth

04:18:39.280 --> 04:18:43.640
[Amit Varma]: trying because the impact of that would be so massive, that it's, you know, positive

04:18:43.640 --> 04:18:48.160
[Amit Varma]: EV just to try for that. So, I'm not going to judge by percentage, I'm just, you know,

04:18:48.160 --> 04:18:51.400
[Amit Varma]: trying to get a sense of how likely you feel it is by asking you for a number.

04:18:51.400 --> 04:18:55.360
[Guest]: No, see, I think, I mean, so I don't think I have a number in the for the following reason,

04:18:55.360 --> 04:18:59.480
[Guest]: right, which is, and I can come back and, you know, talk about CJIS as well a little

04:18:59.480 --> 04:19:05.840
[Guest]: bit more. See, the way I'm approaching this is, what maximizes the probability, right,

04:19:05.840 --> 04:19:09.680
[Guest]: in that a lot of these things will happen, right? So, the book is laying out an entire

04:19:09.680 --> 04:19:14.720
[Guest]: menu of reform ideas, right? So, some of them will catch fire somewhere, others will not,

04:19:14.720 --> 04:19:19.080
[Guest]: some will fall completely flat, and nobody will pick up anything, right? But then, what

04:19:19.080 --> 04:19:24.280
[Guest]: we're seeing at CJIS is that there is already so much appreciation of the work that we're

04:19:24.280 --> 04:19:29.040
[Guest]: doing, right? I mean, and, you know, again, I prefer the government to kind of talk about

04:19:29.040 --> 04:19:33.740
[Guest]: it rather than me talk about it, but I'll just say that there is, there are enough indicators

04:19:33.740 --> 04:19:37.800
[Guest]: of real revealed preference, right, in terms of the cross conversations happening across

04:19:37.800 --> 04:19:41.800
[Guest]: states and people calling us and stuff like that. So, I feel actually very optimistic

04:19:41.800 --> 04:19:51.720
[Guest]: that out of this broad agenda, we will do maybe somewhere between 30 to 50% of these

04:19:51.720 --> 04:19:56.600
[Guest]: ideas in at least one state, okay, and over 10 years, right? Because like they say, people,

04:19:56.600 --> 04:19:59.840
[Guest]: you underestimate what you can, you overestimate what you can do in one year and underestimate

04:19:59.840 --> 04:20:03.480
[Guest]: what you can do in 10 years, right? I mean, so, which is partly why, you know, I see this

04:20:03.480 --> 04:20:08.320
[Guest]: as a 10-20 year investment, right? I mean, in the kind of reforms, but I'm actually,

04:20:08.320 --> 04:20:13.400
[Guest]: I'm very optimistic. And it's not just, okay, I mean, now to be realistic, in terms of the

04:20:13.400 --> 04:20:17.960
[Guest]: nature of even government officials or bureaucracies, right? I mean, is that, see, there are 20,

04:20:17.960 --> 04:20:23.560
[Guest]: and this I'm just generalizing, right? But in most orgs, about 20%, who are really outstanding,

04:20:23.560 --> 04:20:28.240
[Guest]: okay, who kind of are thinkers, who are well intentioned, motivated, really, really kind

04:20:28.240 --> 04:20:32.920
[Guest]: of want to get stuff done. There's about 60%, I would say, like, you know, who are good,

04:20:32.920 --> 04:20:36.480
[Guest]: but over time have had the enthusiasm beaten out of them, right? I mean, and so they have

04:20:36.480 --> 04:20:41.240
[Guest]: essentially kind of doing, you know, not doing bad things, but not going out of the way to

04:20:41.240 --> 04:20:45.000
[Guest]: kind of, you know, take on, they're kind of minding the store. And then there's always

04:20:45.000 --> 04:20:49.760
[Guest]: the 10 to 20%, you know, who are actually kind of the malevolent actors, or at least

04:20:49.760 --> 04:20:53.440
[Guest]: who have kind of figured out how to milk the current system, who are therefore very nervous,

04:20:53.440 --> 04:20:57.400
[Guest]: like, you know, of certain changes. But, you know, the good news, what I'm seeing in many

04:20:57.400 --> 04:21:01.240
[Guest]: states, and maybe this is, again, reflecting the fact that the main place I interact with

04:21:01.240 --> 04:21:05.120
[Guest]: is finance, is that most states actually put really good people in finance, because finance

04:21:05.120 --> 04:21:09.280
[Guest]: is not something you can afford to mess with, because, you know, you see Sri Lanka, you

04:21:09.280 --> 04:21:12.960
[Guest]: see other things, like states go bankrupt, okay. So, in fact, in many of the states that

04:21:12.960 --> 04:21:17.520
[Guest]: we work in, the finance has a certain amount of both sanctity and competence, right? I

04:21:17.520 --> 04:21:21.800
[Guest]: mean, so yeah, so maybe that's why we are seeing a positive reaction, because every

04:21:21.800 --> 04:21:26.600
[Guest]: finance secretary is kind of, so a different way of saying this, is that almost all of

04:21:26.600 --> 04:21:31.400
[Guest]: our public discourse happens on kind of quantity of expenditure to sectors, we just have much

04:21:31.400 --> 04:21:36.000
[Guest]: less discussion on the quality of expenditure, right? I mean, and the core thing we're doing

04:21:36.000 --> 04:21:39.880
[Guest]: is about improving that quality. And that's something that any finance secretary instinctively

04:21:39.880 --> 04:21:45.320
[Guest]: understands. And so if you are able to support that, you know, people have been very, very

04:21:45.320 --> 04:21:48.480
[Guest]: positive about it. Now, of course, all the ideas eventually have to go through political

04:21:48.480 --> 04:21:53.400
[Guest]: filters and stuff like that. But, you know, and even as an economic advisor, I think Arun

04:21:53.400 --> 04:21:56.480
[Guest]: Subramanian, recently, once said this about Arun Subramanian, he said, you know, his job

04:21:56.480 --> 04:22:01.360
[Guest]: is to present ideas, we don't have to accept all of them, right? I mean, but we will listen.

04:22:01.360 --> 04:22:03.520
[Guest]: And that's the most you can ask for, right? So yeah.

04:22:03.520 --> 04:22:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's kind of what this podcast does. Our job is to talk about ideas, other people

04:22:09.600 --> 04:22:15.320
[Amit Varma]: can only listen. So we choose to, you know, do something or not. But yeah, and they choose

04:22:15.320 --> 04:22:18.800
[Amit Varma]: to listen. And they're still here four plus hours into the thing. And why are they here?

04:22:18.800 --> 04:22:22.000
[Amit Varma]: They're here because we haven't discussed your paper yet. You said it's the most important

04:22:22.000 --> 04:22:25.720
[Amit Varma]: paper you've done. We haven't discussed it yet. We cannot, we cannot disappoint them

04:22:25.720 --> 04:22:30.880
[Amit Varma]: at this moment in time. So briefly, you know, I know you're tired. I know you're tired.

04:22:30.880 --> 04:22:34.080
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to, I don't want to mess with you too much. India needs you. Take care of

04:22:34.080 --> 04:22:40.440
[Amit Varma]: your health. Don't get COVID again. So tell us about your NREGA paper. And you know, why

04:22:40.440 --> 04:22:41.440
[Guest]: it's so exciting.

04:22:41.440 --> 04:22:44.520
[Guest]: Yeah, so I mean, we can have much longer, if at some point we do an episode just on

04:22:44.520 --> 04:22:48.760
[Guest]: welfare and social protection, we can have a longer discussion. But see, I think the

04:22:48.760 --> 04:22:54.640
[Guest]: core, so what is the paper doing? Okay, the paper is presenting large scale, randomized

04:22:54.640 --> 04:23:01.280
[Guest]: experiment evidence of what happens to the overall economy, then you improve the implementation

04:23:01.280 --> 04:23:06.880
[Guest]: of NREGA. Okay, so now NREGA itself as a program when it was rolled out was not randomized.

04:23:06.880 --> 04:23:11.640
[Guest]: Okay, so the best evaluations to date have relied on what's called a difference in difference

04:23:11.640 --> 04:23:15.120
[Guest]: where you look at districts that got it with districts that did not. But the problem is

04:23:15.120 --> 04:23:19.200
[Guest]: those districts were not randomly selected, right? So there's other pre-existing differences.

04:23:19.200 --> 04:23:23.360
[Guest]: And the other problem is that there wasn't a big round of the NSS at that time. So you

04:23:23.360 --> 04:23:28.160
[Guest]: actually haven't had good enough data on many of the outcomes we care about. So the literature

04:23:28.160 --> 04:23:32.720
[Guest]: in NREGA itself has had, you know, what my co-author Sandeep Sukhtankar calls, what we

04:23:32.720 --> 04:23:36.960
[Guest]: call Sukhtankar's third law of NREGS, right, which is for every study that finds X, there

04:23:36.960 --> 04:23:41.040
[Guest]: are studies that find minus X or zero. Okay, so, and that's part of the challenge with

04:23:41.040 --> 04:23:44.800
[Guest]: research because the results are sensitive to the method, sensitive to the data, sensitive

04:23:44.800 --> 04:23:49.440
[Guest]: to the state, and that's been a big challenge. So the opportunity in this paper was, and

04:23:49.440 --> 04:23:53.040
[Guest]: frankly, this was a bit of an accidental paper, we're not expected to write it. The reason

04:23:53.040 --> 04:23:57.760
[Guest]: it's an accidental paper was the randomized control trial we did was actually designed

04:23:57.760 --> 04:24:03.640
[Guest]: to study an intervention to reduce corruption and improve implementation. Okay, so that

04:24:03.640 --> 04:24:07.760
[Guest]: paper, which was published in the American Economic Review in 2016, was called Building

04:24:07.760 --> 04:24:13.040
[Guest]: State Capacity. And that was studying in unified Andhra Pradesh in eight districts, randomized

04:24:13.040 --> 04:24:17.960
[Guest]: across a population of about 20 million people. It was studying the effectiveness of biometric

04:24:17.960 --> 04:24:24.360
[Guest]: smart cards on improving NREGA implementation. Okay, so the outcome there was really just

04:24:24.360 --> 04:24:28.480
[Guest]: NREGA implementation, which is how much, you know, did you get your money. So we measure

04:24:28.480 --> 04:24:32.920
[Guest]: leakage very carefully, because we measure the administrative data on how much money

04:24:32.920 --> 04:24:37.360
[Guest]: was dispersed to a given job card, and we do matched household surveys to measure, did

04:24:37.360 --> 04:24:40.640
[Guest]: you actually get it? Okay, so part of the problem with the public discourse and say

04:24:40.640 --> 04:24:46.200
[Guest]: Aadhaar or biometrics and leakage is that the government says we have reduced leakage

04:24:46.200 --> 04:24:50.520
[Guest]: because we have reduced the spending. Okay, the activists will say yes, but you have increased

04:24:50.520 --> 04:24:54.240
[Guest]: exclusion because the money, you know, people are not getting. So unless you have matched

04:24:54.240 --> 04:24:58.400
[Guest]: data between the government disbursals and what people are getting, you are only seeing

04:24:58.400 --> 04:25:02.240
[Guest]: half the side of the puzzle, right? So the methodological, I mean, the strength of that

04:25:02.240 --> 04:25:07.400
[Guest]: paper is A, we have randomized across eight districts at the mandal level. So in fact,

04:25:07.400 --> 04:25:11.040
[Guest]: statistically, this is why it's lovely to work in Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, because

04:25:11.040 --> 04:25:14.720
[Guest]: you can randomize at the mandal level and get a large sample because you have four times

04:25:14.720 --> 04:25:18.160
[Guest]: as many mandals as districts. So, but that was a side benefit, right? That's not why

04:25:18.160 --> 04:25:22.760
[Guest]: we were there. We were there because I'd worked in the state before. But, and AP was one of

04:25:22.760 --> 04:25:28.480
[Guest]: the leaders in NREGA. Okay, so but long story short, that paper, which is was done in 2016,

04:25:28.480 --> 04:25:33.160
[Guest]: essentially finds that the smart cards had a dramatic positive effect in improving both

04:25:33.160 --> 04:25:37.860
[Guest]: kind of in reducing corruption, improving timeliness of payments and improving the predictability

04:25:37.860 --> 04:25:42.400
[Guest]: of payments. Okay, so in every way, and that's why that paper is called Building State Capacity,

04:25:42.400 --> 04:25:47.920
[Guest]: because it brings the program closer to what the framers of the law intended it to do.

04:25:47.920 --> 04:25:54.240
[Guest]: Okay, so that's what that paper does. Now, how this paper emerged was really as an accident

04:25:54.240 --> 04:25:57.800
[Guest]: and going back to what I'm saying, you know, as researchers, the joys in discovering new

04:25:57.800 --> 04:26:01.840
[Guest]: facts and then making sense of it, right? So this is really an example of that journey,

04:26:01.840 --> 04:26:06.920
[Guest]: right? We had not expected to find these results, or write this paper. So one of the results

04:26:06.920 --> 04:26:13.920
[Guest]: we were looking at in 2015, or 2014, was looking at the impact on total incomes of the poor

04:26:13.920 --> 04:26:19.360
[Guest]: in their treated areas. Okay. And what you saw was that there was this huge increase

04:26:19.360 --> 04:26:25.280
[Guest]: in income, okay, and the increase in income was 10 times higher than the increase in NREGA

04:26:25.280 --> 04:26:29.160
[Guest]: income. Because remember, we've reduced corruption in NREGA, you've reduced the work done in

04:26:29.160 --> 04:26:32.680
[Guest]: those days. So there is obviously an increase in NREGA income. Okay. But what's interesting

04:26:32.680 --> 04:26:37.720
[Guest]: is that the total income increase goes up about 12 to 13%. And only 10% of that is coming

04:26:37.720 --> 04:26:43.880
[Guest]: from NREGA. The remaining 90% seems to be coming from other sources. Okay. And so that

04:26:43.880 --> 04:26:47.360
[Guest]: became this huge puzzle. And it was such a big puzzle that we realized that we could

04:26:47.360 --> 04:26:51.440
[Guest]: not do justice to that in the previous paper. Okay, so that previous, so this is then, I

04:26:51.440 --> 04:26:54.360
[Guest]: mean, this is something Paul Sandeep and I have been working on now for about 14 years.

04:26:54.360 --> 04:26:59.240
[Guest]: Okay, we started in 2009. Okay, so to give you a sense of what the academic life looks

04:26:59.240 --> 04:27:06.040
[Guest]: like, two papers, okay, two major papers, we worked on for 14 years. Okay, so, you know,

04:27:06.040 --> 04:27:09.400
[Guest]: we thought and designed the experiments, we worked with the government to get the buy-in,

04:27:09.400 --> 04:27:14.520
[Guest]: we raised the funding for it, we did the randomization, there were two years from 2010 to 2012, where

04:27:14.520 --> 04:27:20.080
[Guest]: the actual experiment happened, you had endline data collection in 2012. Then it took us kind

04:27:20.080 --> 04:27:24.680
[Guest]: of, you know, a year to clean and analyze the data, start writing the first draft, start

04:27:24.680 --> 04:27:30.920
[Guest]: presenting in conferences, getting feedback, iterating, submitted for publication in 2014,

04:27:30.920 --> 04:27:34.280
[Guest]: then you get the revise and resubmit from the journals, finally appears in print in

04:27:34.280 --> 04:27:39.920
[Guest]: 2016. Okay, so that is that first paper. The genesis of the second paper starts in about

04:27:39.920 --> 04:27:44.040
[Guest]: 2015, when we start seeing that these income effects are so big, and we're like, how on

04:27:44.040 --> 04:27:50.120
[Guest]: earth do you make sense of this? Okay. And then what is really kind of interesting was

04:27:50.120 --> 04:27:55.160
[Guest]: that we see that the private sector income has gone up very sharply in both agriculture

04:27:55.160 --> 04:28:00.000
[Guest]: and non-agriculture, we see that the market wage has gone up. And then the most kind of

04:28:00.000 --> 04:28:04.400
[Guest]: stunning result is that not only has the wage gone up, but private sector employment has

04:28:04.400 --> 04:28:08.440
[Guest]: also gone up, okay, which is kind of violating econ 101, which is normally when wages go

04:28:08.440 --> 04:28:14.000
[Guest]: up, employment goes down. Okay, so how could wages and employment both go up? Okay, so

04:28:14.000 --> 04:28:20.120
[Guest]: long story short, I think, we have ourselves puzzled and struggled, right? And in fact,

04:28:20.120 --> 04:28:25.520
[Guest]: in the early years, so this paper we had first written and presented at one of the top conferences

04:28:25.520 --> 04:28:31.040
[Guest]: in 2016. And we thought we had enough in those results, because it was randomised, right?

04:28:31.040 --> 04:28:34.440
[Guest]: Because the experiment was randomised. So we thought we had enough on those results

04:28:34.440 --> 04:28:38.480
[Guest]: to merit a top journal publication, right? So we submitted then, you know, to the QGE.

04:28:38.480 --> 04:28:41.880
[Guest]: Now, these are intricacies of the academic publication process, which is, you know, the

04:28:41.880 --> 04:28:46.920
[Guest]: Quarterly Journal of Economics. And we got a very kind of, you know, sympathetic rejection,

04:28:46.920 --> 04:28:50.880
[Guest]: saying that everybody thought that the question was important, everything was important, but

04:28:50.880 --> 04:28:54.760
[Guest]: basically people felt the results were too big, okay, that they just couldn't make sense

04:28:54.760 --> 04:28:59.080
[Guest]: of it. And they wanted us to probe harder on the mechanisms, okay, of what is happening,

04:28:59.080 --> 04:29:03.520
[Guest]: what is the mechanism by which both wages and employment could go up. And because the

04:29:03.520 --> 04:29:07.880
[Guest]: result is so counterintuitive, and this goes back to the peer review process, because the

04:29:07.880 --> 04:29:11.960
[Guest]: result is so counterintuitive, I think it's natural for reviewers to pressure test more,

04:29:11.960 --> 04:29:15.400
[Guest]: okay, and saying, is there some mistake, right, in your data collection, in your sampling

04:29:15.400 --> 04:29:20.120
[Guest]: and stuff like that. So long story short, we got rejected at both the QGE and the AER,

04:29:20.120 --> 04:29:23.520
[Guest]: the American Economic Review, which are two of the top publications. And then we went

04:29:23.520 --> 04:29:27.880
[Guest]: back to the drawing board, because we really had a sense that this result was truly important,

04:29:27.880 --> 04:29:32.160
[Guest]: right? And this is where the value of the randomised control trial comes in. Because

04:29:32.160 --> 04:29:36.800
[Guest]: suppose the result was just correlational, I would always say, okay, maybe the result

04:29:36.800 --> 04:29:41.440
[Guest]: is spurious, because of some omitted variable, okay. But because this was randomised, there

04:29:41.440 --> 04:29:44.960
[Guest]: is no questioning the facts. It's like Sherlock Holmes says, right, if the facts change, then

04:29:44.960 --> 04:29:49.640
[Guest]: you change your mind. And that's, again, the power of the RCT in this case was because

04:29:49.640 --> 04:29:54.520
[Guest]: the facts were incontrovertible, right? So we then had to go back and question our assumptions

04:29:54.520 --> 04:29:59.240
[Guest]: of how do you make sense of the fact, okay. And if you go back to econ theory, you'll

04:29:59.240 --> 04:30:04.680
[Guest]: see that, basically, how can wages and employment both go up, they can go up for multiple reasons,

04:30:04.680 --> 04:30:10.120
[Guest]: they can go up if the NREGA assets made people more productive, okay. They could go up if,

04:30:10.120 --> 04:30:15.320
[Guest]: basically, if there was employer market power, okay, with monopsony. So this is the kind

04:30:15.320 --> 04:30:20.320
[Guest]: of a very nuanced kind of result. But essentially, a monopolist is kind of going to suppress

04:30:20.320 --> 04:30:25.280
[Guest]: quantity and jack up price. A monopsonist who's a single buyer, if you have market power,

04:30:25.280 --> 04:30:29.920
[Guest]: you will keep the wage low and keep employment also low. So historically, if you look at

04:30:29.920 --> 04:30:34.560
[Guest]: the origins of trade unions, and why unions in the 19th century UK were a good thing for

04:30:34.560 --> 04:30:39.800
[Guest]: both equity and efficiency, is that if you have a monopsonist buyer, then putting market

04:30:39.800 --> 04:30:44.880
[Guest]: power on the side of the employees actually improves both wages and employment up to a

04:30:44.880 --> 04:30:48.120
[Guest]: point, okay. It's only when you go over that, that it becomes kind of, you know, then it's

04:30:48.120 --> 04:30:52.920
[Guest]: an insider and seeking business, okay. So the theoretical mechanisms were could there

04:30:52.920 --> 04:30:58.120
[Guest]: be monopsony and then there is an aggregate demand effect, okay, which is that if the

04:30:58.120 --> 04:31:02.240
[Guest]: poor have more income, and if they're demanding local goods and services, then that could

04:31:02.240 --> 04:31:07.400
[Guest]: create a demand multiplier in the local economy, okay. But then we had to go back to the drawing

04:31:07.400 --> 04:31:11.840
[Guest]: board to figure out how would we test all of these possible hypotheses and mechanisms,

04:31:11.840 --> 04:31:16.480
[Guest]: correct. So the first kind, and again, we got very lucky in some ways, that the experiment

04:31:16.480 --> 04:31:22.680
[Guest]: happened 2010 to 2012. And this was a period when the socio-economic caste census happened

04:31:22.680 --> 04:31:28.280
[Guest]: in late 2011, and the economic census happened in 2013. See, one of the, this is now very

04:31:28.280 --> 04:31:33.960
[Guest]: small, but one of the challenges for us was that our data in our survey, we were sampling

04:31:33.960 --> 04:31:39.240
[Guest]: from the universe of NREGA job card holders, okay. So that is 50% of the population. But

04:31:39.240 --> 04:31:43.320
[Guest]: we didn't have survey data from the employers, okay, from the landlord. So even if wages

04:31:43.320 --> 04:31:48.120
[Guest]: here are going up, maybe there is enough offset there that the net effects could be negative,

04:31:48.120 --> 04:31:52.440
[Guest]: okay. So how do you truly say that the effects are positive? So for that, we need to get

04:31:52.440 --> 04:31:57.920
[Guest]: census data that goes beyond our survey. So we got lucky that the SEC sees a census, the

04:31:57.920 --> 04:32:02.960
[Guest]: economic census is a census, and this happened late 2011-2013. So long story short, this

04:32:02.960 --> 04:32:07.080
[Guest]: is a bit like, I keep saying that, but it is a bit of a detective story, right, because

04:32:07.080 --> 04:32:11.160
[Guest]: I'm giving you a sense of both the results and the journey of how we got there, right.

04:32:11.160 --> 04:32:17.360
[Guest]: So now what happens with the SECC data, which is really nice, is that we have data on every

04:32:17.360 --> 04:32:21.760
[Guest]: individual in the village, correct, but it also gives you the land holdings. And so that

04:32:21.760 --> 04:32:26.960
[Guest]: allows you to construct a measure of landholder concentration in every village, which is then

04:32:26.960 --> 04:32:31.400
[Guest]: a measure of monopsony and a measure of employer market power, okay. And what we're able to

04:32:31.400 --> 04:32:39.240
[Guest]: test and show is that the employment effect of improving NREGA is more positive in areas

04:32:39.240 --> 04:32:43.400
[Guest]: where there is more employer market power, which is completely consistent with the monopsony

04:32:43.400 --> 04:32:48.080
[Guest]: story, okay. And so then that gives you the smoking gun evidence on the mechanism. And

04:32:48.080 --> 04:32:53.120
[Guest]: then what's very interesting is, because our survey data is not like the NSS, we didn't

04:32:53.120 --> 04:32:56.960
[Guest]: have very detailed data on consumption, okay, but we had good data on savings. And you see

04:32:56.960 --> 04:33:01.080
[Guest]: that people are spending most of this extra money, right. And so we also find evidence

04:33:01.080 --> 04:33:05.520
[Guest]: of this demand multiplier, because what you see in the economic census is there is an

04:33:05.520 --> 04:33:10.480
[Guest]: increase in the number of non-agricultural firms and an increase in the employment in

04:33:10.480 --> 04:33:15.440
[Guest]: these firms. And most of these are very, very, very small local firms, okay. So, and again,

04:33:15.440 --> 04:33:18.880
[Guest]: this goes back to, so the reason I, you know, I'll come back to why I think the paper is

04:33:18.880 --> 04:33:23.120
[Guest]: kind of why I personally find it the most important paper is because it also connects

04:33:23.120 --> 04:33:28.680
[Guest]: to many, many old classic issues in development, right, that when people are very, very poor,

04:33:28.680 --> 04:33:33.880
[Guest]: you can get these kind of demand externalities, whereby you can kind of crowd in a positive

04:33:33.880 --> 04:33:38.480
[Guest]: cycle of kind of firm creation as well. And, you know, so anyway, long, and then there's

04:33:38.480 --> 04:33:42.000
[Guest]: a bunch of other work in terms of mechanisms and credit and all of this. So that's why

04:33:42.000 --> 04:33:46.840
[Guest]: it's, you know, but a paper like this, and the journal restricts us to 40 to 45 pages,

04:33:46.840 --> 04:33:50.760
[Guest]: and then we've got about 60 pages of appendices, right, mean with each appendix going through

04:33:50.760 --> 04:33:54.640
[Guest]: different robustness, building a formal model of rural labour markets, quantifying the extent

04:33:54.640 --> 04:33:58.440
[Guest]: of employee market power. And so, yeah, so I think, you know, the journey of the paper

04:33:58.440 --> 04:34:04.280
[Guest]: is after we did all of this, I think in 2019, with, 2019, yes, this is, again, giving you

04:34:04.280 --> 04:34:08.680
[Guest]: a sense of how long these things take. Submit to Econometrica, right, which is another of

04:34:08.680 --> 04:34:13.240
[Guest]: the most prestigious journals. So three referees, but then I think the editor got caught with

04:34:13.240 --> 04:34:17.400
[Guest]: COVID and health issues and stuff. So it took 11 months to come back, then it took us 11

04:34:17.400 --> 04:34:21.920
[Guest]: months to kind of do the revision, including most of last summer, because we took three

04:34:21.920 --> 04:34:27.240
[Guest]: entire months, just redoing so much of the analysis. Then there is this very cool piece

04:34:27.240 --> 04:34:31.120
[Guest]: of analysis we did, which will then bring me back to how this is connected to federalism.

04:34:31.120 --> 04:34:36.520
[Guest]: Okay, so because that was the context in which I sent you the paper, you know, is that one

04:34:36.520 --> 04:34:40.680
[Guest]: of the cool things we were able to do in the revision is that we were able to do a full

04:34:40.680 --> 04:34:44.080
[Guest]: distribution analysis in the following way, right, because remember, I told you, we only

04:34:44.080 --> 04:34:49.520
[Guest]: have data on NREGA job card holders, which is only 50% of the population, okay. But what

04:34:49.520 --> 04:34:55.280
[Guest]: we were able to do is, even in that NREGA sample, it turns out that the returns to land

04:34:55.280 --> 04:34:59.280
[Guest]: actually fall, okay, because if wages have gone up and productivity has not gone up,

04:34:59.280 --> 04:35:03.320
[Guest]: then somebody has to lose, okay, and prices have not gone up. So it turns out that land

04:35:03.320 --> 04:35:08.800
[Guest]: profits do fall, okay, like I mean, in areas with better implemented NREGA. And what we

04:35:08.800 --> 04:35:13.880
[Guest]: can do is we can take that result and overlay that on the SECC land distribution, because

04:35:13.880 --> 04:35:18.440
[Guest]: SECC gives you the entire distribution. And that provides this very nice distributional

04:35:18.440 --> 04:35:25.360
[Guest]: analysis that shows that the aggregate effects are positive, but the bottom 92% of the population

04:35:25.360 --> 04:35:30.400
[Guest]: does much better, okay, but the top seven and a half percent of top landholders do lose

04:35:30.400 --> 04:35:35.480
[Guest]: because their loss of profits is greater, okay, like I mean, than the gain in income.

04:35:35.480 --> 04:35:39.720
[Guest]: And that connects us back to the political economy of local elites and distribution,

04:35:39.720 --> 04:35:44.760
[Guest]: right, that even though this was a program that on aggregate improved both equity and

04:35:44.760 --> 04:35:50.280
[Guest]: efficiency, it did come at the cost of local power structures, and which is why there was

04:35:50.280 --> 04:35:55.920
[Guest]: so much vociferous opposition from landlords, okay, like to this, which is documented both

04:35:55.920 --> 04:36:01.680
[Guest]: by you know, Drez and Hrithika Khera and others. But in fact, this is other beautiful American

04:36:01.680 --> 04:36:06.000
[Guest]: economic review paper by Ashok Kotwal and co-authors. In fact, he just passed away recently

04:36:06.000 --> 04:36:10.400
[Guest]: and he was a giant in, you know, in economics. And this was a paper called clientelism in

04:36:10.400 --> 04:36:15.160
[Guest]: Indian villages, where they study local elections in Maharashtra, very, very carefully. And

04:36:15.160 --> 04:36:19.880
[Guest]: one of the points they make is that the entire reason local elites want to control local

04:36:19.880 --> 04:36:25.120
[Guest]: governments is that they want to thwart the implementation of programs like NREGA. Okay,

04:36:25.120 --> 04:36:30.120
[Guest]: so and you can see how this connects all the way back to our federalism loop, right, and

04:36:30.120 --> 04:36:35.800
[Guest]: mean that a progressive state that wants to improve outcomes for the most marginalized

04:36:35.800 --> 04:36:41.400
[Guest]: has to deal with the resistance that will come from local elites. And what made NREGA,

04:36:41.400 --> 04:36:45.280
[Guest]: what improved NREGA implementation, even today in Bihar and other places, the feudal structure

04:36:45.280 --> 04:36:49.920
[Guest]: has been too strong for NREGA to be effectively implemented, right. So it took a political

04:36:49.920 --> 04:36:55.360
[Guest]: decision in Andhra to prioritize NREGA implementation. The chief minister put one of their top officers

04:36:55.360 --> 04:37:00.160
[Guest]: as rural development secretary for five years, to kind of continuously push on different

04:37:00.160 --> 04:37:05.720
[Guest]: aspects of NREGA implementation. So there's another whole book recently by Rajesh Veeraragavan

04:37:05.720 --> 04:37:10.400
[Guest]: called patching development, and he talks both about the top down and how the implementation

04:37:10.400 --> 04:37:17.160
[Guest]: itself took kind of very strong political and bureaucratic will, and a lot of this required

04:37:17.160 --> 04:37:22.760
[Guest]: top down technological interventions, and bottom up mechanisms of social audits, whereby

04:37:22.760 --> 04:37:28.480
[Guest]: you did bring the community in, but you empowered them by kind of creating a directorate of

04:37:28.480 --> 04:37:34.280
[Guest]: social audit within the department, and then gave people the power to go and audit whether

04:37:34.280 --> 04:37:38.160
[Guest]: these projects are actually taking place, right. So even something as, you know, what

04:37:38.160 --> 04:37:42.680
[Guest]: sounds like, oh, this is just implementation, it's an enormous undertaking, right, to take

04:37:42.680 --> 04:37:46.840
[Guest]: a program like this, that is upending local power structures, and how do you implement

04:37:46.840 --> 04:37:51.320
[Guest]: that? And this is then circles back with why the research is so important. And why do I

04:37:51.320 --> 04:37:56.680
[Guest]: consider this the most important paper? It's because it proved my initial hypothesis wrong,

04:37:56.680 --> 04:38:02.080
[Guest]: right. So my initial hunch in the 2000s was that this is kind of, you know, that it cannot

04:38:02.080 --> 04:38:06.240
[Guest]: be good for the economy to boost wages without boosting productivity, right. And the fact

04:38:06.240 --> 04:38:11.040
[Guest]: that we found this was positive, it was positive in the experimental results. So that forces

04:38:11.040 --> 04:38:15.680
[Guest]: us to go back and question our priors, think about what is the data that will allow us

04:38:15.680 --> 04:38:22.320
[Guest]: to test these things. And then it's a detective story, right? And then one initial hypothesis

04:38:22.320 --> 04:38:26.480
[Guest]: we had was maybe it's the NREGA assets, okay, that are building productivity. But then you

04:38:26.480 --> 04:38:30.960
[Guest]: go look at the data and do some calibrations, and it turns out it is not the assets, okay.

04:38:30.960 --> 04:38:34.000
[Guest]: So anyway, so this is now getting into the weeds of the paper, and people can read 100

04:38:34.000 --> 04:38:38.480
[Guest]: pages if they want at least 45 pages of it. And then, you know, we just got our second

04:38:38.480 --> 04:38:43.440
[Guest]: round revise and resubmit. And, you know, we spent 11 months and given how grumpy referees

04:38:43.440 --> 04:38:48.000
[Guest]: tend to be like, you know, one of the gratifying things was the referee report starting with

04:38:48.000 --> 04:38:53.040
[Guest]: I have been very impressed by the amount of work the authors have done, like in this paper.

04:38:53.040 --> 04:38:56.720
[Guest]: But this then gives you an example of why books get delayed, because that is still my

04:38:56.720 --> 04:39:00.640
[Guest]: core job, right, of kind of actually writing these research papers.

04:39:00.640 --> 04:39:05.560
[Amit Varma]: No, it just sounds like such an amazing paper, because it's not just about economics, it's

04:39:05.560 --> 04:39:10.600
[Amit Varma]: also about society. It's also about politics. Like this is a heck of a detective story.

04:39:10.600 --> 04:39:15.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if it's a web series, who would you like to play you?

04:39:15.640 --> 04:39:17.840
[Amit Varma]: I haven't thought about that at all.

04:39:17.840 --> 04:39:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Think about it. Now I'm going to put you on the spot. What is this? Think about it. Who

04:39:20.720 --> 04:39:22.720
[Amit Varma]: would you like to play you?

04:39:22.720 --> 04:39:29.560
[Guest]: No, I'm, I'm just not good at this. But yeah, eventually, like, you know, maybe, yeah, maybe

04:39:29.560 --> 04:39:33.080
[Guest]: you are the creative guy, you can think about somebody who would be excited about this,

04:39:33.080 --> 04:39:38.800
[Guest]: but I don't I don't watch enough TV or movies to immediately have a name. Again, part of

04:39:38.800 --> 04:39:43.840
[Guest]: the academic temperament is to say, I don't know when I don't know, like, you know, so

04:39:43.840 --> 04:39:45.880
[Guest]: you can't force me to answer something I don't know.

04:39:45.880 --> 04:39:52.400
[Amit Varma]: Okay, I'll, you can tell me in song in the next Antakshari we do for the next episode.

04:39:52.400 --> 04:39:55.680
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just like, 14 years on two papers, my God.

04:39:55.680 --> 04:39:58.760
[Guest]: And that's not the only thing that's happening, right? I mean, it is, I mean, there are a

04:39:58.760 --> 04:40:03.280
[Guest]: whole bunch of other things that happen. But I think part of the research process is that

04:40:03.280 --> 04:40:07.200
[Guest]: there is this constant process of discovery, rediscovery. And I think the one thing in

04:40:07.200 --> 04:40:10.680
[Guest]: economics that's different from other fields is many other fields publish very short papers

04:40:10.680 --> 04:40:15.680
[Guest]: with new facts as an experiment. The thing in economics is, because there is this need

04:40:15.680 --> 04:40:20.400
[Guest]: to not just get the result, but at least for the top journals, to really probe into mechanisms

04:40:20.400 --> 04:40:24.440
[Guest]: and saying, because you don't get published in the top journal, if this was just about

04:40:24.440 --> 04:40:29.080
[Guest]: NREGA in India, right? It is what is it illustrating about the mechanisms of rural labour markets?

04:40:29.080 --> 04:40:33.600
[Guest]: What is it illustrating about the mechanisms of some of these demand externalities, etc.

04:40:33.600 --> 04:40:38.480
[Guest]: So, you know, it just takes a lot more probing, probing, probing and coming back to being

04:40:38.480 --> 04:40:42.560
[Guest]: a, you know, this is an example where I think the peer review process has been fantastic

04:40:42.560 --> 04:40:46.760
[Guest]: because it has improved the paper so much, because we have been pushed and pushed and

04:40:46.760 --> 04:40:51.480
[Guest]: pushed and pushed and pushed. But we've had to also work our backsides off to do it.

04:40:51.480 --> 04:40:55.480
[Amit Varma]: Amazing. Let me ask you a question. Let's see how good an economist you are. Can you

04:40:55.480 --> 04:41:01.800
[Amit Varma]: answer this? And the question is, although the IPL and NREGA are completely different

04:41:01.800 --> 04:41:04.200
[Amit Varma]: things, what is the one thing they have in common?

04:41:04.200 --> 04:41:05.200
[Unknown]: Nahi pata.

04:41:05.200 --> 04:41:12.840
[Amit Varma]: Nahi pata. Main pata toh. Yeh kaise economist ho yaar? You know, I tell my friends, somebody

04:41:12.840 --> 04:41:15.920
[Amit Varma]: asked me the other day, who is this Kartik Muralidharan? And I said, dekhna, one day

04:41:15.920 --> 04:41:20.520
[Amit Varma]: he will win the Nobel Prize for Economics, maybe for this paper only. That will be nice.

04:41:20.520 --> 04:41:24.120
[Amit Varma]: Not for something you said on my podcast, obviously, and you failed this question. But

04:41:24.120 --> 04:41:29.780
[Amit Varma]: the answer is this, that see, the BCCI, like all sporting bodies, is basically a monopsony.

04:41:29.780 --> 04:41:34.280
[Amit Varma]: If you're a cricketer, you can't sell your services to anybody else, but the BCCI. So

04:41:34.280 --> 04:41:38.680
[Amit Varma]: now, what do you do to break the system? And in this case, the BCCI did it themselves.

04:41:38.680 --> 04:41:43.640
[Amit Varma]: It wasn't imposed from elsewhere. They started the IPL, you know, and what did the IPL do?

04:41:43.640 --> 04:41:48.520
[Amit Varma]: It raised wages and employment. So there you go. That's what you have in common. You know,

04:41:48.520 --> 04:41:52.680
[Amit Varma]: Dr. John Reyes will suddenly turn on his TV and start watching the IPL.

04:41:52.680 --> 04:42:00.840
[Guest]: IPL is basically, that's creating a whole new market. But it highlights again, you know,

04:42:00.840 --> 04:42:04.840
[Guest]: if I can, you know, take a minute and go into the social protection chapter, right? Like,

04:42:04.840 --> 04:42:09.720
[Guest]: I mean, why I think, you know, we need to think about our welfare spending, A, in a

04:42:09.720 --> 04:42:14.720
[Guest]: much more nuanced way, and B, in a fundamentally empirical way, right? Which is we think about,

04:42:14.720 --> 04:42:18.160
[Guest]: okay, saare welfare programs, like, you know, is either freebies or, you know, again, the

04:42:18.160 --> 04:42:21.720
[Guest]: right things, they are freebies, the left things, we don't do enough. Okay. And again,

04:42:21.720 --> 04:42:25.960
[Guest]: the basic point is that if you look at something like farm electricity subsidies, right, those

04:42:25.960 --> 04:42:30.680
[Guest]: are probably the single worst financial policy we have in the country, right? Because it

04:42:30.680 --> 04:42:34.200
[Guest]: is bad, you know, when I look at quality of welfare expenditure, you think about targeting,

04:42:34.200 --> 04:42:38.200
[Guest]: you think about delivery, you think about distortions, right? So it's miserable on targeting

04:42:38.200 --> 04:42:43.160
[Guest]: because top 5% of farmers get 50% of the benefits, the bottom 50% of landless owners basically

04:42:43.160 --> 04:42:47.000
[Guest]: get nothing. So though you call it farmer welfare, it's really like a mean, a slice

04:42:47.000 --> 04:42:51.360
[Guest]: of elite farmers. Second is in terms of going back to your episode with Ajay and Akshay

04:42:51.360 --> 04:42:55.600
[Guest]: on electricity reform, right? I mean, that the dysfunction of our discoms is partly hidden

04:42:55.600 --> 04:42:59.640
[Guest]: behind free electricity, right? Because that allows them to cover the T&D losses and saying

04:42:59.640 --> 04:43:02.960
[Guest]: ye toh free hai, recovery nahi ho raha hai. So your discom crisis is kind of partly coming

04:43:02.960 --> 04:43:06.960
[Guest]: from there. And then you have your ecological crisis of the downstream, the water crisis

04:43:06.960 --> 04:43:11.480
[Guest]: that's happening because of the suboptimal kind of cultivation, right? So kind of, and

04:43:11.480 --> 04:43:15.120
[Guest]: then going back to trust. So in a way, this was not about farm laws per se, because farm

04:43:15.120 --> 04:43:18.280
[Guest]: laws wasn't really taking on this issue of subsidy reform, which is way more complicated,

04:43:18.280 --> 04:43:23.760
[Guest]: right? But I think why a program like PM Kisan is important is that once you can build the

04:43:23.760 --> 04:43:27.960
[Guest]: trust with farmers that the state, in fact, can deliver money to you, right? I mean, and

04:43:27.960 --> 04:43:32.880
[Guest]: does this a few times, then it gives you at least some political space of crafting a reform

04:43:32.880 --> 04:43:36.640
[Guest]: idea, which again, I have in the expenditure chapter of kind of saying, can I take the

04:43:36.640 --> 04:43:40.520
[Guest]: fiscally same amount of subsidy and kind of give it to you as a DBT, like, you know, but

04:43:40.520 --> 04:43:45.080
[Guest]: then with metering and billing of the electricity. So it's not about saving money, but it's at

04:43:45.080 --> 04:43:48.720
[Guest]: least about reducing the distortions, right? So that's the kind of reform that we need

04:43:48.720 --> 04:43:53.600
[Guest]: as a country. It requires both kind of conceptual architecture, it requires communication, it

04:43:53.600 --> 04:43:57.960
[Guest]: requires trust, but you know, hopefully we'll build enough of a public consensus around

04:43:57.960 --> 04:44:01.680
[Guest]: something like that that needs to happen. Conversely, something like NREGA has been

04:44:01.680 --> 04:44:05.160
[Guest]: something that improves both equity and efficiency, right? So you have welfare spending that's

04:44:05.160 --> 04:44:09.360
[Guest]: bad for equity and efficiency, welfare spending that's good for both. And there are others

04:44:09.360 --> 04:44:13.680
[Guest]: that are good for equity, bad for efficiency, vice versa, that reasonable people can disagree.

04:44:13.680 --> 04:44:17.720
[Guest]: And at least as a country, if we can agree on moving from this bottom left quadrant where

04:44:17.720 --> 04:44:21.760
[Guest]: things are bad for equity and efficiency, to things that are good on equity and efficiency,

04:44:21.760 --> 04:44:25.880
[Guest]: that's again, one of the ways in which you move the arc towards delivering more value

04:44:25.880 --> 04:44:26.880
[Guest]: for money.

04:44:26.880 --> 04:44:31.240
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous. And I completely agree with you about free electricity for farmers being a

04:44:31.240 --> 04:44:35.400
[Amit Varma]: bad thing. And one of the illustrations of that, and it's a classic scene in the unseen,

04:44:35.400 --> 04:44:39.560
[Amit Varma]: is that, you know, in Punjab, the farmers were incentivized to grow rice because of

04:44:39.560 --> 04:44:44.680
[Amit Varma]: an MSP for rice, right? Which they otherwise would not have because of market dynamics.

04:44:44.680 --> 04:44:49.880
[Amit Varma]: But it's an arid land, rice needs a lot of water. What do they do? They use bore wells

04:44:49.880 --> 04:44:53.520
[Amit Varma]: to get the water out of the ground. And how do they run these bore wells? Because electricity

04:44:53.520 --> 04:44:58.600
[Amit Varma]: is free. So, you know, you have MSPs and free electricity distorting the whole marketplace,

04:44:58.600 --> 04:45:02.400
[Amit Varma]: you have a lot of rice. What happens when they produce a lot of rice? They've got rice

04:45:02.400 --> 04:45:06.720
[Amit Varma]: stubble at the end of the season to get rid of. How do they get rid of it? The easiest

04:45:06.720 --> 04:45:11.680
[Amit Varma]: way for them is to burn it. What happens when they burn it? The fumes go to Delhi and exacerbates

04:45:11.680 --> 04:45:16.400
[Amit Varma]: the Delhi fog. So the worst of the Delhi fog happens when farmers in Punjab are burning

04:45:16.400 --> 04:45:21.480
[Amit Varma]: rice. And, you know, again, seen in the unseen, all of these sort of connections floating

04:45:21.480 --> 04:45:27.600
[Amit Varma]: around. But, you know, something like that is an almost impossible problem of the political

04:45:27.600 --> 04:45:31.280
[Amit Varma]: economy to solve because a Punjab politician can't piss the farmers off. So what do you

04:45:31.280 --> 04:45:37.080
[Amit Varma]: do? It's just so incredibly complicated. But a couple of sort of final questions and one

04:45:37.080 --> 04:45:41.640
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, and both are actually in the personal realm, but one is the good news for

04:45:41.640 --> 04:45:46.560
[Amit Varma]: all my listeners that Mr. Karthik Muralidharan is shifting to India, you know, putting skin

04:45:46.560 --> 04:45:50.920
[Amit Varma]: in the game as it were. So tell me a little bit about, you know, this already people are

04:45:50.920 --> 04:45:55.960
[Amit Varma]: jumping I can hear listeners in advance. So tell me a little bit about, you know, what

04:45:55.960 --> 04:45:58.160
[Amit Varma]: prompted you to come back to India? What will you be doing?

04:45:58.160 --> 04:46:02.880
[Guest]: No, and I think, again, I feel like your show is, you know, I mean, there is a certain amount

04:46:02.880 --> 04:46:05.960
[Guest]: of commitments I'm making, and then hopefully following through on them, like, you know,

04:46:05.960 --> 04:46:10.040
[Guest]: once I think like, you know, I said this in 2020, right? I mean, that I, you know, that

04:46:10.040 --> 04:46:13.680
[Guest]: I feel that I'm at this inflection point where so far, my life has been nine months, US three

04:46:13.680 --> 04:46:17.400
[Guest]: months India. And it's not like I'm moving back fully, but I'm just flipping that around

04:46:17.400 --> 04:46:22.200
[Guest]: to nine months, India, three months, US. Okay, so, so basically, I have over a year of accumulated

04:46:22.200 --> 04:46:27.240
[Guest]: sabbatical, I have grants that buy out some of my teaching. And so and I think, you know,

04:46:27.240 --> 04:46:30.960
[Guest]: at a function, so basically, it'll mean that we're moving to Chennai, we're getting there

04:46:30.960 --> 04:46:34.880
[Guest]: September 1, the big and the big marker of moving is that the kids will be in school

04:46:34.880 --> 04:46:38.040
[Guest]: in India, right? I mean, in Chennai. So that's really the big marker. It's not like I'm just

04:46:38.040 --> 04:46:42.240
[Guest]: coming on sabbatical, like, you know, they'll be there. And I will, you know, be back for

04:46:42.240 --> 04:46:45.880
[Guest]: 10 weeks a year and do my teaching in the US. So you know, so that way, I'm still a

04:46:45.880 --> 04:46:50.800
[Guest]: UCSD professor, that's kind of my main job. But the big thing I'll be doing in India,

04:46:50.800 --> 04:46:54.080
[Guest]: in addition to kind of, you know, not just hopefully finishing the book and getting it

04:46:54.080 --> 04:46:59.440
[Guest]: out, but doing a lot more dissemination work of getting the ideas out in a much more, you

04:46:59.440 --> 04:47:02.840
[Guest]: know, accessible way, right? I mean, spending time in Indian universities, giving talks,

04:47:02.840 --> 04:47:07.520
[Guest]: doing stuff like that. But also, it's really building out CEGIS, right? Because CEGIS is

04:47:07.520 --> 04:47:11.920
[Guest]: now, you know, like, that's the skin in the game. That's the walk the talk kind of piece

04:47:11.920 --> 04:47:15.840
[Guest]: of this whole enterprise, right? I mean, which is, it's one thing to have a bunch of ideas,

04:47:15.840 --> 04:47:19.920
[Guest]: but you really and, and I don't have money, what I have is time, right? So the way I put

04:47:19.920 --> 04:47:24.800
[Guest]: skin in the game is committing my time to things that I think are truly important. And,

04:47:24.800 --> 04:47:28.120
[Guest]: you know, this, I can say a little bit more about CEGIS now, right, which is the Centre

04:47:28.120 --> 04:47:31.960
[Guest]: for Effective Governance of Indian States. You know, we're a nonprofit that works with

04:47:31.960 --> 04:47:35.440
[Guest]: state governments, usually in partnership in the finance departments, right, mean to

04:47:35.440 --> 04:47:40.920
[Guest]: just try and slowly, right, very, very gently, start implementing some of these principles

04:47:40.920 --> 04:47:46.160
[Guest]: in areas of kind of low hanging fruit. And the key USPs, you know, because there's both

04:47:46.160 --> 04:47:50.000
[Guest]: intellectual and conceptual clarity, and therefore a certain credibility with the government

04:47:50.000 --> 04:47:55.520
[Guest]: and being a nonprofit allows us to, you know, I think, unlike a consultant, I mean, consulting

04:47:55.520 --> 04:47:59.520
[Guest]: firms are constantly dependent on government contracts. So you have two problems there,

04:47:59.520 --> 04:48:03.040
[Guest]: right? Beyond the confidence and confidence intervals quip I made, like, you know, it's

04:48:03.040 --> 04:48:08.680
[Guest]: that. So one is, because you are a paid vendor, right? I mean, you only execute what you're

04:48:08.680 --> 04:48:13.520
[Guest]: told in a very tactical way, right? But you don't kind of actually take on a broader thing

04:48:13.520 --> 04:48:19.200
[Guest]: of what should be done. And the second problem is, again, yeah, because the, the consultants

04:48:19.200 --> 04:48:22.680
[Guest]: in some case, in some ways, are not interested in state capacity, right? They want state

04:48:22.680 --> 04:48:25.760
[Guest]: dependency, because that's what creates the contracts, right? That's kind of what you're

04:48:25.760 --> 04:48:30.320
[Guest]: interested in. And because, you know, we're coming in as a nonprofit with a deep commitment

04:48:30.320 --> 04:48:35.680
[Guest]: to improving state capacity. So for example, in Telangana, which is where we started work,

04:48:35.680 --> 04:48:40.760
[Guest]: and mainly because a lot of this just requires trust, right? I mean, and so the current principal

04:48:40.760 --> 04:48:44.320
[Guest]: secretary of finance, you know, was commissioned in school education in 2004, when I first

04:48:44.320 --> 04:48:48.000
[Guest]: started working in the state, right? So they know that there's a long term commitment when

04:48:48.000 --> 04:48:52.040
[Guest]: I'm there, right? And so but one of the things we've done there is that the government has

04:48:52.040 --> 04:48:55.880
[Guest]: seconded a bunch of its own staff to this unit, so that they are getting trained in

04:48:55.880 --> 04:49:00.340
[Guest]: the data analysis in the ways we're doing things. And so, yeah, so that's kind of building

04:49:00.340 --> 04:49:04.000
[Guest]: up in a big way, we added, we've added one state a year, right? It was Telangana, then

04:49:04.000 --> 04:49:08.400
[Guest]: Delhi, then Tamil Nadu, Assam, and there's demand now from three or four other states.

04:49:08.400 --> 04:49:12.640
[Guest]: So I think the biggest thing I'm going to be doing is really, you know, this Vijayan

04:49:12.640 --> 04:49:17.920
[Guest]: team are building the org, but I will function more in the realm of ideas of saying, you

04:49:17.920 --> 04:49:21.760
[Guest]: know, here is what we need to do, how do we build kind of the broader understanding of

04:49:21.760 --> 04:49:26.560
[Guest]: what needs to happen. So that's the hope, you know, so and then at a personal level,

04:49:26.560 --> 04:49:29.280
[Guest]: like I said, normally, I come to India every three months in the pandemic, I've come only

04:49:29.280 --> 04:49:33.160
[Guest]: twice in two and a half years. So I just want to go back to the field, I just want to reconnect,

04:49:33.160 --> 04:49:36.640
[Guest]: I want to be in the field, going back to schools, going back to clinics, going back to panchayat

04:49:36.640 --> 04:49:40.760
[Guest]: secretaries and just, you know, just really, really reconnecting. And that's what I'm hoping

04:49:40.760 --> 04:49:41.760
[Amit Varma]: to do.

04:49:41.760 --> 04:49:47.880
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic. More power to you. And, and one suggestion regarding sort of the writing you

04:49:47.880 --> 04:49:51.880
[Amit Varma]: do moving forward is that why don't you start a newsletter, you know, where you write every

04:49:51.880 --> 04:49:57.120
[Amit Varma]: week and I'm serious, it doesn't have to be about ideas or research or study, just start

04:49:57.120 --> 04:50:00.760
[Amit Varma]: something personal where you talk about how your week was, something interesting you read,

04:50:00.760 --> 04:50:05.120
[Amit Varma]: something interesting you did. And, and since I'm saying this, sort of on a forum where

04:50:05.120 --> 04:50:09.760
[Amit Varma]: others can hear this advice that I'm giving to you, I actually give this advice to everyone,

04:50:09.760 --> 04:50:14.120
[Amit Varma]: I think, for most people, it's a good idea, because it's a good way to always be thinking

04:50:14.120 --> 04:50:17.720
[Amit Varma]: about stuff, getting their mind working, moving the writing muscle, you don't, of course need

04:50:17.720 --> 04:50:22.880
[Amit Varma]: those things, because you do think about stuff enough and write enough. But, you know, just

04:50:22.880 --> 04:50:28.480
[Amit Varma]: as a way of writing, sort of a way of thinking aloud, like one of the fascinating things

04:50:28.480 --> 04:50:32.680
[Amit Varma]: that I find about Twitter is that if you curate your feed properly, you get access to some

04:50:32.680 --> 04:50:36.280
[Amit Varma]: of the brightest minds in the world thinking aloud for your benefit, what a privilege that

04:50:36.280 --> 04:50:43.000
[Amit Varma]: is. And if someone like you writes a newsletter as well, you know, other people get that insight,

04:50:43.000 --> 04:50:46.760
[Amit Varma]: they get to know the person, they become more receptive to the ideas, therefore, you're

04:50:46.760 --> 04:50:49.880
[Amit Varma]: going on a journey, you're taking them with you, you know, maybe they would have been

04:50:49.880 --> 04:50:55.520
[Amit Varma]: with you on your 14 year journey of writing these papers. So a serious suggestion I'd

04:50:55.520 --> 04:51:00.460
[Amit Varma]: give which you can think about. And meanwhile, you know, the, you know, the mandatory sort

04:51:00.460 --> 04:51:06.400
[Amit Varma]: of last question, would you like to recommend, you know, books, films, music, which you haven't

04:51:06.400 --> 04:51:09.720
[Amit Varma]: recommended before, because I've completely forgotten if I asked you this in previous

04:51:09.720 --> 04:51:13.880
[Amit Varma]: episodes, and you recommended stuff. But whatever is top of the mind these days, what are you

04:51:13.880 --> 04:51:16.400
[Amit Varma]: enjoying? You know, what gives you joy?

04:51:16.400 --> 04:51:21.580
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, and again, I think what I said last time was that I'm listening to podcasts

04:51:21.580 --> 04:51:26.760
[Guest]: much more than reading books. And so I, you know, there's, there's a whole new list of

04:51:26.760 --> 04:51:30.960
[Guest]: your favorite episodes, you know, I think, which I just really enjoyed so much, I think.

04:51:30.960 --> 04:51:34.880
[Guest]: And particularly, I think you've been doing a great job of, you know, of just having more

04:51:34.880 --> 04:51:38.800
[Guest]: women on the show. And I've just loved, you know, whether it's Shrayana, whether it's

04:51:38.800 --> 04:51:44.440
[Guest]: Neelanjana, whether it's Nirupam Rao, who I know, Urvashi, you know, so all of these

04:51:44.440 --> 04:51:48.680
[Guest]: have been great episodes. I've loved, I think the Sneaky Artist one, the one with Mrinal

04:51:48.680 --> 04:51:52.480
[Guest]: Pandey was great. I've just loved so many of these episodes, right? Because I just walk

04:51:52.480 --> 04:51:57.160
[Guest]: and listen. And it's been fun, because like I said, I connect the dots. I'm sometimes

04:51:57.160 --> 04:52:00.720
[Guest]: learning new things. There's just so much from new perspectives. For example, you know,

04:52:00.720 --> 04:52:06.840
[Guest]: I think the the more artistic people, right, who you talk to, who I think clearly, at one

04:52:06.840 --> 04:52:15.240
[Guest]: level are very suspicious of, you know, markets and efficiency and commoditization and scale,

04:52:15.240 --> 04:52:19.080
[Guest]: you know, I think the episode with Anupurna was great, right? Like, you know, about just

04:52:19.080 --> 04:52:24.200
[Guest]: the making those Japanese, right? Because it's all, it is not about scale, it is not

04:52:24.200 --> 04:52:28.520
[Guest]: about cost effectiveness, it is not about, it is about kind of, you know, that intrinsic

04:52:28.520 --> 04:52:34.520
[Guest]: beauty and the slowness is part of what it's about, right? I mean, so I think it's just

04:52:34.520 --> 04:52:39.000
[Guest]: coming from kind of a productivity paradigm, right? I mean, the way I do, I think kind

04:52:39.000 --> 04:52:43.080
[Guest]: of just hearing those has just been, you know, it's not like I don't have that part of me

04:52:43.080 --> 04:52:47.720
[Guest]: with my love of music and all of that stuff. But it's just very nice to just hear those

04:52:47.720 --> 04:52:51.400
[Guest]: pieces, right? So yeah, I think in terms of books, you know, more recently, I think in

04:52:51.400 --> 04:52:55.800
[Guest]: the context of federalism, in fact, I mean, the one thing again, which I thought you would

04:52:55.800 --> 04:52:59.240
[Guest]: ask, which I did want to cover a little bit, right? I mean, is as we think about India

04:52:59.240 --> 04:53:02.640
[Guest]: at 75, you know, you, you ask the hope and despair type question, you know, the things

04:53:02.640 --> 04:53:05.240
[Guest]: about, so there are some things I am, you know, there's one thing I'm very concerned

04:53:05.240 --> 04:53:09.760
[Guest]: about, which I do want to talk about. But in thinking about federalism, I actually there's

04:53:09.760 --> 04:53:13.720
[Guest]: this little volume by Madhav Khosla that he puts together, like, you know, letters to

04:53:13.720 --> 04:53:18.360
[Guest]: chief ministers, where it was just mind blowing to me that Jawaharlal Nehru used to write

04:53:18.360 --> 04:53:24.760
[Guest]: letters every 15 days to every chief minister, okay, and he did this for pretty much 14-15

04:53:24.760 --> 04:53:29.280
[Guest]: years. And like Madhav says, you know, I think the value of those letters is that when you

04:53:29.280 --> 04:53:34.040
[Guest]: read Nehru's books, they're all pre-independent. So they're really more as political activists,

04:53:34.040 --> 04:53:38.040
[Guest]: as opposed to kind of taking, so like they say, right, you campaign in poetry and govern

04:53:38.040 --> 04:53:43.840
[Guest]: in prose, right? I mean, so kind of taking the grand lofty ideas of the, you know, of

04:53:43.840 --> 04:53:47.960
[Guest]: the idealist into the practical realities of running the government and seeing that

04:53:47.960 --> 04:53:51.720
[Guest]: discourse with the chief ministers. I mean, I just think it was, yeah, it's just wonderful

04:53:51.720 --> 04:53:55.720
[Guest]: in terms of what it shows about thoughtfulness, about inclusiveness, going back to what you

04:53:55.720 --> 04:53:58.480
[Guest]: were saying about, you know, writing every week. I mean, I never thought about that.

04:53:58.480 --> 04:54:02.920
[Guest]: But you know, I say I don't have the time, but here was a prime minister making time

04:54:02.920 --> 04:54:06.920
[Guest]: to do that kind of writing, I mean, every 15 days, and it suggests that how important

04:54:06.920 --> 04:54:11.760
[Guest]: it was, partly as an act of self-reflection, partly as an act of communication. And I think

04:54:11.760 --> 04:54:15.640
[Guest]: the reason I want to call attention to that is going back to something else you said about

04:54:15.640 --> 04:54:20.040
[Guest]: kind of how our public space for dialogues and difficult conversations seems to have

04:54:20.040 --> 04:54:24.480
[Guest]: kind of shrunk, right? I mean, where people are talking past each other, you know, there's

04:54:24.480 --> 04:54:29.280
[Guest]: posturing, there's extremities, and how do you kind of find the middle? So I found that

04:54:29.280 --> 04:54:33.080
[Guest]: quite nice. There's this other recent book, which I don't know if it's out yet, but I

04:54:33.080 --> 04:54:36.880
[Guest]: got a pre-copy from my friend Rahul Sagar, who's got, you know, two books. One is on

04:54:36.880 --> 04:54:40.520
[Guest]: Indian foreign policy and intellectual thought in the 19th century. The other one is called

04:54:40.520 --> 04:54:48.040
[Guest]: The Progressive Maharaja, which I think, so it's an incredible piece of historical detective

04:54:48.040 --> 04:54:54.160
[Guest]: work. And it's based on, you know, Sir Madhava Rao, who was the Diwan of Travancore, and

04:54:54.160 --> 04:54:59.560
[Guest]: then the Diwan of Baroda. And it's a set of lessons in governance and statecraft, right,

04:54:59.560 --> 04:55:04.160
[Guest]: and that he had put together for the young prince. And so what is great about it is it's

04:55:04.160 --> 04:55:09.960
[Guest]: kind of, you know, it's both deeply Indian, but also Western, and it reflects kind of,

04:55:09.960 --> 04:55:15.280
[Guest]: you know, what I hope an India will be, which is both kind of confident in what we are,

04:55:15.280 --> 04:55:19.840
[Guest]: but open to the best from around the world, right? I mean, and so I think that book is,

04:55:19.840 --> 04:55:24.720
[Guest]: yeah, I mean, and also, it kind of resonated with what I'm trying to do right now, which

04:55:24.720 --> 04:55:28.400
[Guest]: is really, I guess, write a modern book on statecraft in some ways, but more internally

04:55:28.400 --> 04:55:31.880
[Guest]: facing as opposed to aspects of externally facing. So yeah, I mean, these are a couple

04:55:31.880 --> 04:55:33.880
[Guest]: of recent books, which I've liked a lot.

04:55:33.880 --> 04:55:39.640
[Amit Varma]: Wow, thanks a lot. And so I'll ask the hope this were a question since you prepared for

04:55:39.640 --> 04:55:40.640
[Amit Varma]: it, or have you already given the answer?

04:55:40.640 --> 04:55:45.080
[Guest]: No, no, it was not even prepared, you know, I mean, I think basically, I think, see, as

04:55:45.080 --> 04:55:50.760
[Guest]: we take stock about India 75, I mean, I think the thing, you know, the thing I do want to

04:55:50.760 --> 04:55:54.440
[Guest]: reflect on, and you've said a couple of times, it's not even about preparing, it was more

04:55:54.440 --> 04:55:58.680
[Guest]: connecting thoughts based on things you've said, about, you know, what keeps the country

04:55:58.680 --> 04:56:02.760
[Guest]: together, right? I mean, what keeps the country together? And are there things that we are

04:56:02.760 --> 04:56:06.480
[Guest]: taking for granted? Are there fault lines that we need to be careful about that we need

04:56:06.480 --> 04:56:12.880
[Guest]: to kind of do purposeful, deliberative thinking about these fault lines without assuming them

04:56:12.880 --> 04:56:17.680
[Guest]: away? Okay, so because these are very complex issues that are coming down the turnpike,

04:56:17.680 --> 04:56:23.800
[Guest]: okay. So I think the larger question about what keeps India together, I think, you know,

04:56:23.800 --> 04:56:28.000
[Guest]: does justice to that. And there are themes of that in many of your episodes, right, including

04:56:28.000 --> 04:56:32.680
[Guest]: Chinmayon migration, right? I mean, just that sheer amount of internal migration connection,

04:56:32.680 --> 04:56:35.880
[Guest]: you know, keeps everything together, which is wonderful. I think there's something else,

04:56:35.880 --> 04:56:41.160
[Guest]: which I don't know if it's been in an episode, but which I think is worth, and this is interesting,

04:56:41.160 --> 04:56:46.080
[Guest]: right? Because Ram, the book is masterful, that last chapter on kind of why India survives

04:56:46.080 --> 04:56:49.680
[Guest]: is masterful. But you know, it actually does have a bit of a blind spot, which I think

04:56:49.680 --> 04:56:53.920
[Guest]: speaks to some of the broader fault lines we face as a country right now, which is, it completely

04:56:53.920 --> 04:56:58.440
[Guest]: ignores the, you know, so he does talk about religion, but says religion is not what unifies

04:56:58.440 --> 04:57:02.560
[Guest]: the country, because we're not a religious state, which is true. But there is also a

04:57:02.560 --> 04:57:07.240
[Guest]: level where there is a cultural component of travel and pilgrimage, say, right? Like,

04:57:07.240 --> 04:57:10.720
[Guest]: you know, I mean, that people just travel around the country. And one of the book references,

04:57:10.720 --> 04:57:14.840
[Guest]: in fact, which many of you readers may not have seen, is this wonderful book by Diana

04:57:14.840 --> 04:57:18.120
[Guest]: Eck, who's a professor of religion, Indian religion at Harvard, right, like, you know,

04:57:18.120 --> 04:57:22.200
[Guest]: called India's Sacred Geography. And she's got this lovely phrase there about saying

04:57:22.200 --> 04:57:26.440
[Guest]: that this is not a country unified by the power of kings and princes, but by the footsteps

04:57:26.440 --> 04:57:32.080
[Guest]: of its pilgrims, right? And, you know, so and growing up in Ahmedabad, I know how, for

04:57:32.080 --> 04:57:36.240
[Guest]: example, my South Indian relatives would come and go to Dwarka and go to Somnath, and that

04:57:36.240 --> 04:57:39.320
[Guest]: was an important part of coming to Gujarat, you know, whether it's going to Kashi, whether

04:57:39.320 --> 04:57:43.080
[Guest]: it's going to Rameshwaram. So I think, you know, that's there. And so, but the reason

04:57:43.080 --> 04:57:46.840
[Guest]: I'm saying all of this is that we have going back to federalism and going back to the optimal

04:57:46.840 --> 04:57:51.160
[Guest]: size of countries and going back to what keeps India together. I think that there are many,

04:57:51.160 --> 04:57:55.960
[Guest]: many, many layers, right? So there is a modern, there are traditional reasons for why we are

04:57:55.960 --> 04:58:01.120
[Guest]: together, including, say, things like pilgrimage, the reasons like migration, reasons like the

04:58:01.120 --> 04:58:05.200
[Guest]: modern institutions, whether it's the civil service. So all of these things have kind

04:58:05.200 --> 04:58:11.280
[Guest]: of played their own role in stitching together, right? The miracle that is India, okay? But

04:58:11.280 --> 04:58:15.200
[Guest]: we can't take it for granted. We can't take it for granted. And, you know, for example,

04:58:15.200 --> 04:58:18.600
[Guest]: there used to be this thing called National Integration Council, okay? And part of their

04:58:18.600 --> 04:58:24.360
[Guest]: job was precisely to constantly think about, you know, identifying and preempting fault

04:58:24.360 --> 04:58:29.080
[Guest]: lines, right? I mean, through kind of proactive action. So I think, as I think about India,

04:58:29.080 --> 04:58:34.880
[Guest]: what worries me the most is kind of the parliamentary delimitation, okay? Like, I mean, that may

04:58:34.880 --> 04:58:39.520
[Guest]: be coming up, right? And so that's the can we've kicked down for 50 years, right? With

04:58:39.520 --> 04:58:43.840
[Guest]: 71, there was a constitutional amendment, and we've frozen the representation at that

04:58:43.840 --> 04:58:50.560
[Guest]: 71 population. But if we were to redo this now, okay, based on population, then effectively,

04:58:50.560 --> 04:58:56.160
[Guest]: you are completely reshaping the political map of the country, right? In terms of the

04:58:56.160 --> 04:58:59.960
[Guest]: population ratios, if you were to keep Kerala as a constant, right? I mean, would have more

04:58:59.960 --> 04:59:04.040
[Guest]: than doubled in UP and Bihar, right? Relative to, and not just the South, but parts of the

04:59:04.040 --> 04:59:08.800
[Guest]: West as well, right? So as we think about the grand federal compromise that's India,

04:59:08.800 --> 04:59:13.180
[Guest]: and you can see why this is such a core tension, right? Because there are democratic reasons

04:59:13.180 --> 04:59:18.360
[Guest]: to say that we need to not veer too far away from one person, one vote, okay? So which

04:59:18.360 --> 04:59:24.120
[Guest]: would say that any delimitation is the right thing to do. But that also goes deeply contra,

04:59:24.120 --> 04:59:29.520
[Guest]: right? Like, I mean, to kind of this federal spirit, and you can see, and because the South

04:59:29.520 --> 04:59:33.440
[Guest]: would then, not just South, but the South and the West, right? I mean, is worse off

04:59:33.440 --> 04:59:38.120
[Guest]: both economically and politically, right? Like, and so how do we navigate this is going

04:59:38.120 --> 04:59:43.720
[Guest]: to require an enormous amount of political and, you know, and imagination to say, here

04:59:43.720 --> 04:59:49.560
[Guest]: are these principles that are in tension with each other. And how do we architect something

04:59:49.560 --> 04:59:55.080
[Guest]: that allows everybody to be better off, right? And but that requires, you know, genuine dialogue,

04:59:55.080 --> 04:59:58.840
[Guest]: it requires creating the space for dialogue. And I don't think it's something that, you

04:59:58.840 --> 05:00:02.280
[Guest]: know, this particular government is incapable of, right? I think Arun Jaitley is, you know,

05:00:02.280 --> 05:00:07.440
[Guest]: he shepherded GST through partly through kind of a consultative temperament that listened

05:00:07.440 --> 05:00:12.120
[Guest]: to everybody, right? Like, I mean, and brought things together. And I do think that this

05:00:12.120 --> 05:00:17.400
[Guest]: is something that we should prepare for, right? I mean, and have either, you know, some body

05:00:17.400 --> 05:00:21.280
[Guest]: of experts, constitutional body, political representation to kind of, you know, so that

05:00:21.280 --> 05:00:26.240
[Guest]: it doesn't hit us out of nowhere. And then because once again, positions get entrenched,

05:00:26.240 --> 05:00:29.920
[Guest]: it'll be very, very difficult, right? Because, you know, if you have people saying, no, one

05:00:29.920 --> 05:00:34.480
[Guest]: person, one vote, we have to do this, or others say, no, we had actually talked about population

05:00:34.480 --> 05:00:37.840
[Guest]: control education as a national goal. And there are states that have met this and states

05:00:37.840 --> 05:00:42.800
[Guest]: that have not. And if you were to follow delimitation, you would completely change the federal contract.

05:00:42.800 --> 05:00:48.400
[Guest]: So that I think is very, very, it's one of the most difficult problems I see coming down

05:00:48.400 --> 05:00:54.000
[Guest]: the turnpike. And, you know, you can't just push it away, right? And so it's going to

05:00:54.000 --> 05:00:59.760
[Guest]: require both political and institutional imagination, right? So there are ways to kind of navigate

05:00:59.760 --> 05:01:05.440
[Guest]: this. You know, one, you might say, listen, we froze things in 2001, and things have turned

05:01:05.440 --> 05:01:09.960
[Guest]: out fine, like, you know, so we can keep that and, you know, things have served us fine.

05:01:09.960 --> 05:01:13.080
[Guest]: The other is to say, we are deviating more and more from the principle of one person,

05:01:13.080 --> 05:01:17.440
[Guest]: one vote. And so you need some modifications. And so then you could have, you could think

05:01:17.440 --> 05:01:22.640
[Guest]: about saying that maybe, right, you know, you think about the two houses of parliament,

05:01:22.640 --> 05:01:26.560
[Guest]: right? I mean, going back to the original purpose of Rajya Sabha as something represented.

05:01:26.560 --> 05:01:30.800
[Guest]: So you're saying, there are maybe the Lok Sabha becomes population proportional, and

05:01:30.800 --> 05:01:34.360
[Guest]: then, but the Rajya Sabha goes to kind of a fixed number per state, or, you know, some

05:01:34.360 --> 05:01:39.760
[Guest]: hybrid so that there is a certain amount of voice that is kind of there for the less popular

05:01:39.760 --> 05:01:45.200
[Guest]: states. Or you could have formulae that look like saying, we will freeze political representation

05:01:45.200 --> 05:01:49.440
[Guest]: the way it is, but on the fiscal side, allow the Finance Commission to start accounting

05:01:49.440 --> 05:01:52.880
[Guest]: for newer populations, right? So anyway, so I'm just putting this out there and saying

05:01:52.880 --> 05:01:57.720
[Guest]: that, you know, India at 75 is an incredible achievement that, you know, we're all proud

05:01:57.720 --> 05:02:03.000
[Guest]: of, that we're all a part of. But I think, I do worry, and this goes back to some of

05:02:03.000 --> 05:02:09.040
[Guest]: your older, you know, earlier questions about that, are we shrinking the public space for

05:02:09.040 --> 05:02:15.540
[Guest]: the difficult conversations about, you know, where we are able to listen, and really come

05:02:15.540 --> 05:02:20.080
[Guest]: up with win-win solutions or solutions that are effectively compromises that represent

05:02:20.080 --> 05:02:24.440
[Guest]: kind of the validity of different people's positions, and how do you come up with something

05:02:24.440 --> 05:02:30.000
[Guest]: like that, right? And so, yeah, so not to be pessimistic, but I'm just saying that we

05:02:30.000 --> 05:02:35.240
[Guest]: cannot take these things for granted. And it does require constant purposeful engagement

05:02:35.240 --> 05:02:39.320
[Guest]: by the citizens and leaders of the country to kind of make sure that we continue to stay

05:02:39.320 --> 05:02:42.480
[Guest]: on track and get to full potential.

05:02:42.480 --> 05:02:45.960
[Amit Varma]: I couldn't agree with you more that we can't take it for granted. And I think sometimes

05:02:45.960 --> 05:02:50.680
[Amit Varma]: the mistake that we make is when we think of India as lines on a map, that these are

05:02:50.680 --> 05:02:55.000
[Amit Varma]: the lines on a map, and, you know, this is what we are. And to me, it's a little bit

05:02:55.000 --> 05:03:00.960
[Amit Varma]: more than that. And it's possibly too nebulous to articulate precisely what my idea of India,

05:03:00.960 --> 05:03:05.840
[Amit Varma]: pompous words, might be. But more and more, I think we can't take it for granted, because

05:03:05.840 --> 05:03:10.720
[Amit Varma]: it is under threat. You know, when I see some of the fault lines in our society exploding

05:03:10.720 --> 05:03:14.880
[Amit Varma]: today, like the anti-Muslim politics of today, for example, it makes me really worried about

05:03:14.880 --> 05:03:19.360
[Amit Varma]: where it could go. And, you know, if the worst case scenarios were to come about, however

05:03:19.360 --> 05:03:24.040
[Amit Varma]: low probability there might be, what is the way out of that? I worry about that as well.

05:03:24.040 --> 05:03:28.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, and even this whole sense of okay, we've reached 75 years as this geographic

05:03:28.920 --> 05:03:35.160
[Amit Varma]: entity and more or less these lines on a map, minor modifications here and there. And China

05:03:35.160 --> 05:03:40.000
[Amit Varma]: has nibbled away a bit of it recently. But this is kind of what we've got. But I think

05:03:40.000 --> 05:03:45.680
[Amit Varma]: it's only been 75 years. That's not very long. Things don't last too long. You know, I think

05:03:45.680 --> 05:03:50.240
[Amit Varma]: what one of the biases we have is we think the present moment is permanent, that everything

05:03:50.240 --> 05:03:55.080
[Amit Varma]: will be as it is today. And that is not really the case. I mean, one way in which it could

05:03:55.080 --> 05:04:00.760
[Amit Varma]: change, which is a positive way is that, you know, technology has this push towards globalization

05:04:00.760 --> 05:04:04.680
[Amit Varma]: where we can all be global citizens. And it doesn't really, you know, nation states become

05:04:04.680 --> 05:04:07.840
[Amit Varma]: more and more irrelevant, they don't die, or they don't vanish or something, they just

05:04:07.840 --> 05:04:12.800
[Amit Varma]: become more irrelevant, because individuals become empowered to join whatever collective

05:04:12.800 --> 05:04:18.440
[Amit Varma]: they feel like in whatever way, even if they pay taxes in a particular geography. But another,

05:04:18.440 --> 05:04:22.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I think about delimitation, for example, I wonder if that can be, you

05:04:22.600 --> 05:04:27.160
[Amit Varma]: know, if not handled properly, can that be something that, you know, provides a trigger

05:04:27.160 --> 05:04:30.840
[Amit Varma]: for the lines on the map changing and not looking the same. And I don't even know if

05:04:30.840 --> 05:04:34.120
[Amit Varma]: that would be a good thing or a bad thing. Like one musing that I think I brought it

05:04:34.120 --> 05:04:37.800
[Amit Varma]: up in my episode with Niranjana, which you mentioned you've heard, is that what if at

05:04:37.800 --> 05:04:42.560
[Amit Varma]: independence we weren't one large country like we are, but a whole bunch of small countries,

05:04:42.560 --> 05:04:47.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, federalism by force, as it were, would it be better? And would it be would

05:04:47.360 --> 05:04:51.360
[Amit Varma]: it be worse? And I can make arguments for either, really. So who knows where things

05:04:51.360 --> 05:04:54.840
[Amit Varma]: are going? I mean, I once you know, when I was a poker player wrote a column called unlikely

05:04:54.840 --> 05:05:00.720
[Amit Varma]: is inevitable, about the law of truly large numbers, which basically states that no matter

05:05:00.720 --> 05:05:06.960
[Amit Varma]: how unlikely something is given a large enough sample size is bound to happen. And I think

05:05:06.960 --> 05:05:11.760
[Amit Varma]: given the sample size of time itself, you know, given the sample size of space, we had

05:05:11.760 --> 05:05:17.600
[Amit Varma]: one tiny planet in, you know, such a large universe, you know, millions of years have

05:05:17.600 --> 05:05:23.540
[Amit Varma]: passed, and we've just, you know, gotten through 75 of those, you know, you cannot take anything

05:05:23.540 --> 05:05:27.080
[Amit Varma]: for granted, and you have to fight for what you believe in, and which is, which is in

05:05:27.080 --> 05:05:31.040
[Guest]: fact what you do. But I want to be more optimistic. And again, going back to one of your episodes,

05:05:31.040 --> 05:05:35.960
[Guest]: I think it was Annapurna, right? I think in the end, there was this thing about knowledge

05:05:35.960 --> 05:05:39.320
[Guest]: and love. And she talked about, you know, loving every part of this country, right?

05:05:39.320 --> 05:05:44.440
[Guest]: I mean, having traveled, you know, having traveled around, right? And so, I do think

05:05:44.440 --> 05:05:48.120
[Guest]: that even though these are lines on a map, that there is something truly special about

05:05:48.120 --> 05:05:52.520
[Guest]: the modern Indian state. And then coming back to refrain that you've had in many episodes,

05:05:52.520 --> 05:05:56.840
[Guest]: right? Which is, was this a liberal constitution, illiberal society? Again, so I think Rahul

05:05:56.840 --> 05:06:00.640
[Guest]: Verma had the best answer to that, right? I mean, which is that, whatever it is, it

05:06:00.640 --> 05:06:05.400
[Guest]: is the only version that could have worked, where essentially the core idea of the Indian

05:06:05.400 --> 05:06:11.920
[Guest]: constitution is a constitution that accommodates diversity, right? I mean, and that's why India

05:06:11.920 --> 05:06:16.880
[Guest]: is important, both intrinsically for itself and for the world, right? I mean, it is that

05:06:16.880 --> 05:06:21.400
[Guest]: in a world that, you know, is constantly driven by different kinds of conflict. So, you know,

05:06:21.400 --> 05:06:26.880
[Guest]: even the current government, like, you know, wants India to be, quote, unquote, vishwaguru.

05:06:26.880 --> 05:06:30.960
[Guest]: But that vishwaguruness comes not from proclaim it, but comes from your actions, right? I

05:06:30.960 --> 05:06:36.560
[Guest]: mean, and the actions of kind of building a modern polity, right, that can accommodate

05:06:36.560 --> 05:06:42.080
[Guest]: this kind of diversity in an inclusive, pluralistic way, while kind of building the foundations

05:06:42.080 --> 05:06:48.520
[Guest]: of economic growth and prosperity, and also kind of, you know, building an agenda of empowerment

05:06:48.520 --> 05:06:52.280
[Guest]: of the most marginalized, which again, we've never succeeded as close to our aspirations,

05:06:52.280 --> 05:06:56.000
[Guest]: but those aspirations are there, right? So, I think, you know, and I end my book partly

05:06:56.000 --> 05:06:59.160
[Guest]: with kind of saying, strengthening India, leading the world, right? Like, I mean, which

05:06:59.160 --> 05:07:06.040
[Guest]: is, in the end, the idea of India needs to be something that is sustained by its attractiveness,

05:07:06.040 --> 05:07:11.200
[Guest]: as opposed to by its force, right? So, and coming back to another episode where Pramit,

05:07:11.200 --> 05:07:15.480
[Guest]: I think, talked about when he was a student in Assam, that he would face these kind of,

05:07:15.480 --> 05:07:19.000
[Guest]: you know, there would be the separatist kind of sympathies, right, among the youth, among

05:07:19.000 --> 05:07:22.960
[Guest]: students, whatever, and now as he grew older, he's like, listen, I would still much, much,

05:07:22.960 --> 05:07:26.600
[Guest]: much rather be in India than China, which is the counterfactual, right? Like, I mean,

05:07:26.600 --> 05:07:32.720
[Guest]: and so, essentially, the power of the idea of India is just the, this unique experiment

05:07:32.720 --> 05:07:37.160
[Guest]: in human history that has accommodated this kind of diversity, right? I mean, and created

05:07:37.160 --> 05:07:42.240
[Guest]: that space for flourishing every kind of diversity. So, and that's why I think it's important

05:07:42.240 --> 05:07:46.960
[Guest]: that we survive and we flourish and we do all these things, not just for us, but also

05:07:46.960 --> 05:07:51.320
[Guest]: for the world. But I think as we go back and read some of these early documents of the

05:07:51.320 --> 05:07:56.600
[Guest]: founders of these letters, you know, and I think Rahul, again, is an old friend, right?

05:07:56.600 --> 05:08:01.200
[Guest]: I mean, part of his rediscovery, for example, of Indian public life was that of all these

05:08:01.200 --> 05:08:06.040
[Guest]: periodicals and the incredibly active intellectual life of pre-independence India, where people

05:08:06.040 --> 05:08:10.520
[Guest]: were writing and writing and periodicals and rebutting and going back and forth, you know,

05:08:10.520 --> 05:08:13.920
[Guest]: that we, and that's why I think, again, not to flatter you, right? Like, you know, but

05:08:13.920 --> 05:08:18.560
[Guest]: what makes, I think, the podcast then an important space is that we simply do not have the space

05:08:18.560 --> 05:08:23.280
[Guest]: in our public discourse, right? For these long, deep conversations that are, you know,

05:08:23.280 --> 05:08:26.400
[Guest]: measured respectful engagement. Now, of course, they're all bilateral, but eventually, like,

05:08:26.400 --> 05:08:29.440
[Guest]: you know, maybe there are fora and things that we can create that can do these things.

05:08:29.440 --> 05:08:33.400
[Guest]: So thank you for doing your bit. And we shall stay optimistic about, you know, where this

05:08:33.400 --> 05:08:34.880
[Guest]: great country goes next 25 years.

05:08:34.880 --> 05:08:38.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I should point out to the Rahul Sagar book you're referring to, I think it's

